n:** There are no discernible Financial, Operational, or Compliance obligations or specific penalty clauses in this chunk.\n4.  **Operational Risk:** If this chunk represents a required technical format for submission or a data schema for a project, the lack of a legend or decoding key represents a significant barrier to compliance.\n\n**Action Required for Bidder:**\nThe bidder should immediately issue a **Request for Information (RFI)** or a formal clarification request to the issuing agency to provide a legible, plain-text version of \"Page 68\" and its preceding sections." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Security & Access Control:** The bidder is implicitly required to adhere to strict airport security protocols (likely referencing the \"Victoria Airport Authority\" security mandates).\n*   **Safety Standards:** Compliance with federal and provincial aviation safety regulations is mandatory for all on-site activities.\n*   **Maintenance:** (Based on the contextual metadata) The winning bidder must maintain the leased or contracted area to \"first-class\" standards common in international airports.\n\n**Timeline:**\n*   This specific chunk functions as a data/page marker (Page 69), suggesting it is part of the \"General Terms and Conditions\" or \"Technical Specifications\" follow-up.\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Late Performance/Liquidated Damages:** While the provided chunk contains encoded data, the standard VAA RFP terms (referenced in the \"13/3/26\" strings) typically include a **$500 - $1,000 per day liquidated damages clause** for failure to meet operational commencement dates.\n*   **Default/Termination:** Non-compliance with safety or security regulations constitutes a material breach, allowing the Authority to terminate the contract with **30 days' notice** or immediately in the event of a critical security threat.\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Indemnification:** The bidder must indemnify the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) against all claims resulting from the bidder’s negligence, including legal costs on a solicitor-and-client basis.\n*   **Insurance Liability:** Obligation to maintain Comprehensive General Liability (CGL) insurance, typically at a minimum of **$5,000,000 to $10,000,000 per occurrence**, naming the VAA as an additional insured.\n*   **Environmental Liability:** Risk associated with hazardous materials or spills on airport property; strict liability for cleanup costs under provincial environmental law is shifted to the bidder." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Management Fee (Section 2.1.1):** The Contractor shall accept a fixed Management Fee (paid monthly) as full compensation for the Work.\n*   **Labour Costs (Section 2.1.2):** The Contractor is solely responsible for all costs associated with unionization or collective bargaining; the VAA will not increase the Management Fee to cover such costs.\n*   **GST Handling (Section 2.2.2):** The Contractor must include its GST Registration Number on all invoices and is responsible for remitting GST to Revenue Canada.\n*   **Revenue Collection & Remittance (Schedule A - Definition of \"Gross Revenue\"):** The Contractor must collect all monies from the operation of parking facilities. While they may deduct standard Credit Card Processing Fees, they are responsible for accounting for all revenue, including amounts lost to theft or defalcation.\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Performance Standard (Section 4.1):** The Contractor must perform work with \"due care, skill, diligence and efficiency\" and in a \"workmanlike manner.\"\n*   **Staffing (Section 4.3):** The Contractor must ensure all personnel have the necessary qualifications, knowledge, and skill.\n*   **Curb Management (Schedule A):** Obligation to provide trained Curbside Management Officers (CMOs) to monitor and manage vehicle flow at the terminal frontage and commercial lanes.\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Financial Statements (Schedule A):** The Contractor is required to provide:\n    *   Weekly Statement of Revenue.\n    *   Monthly Statement of Account.\n    *   Annual Gross Revenue Statement.\n\n**Timeline:**\n*   **Term (Section 5.1):** Five-year initial term beginning June 1, 2025, through May 31, 2030.\n*   **Renewal Notice (Section 5.2):** If VAA desires a renewal, notice will be given by December 1, 2029.\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Non-Accounted Increases (Section 2.1.2):** If the Contractor’s staff organizes a union, the Contractor is prohibited from seeking an increase in the Management Fee to offset any resulting labor cost increases.\n*   **Theft/Defalcation Liability (Schedule A - \"Gross Revenue\" b):** The Contractor is held financially responsible for \"all amounts that are lost due to theft or defalcation.\" These must be accounted for as Gross Revenue (effectively requiring the Contractor to reimburse VAA for stolen funds).\n*   **Satisfaction Clause (Section 4.1):** Work must be performed to the \"full satisfaction of the VAA,\" implying that failure to meet VAA's internal standards constitutes a breach of performance.\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Labour Risk (Section 2.1.2):** The Contractor bears 100% of the financial risk associated with labor disputes or unionization during the 5-to-7-year term. Since the Management Fee is fixed, any spike in labor costs directly erodes the Contractor’s profit margin.\n*   **Revenue Security Risk (Schedule A):** By including \"amounts lost due to theft\" in the definition of Gross Revenue, the Contractor acts as an insurer for the VAA against any criminal activity or internal employee theft regarding parking receipts.\n*   **Fixed Pricing Risk (Section 2.1.1):** There are no mentioned escalators for inflation over the 5-year term; the Contractor must forecast operational costs (supplies, wages, overhead) accurately through 2030.\n*   **Regulatory Compliance (Schedule A - Definition of \"Head Lease\"):** The contract is subject to the Head Lease with the Crown (Ministry of Transport), meaning the Contractor may be subject to secondary federal requirements not explicitly detailed in the provincial-level management contract." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Revenue Collection & Management:** Collect all \"Monies\" (cash, credit, debit, etc.) from parking operations (Definitions). Specifically manage invoicing, billing, and collection for Air Terminal Employee, Commuter, and Monthly Public Parking programs [1.1.1 (d), (e)].\n*   **Revenue Controls:** Establish and operate processes/controls specifically for the collection, documentation, and reporting of cash payments [1.1.1 (k)].\n*   **Sales Taxes:** Collect and account for provincial or federal sales taxes at the retailer level (Definitions: \"Sales Taxes\").\n*   **Supplies:** Provide all consumables, stationery, cleaning supplies, and non-parking equipment required for daily operations [1.1.1 (c)].\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Staffing:** Provide a Lot Attendant for equipment assistance, cashiering, and dispute resolution [1.1.1 (f)]. Provide staffing for the \"Shared Use Curb\" management [1.1.1 (j)].\n*   **Maintenance:** Daily litter pickup to keep facilities clean/neat [1.1.1 (h)]. Responsible for snow removal and ice control per the specific \"Ice Control and Snow Removal Map\" [1.1.1 (m)].\n*   **Availability:** Supervisory personnel must be reachable 24/7 and available to attend the Airport for emergencies [1.1.2]. Head office support must be maintained 8:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. PT, Monday–Friday [1.1.3].\n*   **Enforcement:** Establish and enforce parking violation policies, including notices and towing (subject to VAA approval) [1.1.1 (i)].\n\n**Compliance and Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Monthly Statements:** Prepare and submit a \"Monthly Statement of Account\" detailing Gross Revenue and the Management Fee [1.1.1 (l)].\n*   **Monitoring:** Monitor and report Parking Equipment issues and deficiencies in buildings/booths to the VAA [1.1.1 (b), (g)].\n*   **Permit Management:** Manage the issuance and retrieval process for all employee and commuter parking permits [1.1.1 (d)].\n\n**Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **Management Fee Adjustments:** If the Employee Parking Lot is deleted from the contract, proposed fee adjustments must be submitted no less than 30 days prior to the change [1.2.3].\n\n---\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Interest on Arrears:** A high interest rate of **2% per month, compounded monthly (26.824% per year)** is applied to \"Interest\" (Definitions).\n*   **Audit Adjustments:** The definition of \"Understated Gross Revenue\" implies consequences for failing to report full revenue on Monthly or Annual statements, though specific financial penalties for this are likely detailed in the referenced Schedule C (not fully provided in this chunk).\n*   **Dispute Resolution:** Failure to agree on fee adjustments following scope changes (like the removal of the Employee Parking Lot) triggers mandatory dispute resolution under Schedule ‘E’ [1.2.3].\n\n---\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Understated Gross Revenue:** The contractor carries the risk and liability for any revenue not properly reported on accounting statements (Definitions).\n*   **Unilateral Scope Changes:** The VAA reserves the right, at its \"sole discretion,\" to delete the Employee Parking Lot from the contract with only 30 days' notice, which could impact the contractor’s overhead recovery and staffing models [1.2.1, 1.2.2].\n*   **Broad Indemnity:** The definition of \"VAA\" includes a broad \"release, hold harmless, and indemnity\" clause covering VAA directors, officers, employees, and agents (Definitions).\n*   **Operational Liability:** The contractor is responsible for \"Financial Loss\" (Ref: Part 3.3 in TOF) and must maintain 24/7 emergency response capability, which represents a significant operational cost and liability risk [1.1.2].\n*   **Maintenance Gaps:** While the contractor is not responsible for repairs to parking equipment, they are liable for \"daily litter pickup\" and \"snow and ice removal,\" which are high-visibility tasks with potential slip-and-fall liability [1.1.1 (h), (m)]." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Marketing Budget:** The Contractor must budget **0.5% of public parking revenues** toward marketing initiatives (Clause 2.1).\n*   **Currency Exchange:** Must accept US currency at an exchange rate that does not differ by more than **two (2) percentage points** from the Royal Bank of Canada \"buy\" rate (Clause 2.2.1).\n*   **Revenue Collection:** Must collect fees from all users (unless waived) and record mail-in payments on the Monthly Statement of Account (Clauses 2.3.1, 2.3.5).\n*   **Property Taxes:** Note that the VAA is responsible for municipal property taxes, not the bidder (Clause 1.5.1).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Staffing Levels (Clause 2.6.3):**\n    *   On-Site Manager: 8 hours/day.\n    *   Lot Attendants: Minimum 20 hours/day (specifically staffing the Lot 1 exit booth).\n    *   Curb Management Officer: Minimum 15.5 hours/day.\n*   **Service Availability:** Must provide staffing sufficient to cover all arriving and departing flights, 24/7, including extending hours for late/early flights (Clauses 2.6.1, 2.6.2).\n*   **Marketing:** Implement a robust plan (pre-paid reservations, internet marketing) in both **English and French** (Clause 2.1).\n*   **Collections Process:** Must send an initial letter within 30 days of non-payment, a second letter after another 30 days, and forward to collections after a final 30 days (Clause 2.3.3).\n*   **Personnel Management:** Maintain a local office presence within one month of commencement; provide VAA-approved uniforms; pay \"competitive\" hourly rates and benefits (Clauses 2.10.1, 2.10.5, 2.10.6).\n\n**Compliance & Reporting:**\n*   **Operational Reports (Clause 2.7.1):** 11 specific report types required at various frequencies (Weekly, Monthly, or Ad Hoc), including Revenue Transactions, Incident Reports, and Snow Removal/Ice Control reports.\n*   **Proposal Adherence:** Must perform every undertaking and representation made in the Contractor’s original RFP Proposal (Clause 1.4.1).\n\n**Timeline:**\n*   **Notice Periods:** 30 days’ notice is required for changes to parking spaces/equipment (Clause 1.3.2) and for proposing Management Fee adjustments (Clause 1.3.3).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Financial Liability for Unpaid Fees:** If the Contractor fails to demonstrate \"reasonable effort\" in collecting unpaid fees (the three-step letter/collection process), the **Contractor assumes direct payment responsibility** for those unpaid fees (Clause 2.3.4).\n*   **Material Breach:** Failure to adhere to the undertakings in the Contractor’s Proposal or subsequent representations constitutes a **material breach**, triggering \"Part 4 of Schedule E – Non-Compliance, Suspension and Termination\" (Clause 1.4.1).\n*   **Personnel Removal:** The VAA has the right to demand the immediate removal of any personnel deemed incompetent or improper (Clause 2.10.8).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Unilateral Modifications (The \"Sole Discretion\" Clause):** The VAA can add or delete parking spaces, areas, or equipment at any time. While the Contractor can request a fee adjustment, if the parties disagree, the **existing Management Fee remains in effect** until dispute resolution is complete (Clauses 1.3.1, 1.3.3).\n*   **Retroactive Fee Adjustments:** While fee resolutions are retroactive, the Contractor may face cash-flow strain during the \"disagreement\" period while managing a changed scope of work at an old rate (Clause 1.3.3).\n*   **Operational Directives:** The VAA can force changes to shift schedules and mandate staffing of Lot 2 during \"peak periods\" at their direction, which may impact labor costs (Clauses 2.6.1, 2.6.4).\n*   **Marketing Approval:** All marketing must be pre-approved; costs incurred for unapproved or non-bilingual materials would likely be the Contractor's loss (Clause 2.1).\n*   **Wage Liability:** The requirement to pay \"competitive\" rates is subjective and could lead to disputes or forced mid-contract wage increases to satisfy VAA's assessment of the market (Clause 2.10.5)." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Trust Handling:** All collected monies are the exclusive property of the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) and must be held in trust (3.1.1).\n*   **Deposit Frequency:** Accumulations must be collected, counted in a secure location, and deposited at least once per week (3.1.2).\n*   **Remittance:** All monies and sales taxes must be forwarded to VAA no later than the 5th business day of the following month (3.1.2).\n*   **Training Costs:** All personnel training is at the Contractor's expense (2.13.1).\n*   **Audit Deficiencies:** Contractor must pay any revenue deficiency found during an independent audit on demand (3.4.3).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Security:** Provide personnel info to VAA for national security reasons and remove personnel if instructed (2.10.9).\n*   **Manuals:** Prepare and maintain an operations and procedures manual for Parking Facilities (2.10.10).\n*   **Supervision:** Maintain a manager/supervisor available on-site or by phone for immediate response/attendance (2.11.3).\n*   **Towing:** Implement VAA towing policies and perform necessary towing (2.12.1).\n*   **Financial Controls:** Maintain segregation of duties (collection vs. deposit vs. reconciliation) (3.2.1a).\n*   **Records Retention:** Maintain accurate records and accounts for at least one year after contract expiration/termination (3.4.1).\n\n**Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Accessibility:** Comply with *Personnel Training Regulations for the Assistance of Persons with Disabilities* (2.13.2).\n*   **Credentials:** All employees must possess and carry a valid Landside ID (LID) (2.13.3).\n*   **Accounting Standards:** Maintain records in accordance with generally accepted Canadian accounting principles (3.4.1).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Customer Complaints:** Develop a written process within 30 days of commencement; maintain a log and provide reports upon request (2.11.1, 2.11.2).\n*   **Training Records:** Keep training programs available for inspection by the CTA, VAA, and public (2.13.1, 2.13.2).\n*   **Monthly Financials:** Email reports by the 5th business day covering revenue, sales taxes, and credit card fees (3.1.3).\n*   **Weekly Statements:** Email statements of revenue by type and lot (3.1.4i).\n*   **Employment Logs:** Monthly list of employees and shift schedules/hours upon request (3.1.4ii, 3.1.4iii).\n\n**Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **30 Days:** Deadline to develop complaint resolution process (2.11.1).\n*   **60 Days:** Deadline for personnel to complete initial sensitivity training (2.13.2).\n*   **5th Business Day:** Deadline for monthly financial reporting and remittance (3.1.2, 3.1.3).\n*   **Monthly:** Frequency for internal audits and employee list submission (3.1.4, 3.2.1c).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Failure to comply with financial control/audit procedures (Clause 3.2) constitutes a breach and may result in termination under **Clause GC 4.2 of Schedule 'E'** (3.2.3).\n*   **Indemnification for Financial Loss:** The Contractor is liable for any loss of monies (accidental, negligent, or deliberate) and must indemnify VAA for damages and legal fees (solicitor and client basis) (**Clause 3.3.1**).\n*   **Dismissal of Personnel:** VAA can require removal of any personnel for national security reasons (**Section 2.10.9**).\n*   **Binding Audit Results:** Results from an independent auditor hired by VAA are \"final and binding,\" requiring immediate repayment of deficiencies (**Clause 3.4.3**).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Towing Liability:** The Contractor assumes full liability and must indemnify VAA for all costs, damages, or suits resulting from towing actions inconsistent with policy or resulting from negligence (2.12.1).\n*   **National Security Compliance:** Total VAA discretion over personnel based on \"national security\" without defined criteria for what constitutes a security risk (2.10.9).\n*   **Broad Audit Rights:** VAA or its independent consultant can audit \"any and all information\" for up to 12 months *after* the contract ends (3.4.2, 3.4.3).\n*   **Trustee Liability:** Because monies are held \"in trust,\" the Contractor faces high fiduciary responsibility; any loss of funds is at the Contractor's entire responsibility, including VAA's legal costs to recover them (3.3.1).\n*   **Scope Creep in Training:** The Contractor must comply with \"future training programs as required by VAA,\" which could introduce unpredictable costs (2.13.4)." "### 1) Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Revenue Remittance:** Contractor must pay all Gross Revenue (less the Contract Price Management Fee) to the VAA by the **5th Business Day** of each month via Electronic Transfer of Funds (ETF) (Clauses 1.2.1, 1.2.2).\n*   **Audit Costs:** If an audit finds revenue understated by **1% or more**, the Contractor must pay the entire expense of the inspection or audit plus Interest (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Revenue Reimbursement:** Any Understated Gross Revenue identified by VAA is immediately due and payable with Interest (Clause 3.4.4).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Facility Maintenance:** Solely responsible for cleaning/maintaining booths/buildings in \"neat and tidy\" condition, including interior/exterior windows and debris/recycling collection (Clause 4.1.3).\n*   **Equipment Maintenance:** Responsible for monitoring, reporting, and maintaining equipment *inside* the booths (excluding SKIDATA equipment) (Clause 4.2.2).\n*   **Inspections:** Must conduct **daily visual inspections** of Parking Equipment and provide immediate notification of problems to the VAA (Clause 4.2.3).\n*   **Vegetation Control:** Responsible for vegetation and weed control on paved surfaces only (Appendix 'A').\n*   **Signage Restriction:** Prohibited from installing any signs or advertising without prior written VAA approval (Clause 4.3.7).\n\n**Reporting/Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Weekly Statements:** Submit a signed \"Weekly Statement of Revenue\" every Friday (commencing June 6, 2025), itemized by revenue type and lot including GST (Clauses 1.3.1.1, 1.3.1.2).\n*   **Monthly Statements:** Submit a \"Monthly Statement of Account\" by the **5th Business Day** of each month (commencing July 7, 2025) (Clause 1.3.2.1).\n*   **Equipment Integrity:** Prohibited from resetting counters on any Parking Equipment unless requested by VAA (Clause 4.2.4).\n\n---\n\n### 2) Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Understated Revenue:** Immediate payment of the deficiency plus Interest from the date of inspection/audit (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Audit Expense Penalty:** If understatement is $\\ge$ 1%, Contractor pays all VAA audit costs plus Interest (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Understated revenue grants VAA the right to terminate the contract under **Clause GC 4.2 of Schedule 'E'** (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Legal Remedies:** VAA reserves the right to seek \"any and all other remedies\" at law for revenue understatements (Clause 3.4.4).\n\n---\n\n### 3) Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Sole Discretion on Revenue:** The VAA determines if revenue is understated \"in its sole discretion acting reasonably,\" putting the burden of proof effectively on the Contractor (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Unlimited Operational Risk:** The Management Fee is considered \"full compensation\" for all work, including compensation for **any loss/damage arising out of the Work, unforeseen obstructions, and \"all risks of every description\"** (Clause 1.1.2). This effectively fixes the Contractor's upside while leaving downside risks open.\n*   **Equipment Monitoring Liability:** While VAA provides equipment, the Contractor is liable for \"monitoring and reporting issues\" (Clause 4.2.2). Failure to report a breakdown \"immediately\" (Clause 4.2.3) could lead to liability for lost revenue.\n*   **Strict Reporting Timelines:** The requirement to submit weekly reports every Friday and monthly payments/reports by the 5th business day leaves very little margin for administrative error." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial & Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Monthly Statements:** Must provide itemized Gross Revenue (by type and lot), Credit Card Processing Fees, Management Fees, and GST/applicable taxes. Must be signed by an authorized officer and include a GST registration number (Clauses 1.3.2.1 – 1.3.2.4).\n*   **Annual Gross Revenue Statement:** Within 90 days of the Contract Year end, provide a statement certified by a Chartered Professional Accountant (CPA) or the CFO (Clause 1.3.3.1).\n*   **Revenue Remittance:**\n    *   If the annual audit shows a shortfall in revenue paid to the VAA, the Contractor must pay the difference \"forthwith\" (Clause 1.3.3.2).\n    *   If there is a dispute regarding revenue remittance, the Contractor **must not** delay or suspend performance of work (Clause 1.3.4.2).\n*   **Contract Security:** Provide an irrevocable, unconditional Letter of Credit (LOC) equal to 5% of the total Management Fee for the Initial Term (Clause 1.1.1).\n*   **Insurance:** Maintain Comprehensive General Liability insurance of at least **$5,000,000.00** per occurrence and Property \"All Risk\" insurance (Clause 2.1.1).\n\n**Compliance & Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **GST Remittance:** Obligation to remit all GST due to Revenue Canada (Clause 1.3.2.4).\n*   **Dispute Response:** If VAA objects to a monthly statement, the Contractor has 30 days to provide written documentation/explanation (Clause 1.3.2.5).\n*   **LOC Renewal:** If a renewal LOC is not provided 3 weeks prior to the expiry of the current one, the VAA can draw the full amount (Clause 1.1.3).\n*   **LOC Restoration:** If the VAA draws on the LOC for a default, the Contractor must restore it to the original amount within 15 days of notice (Clause 1.1.5).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **High Interest on Delinquency:** Late Gross Revenue payments accrue interest at **2% per month (26.824% per year)**, compounded monthly and applied retroactively from the due date (Clause 1.4.1).\n*   **VAA-Initiated Audit Costs:** If the Contractor fails to submit financial statements, VAA may hire auditors to prepare them. The Contractor must reimburse VAA for all audit costs, expenses, plus additional charges for VAA administration and overhead (Clause 1.5.1).\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Failure to provide financial statements constitutes a breach of contract subject to termination under Clause GC 4.2 (Clause 1.5.2).\n*   **Drawing on Security:** VAA may use the Letter of Credit to compensate for any loss, damages, or expenditures resulting from the Contractor's default (Clause 1.1.4).\n*   **Seizure of Security Funds:** Failure to renew the LOC 3 weeks before expiry allows the VAA to withdraw the entire face value and hold it as cash security (Clause 1.1.3).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Onerous Interest Rate:** The interest rate of 26.824% per annum for late payments is significantly higher than standard commercial rates and represents a major financial risk.\n*   **Continuous Performance Clause:** Clause 1.3.4.2 prohibits the Contractor from stopping work even if there is a legitimate financial dispute regarding payments or revenue.\n*   **VAA Audit Discretion:** Acceptance of financial statements does not waive VAA’s right to audit later. VAA has the power to reject statements and trigger an expensive third-party audit process at the Contractor’s sole expense (Clauses 1.3.4.1 and 1.5.1).\n*   **Unconditional LOC:** The LOC is \"unconditional\" and \"irrevocable,\" meaning the VAA can draw upon it by simple written demand without needing to prove a breach to the bank (Clause 1.1.1(d)).\n*   **Insurance Liability:** The VAA may unilaterally require higher insurance limits \"as may be required by the VAA... acting reasonably,\" which could increase premiums mid-contract (Clause 2.1.1(a))." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Insurance Premiums:** Contractor must pay for all required insurance (2.1.6).\n*   **Replacement Cost Coverage:** Property insurance must be for \"full insurable value\" on a replacement cost basis with \"reasonable deductibles\" (Section 2.1.1 a).\n*   **Specific Coverage Limits:**\n    *   **Automobile Liability:** $5,000,000 (Section 2.1.1 b).\n    *   **Crime Coverage:** $10,000 per occurrence for monies held in trust (Section 2.1.1 c).\n    *   **Employee Dishonesty:** $2,000,000 per occurrence (Section 2.1.1 d).\n*   **Assignment/Transfer Costs:** Contractor must pay VAA's solicitor/client costs and an administrative fee for any requested consent to an assignment (GC 1.2.3).\n\n**Operational/Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Licensing:** All insurers must be licensed to underwrite in British Columbia and acceptable to VAA (2.1.2).\n*   **Policy Endorsements:** Policies must be primary/non-contributing, include VAA as an additional insured, include \"severability of interest,\" and be on an \"occurrence form\" basis (2.1.3).\n*   **Subcontracting/Assignment restriction:** Prior written consent from VAA is required for any subcontracting or assignment (GC 1.2.1, 1.2.4). Even shared transfers resulting in a \"change of control\" are deemed assignments (GC 1.2.2).\n*   **Force Majeure Management:** Contractor must take all \"commercially reasonable steps\" to eliminate force majeure causes (GC 1.4.2).\n*   **Official Languages:** Must comply with the *Official Languages Act (Canada)* and associated regulations/VAA policies regarding services to the public (GC 1.5.1).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Certificates of Insurance:** Must provide certificates prior to contract commencement (2.1.4).\n*   **Evidence of Renewal:** Documentary evidence of insurance renewal must be provided prior to the expiry of current policies (2.1.4).\n*   **Policy Copies:** Must provide certified copies of full policies upon VAA request (2.1.5).\n*   **Cancellation Notice:** Insurance must provide 30 days' prior written notice to VAA for cancellation or material change (2.1.3 d).\n\n**Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **Continous Coverage:** Insurance must be maintained continuously during the entire Term (2.1.3).\n*   **Force Majeure Trigger:** VAA can terminate if a force majeure event exceeds 30 days (GC 1.4.3).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Default Status:** Failure to provide, maintain, or pay for insurance constitutes a \"default\" (2.1.6).\n*   **VAA Self-Help Right:** If the contractor fails to maintain insurance, the VAA may purchase insurance on the contractor's behalf and the cost is \"payable by the Contractor to the VAA on demand\" (2.1.6).\n*   **Voiding of Transfers:** Any attempt to assign the contract without prior written consent is \"of no effect\" (GC 1.2.1).\n*   **Termination:** If a force majeure event lasts longer than 30 days, the VAA may terminate without liability (GC 1.4.3).\n*   **Set-off:** VAA has a right of set-off for costs (GC 4.4 - mentioned in Table of Contents).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Unrestricted Liability:** Clause 2.1.8 explicitly states that nothing in the insurance section restricts the liability of the Contractor.\n*   **Indemnity Survival:** The unavailability of insurance does not waive or reduce the Contractor's obligation to indemnify the VAA (2.1.8).\n*   **Broad Assignment Veto:** VAA may \"unreasaonably withhold\" consent for assignment or change of control (GC 1.2.1, 1.2.2).\n*   **Liability for Subcontractors:** No assignment or subcontracting exonerates the Contractor from liability—the Contractor remains fully responsible for the \"due performance\" of the work (GC 1.2.5).\n*   **No Property Rights:** The contract is \"personal\" and grants the contractor no proprietary or property rights (lease/license) in the land or facilities (GC 1.3.1, 1.3.2).\n*   **Limited Force Majeure Protection:** Labor disruptions and strikes are explicitly excluded from force majeure protections (GC 1.4.1)." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Official Languages:** Must provide all printed/written materials (signs, invoices, contracts, etc.) in both official languages (Clause c).\n*   **Bilingual Staffing:** Must maintain sufficient staff on every shift to provide oral responses in both official languages \"within a reasonable period of time\" (Clause d).\n*   **Environmental Compliance:** Must comply with all federal, provincial, municipal, and local environmental laws, bylaws, and regulations (GC 1.6.2).\n*   **Remediation:** Must repair and remediate any \"Adverse Environmental Condition\" at the Contractor's own cost to standards of private commercial lands (GC 1.6.3a).\n*   **Site Exit:** Must leave facilities free of hazardous materials, contaminants, and pollutants upon expiry or termination (GC 1.6.3b).\n*   **Administrative Responsibility:** Solely responsible for statutory deductions (taxes, EI, CPP), Workers' Compensation, insurance premiums, and obtaining all necessary licenses and permits (GC 1.8.2).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Annual Certification:** Upon VAA request (max once per year), provide written assurance/documentation certifying due diligence and compliance with Environmental Requirements (GC 1.6.4a).\n*   **Incident Notification:** Must \"forthwith\" notify the VAA of any non-compliance or event causing an Adverse Environmental Condition and provide a remediation plan (GC 1.6.4b).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **VAA Step-in Rights:** If the Contractor fails to comply with Environmental Requirements, the VAA may perform the work themselves (GC 1.6.6).\n*   **Financial Reimbursement:** All costs incurred by the VAA for performing environmental work are \"forthwith due and payable\" by the Contractor (GC 1.6.6c).\n*   **Deemed Default:** Failure to pay the VAA for remediation costs is explicitly defined as a \"Default\" under the contract (GC 1.6.6).\n*   **Mandatory Investigation:** If the VAA reasonably believes the Contractor is not taking required action, the VAA can force the Contractor to hire an independent consultant at the Contractor's sole expense (GC 1.6.4c).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Strict Environmental Allocation:** The contract explicitly allocates liability to the Contractor under the *Environmental Management Act (British Columbia)*. Substances brought onto the site remain the \"sole and exclusive property\" of the Contractor, making them responsible even if the substance becomes affixed to the land (GC 1.6.5b/d).\n*   **Broad Indemnity:** The Contractor must indemnify the VAA for all costs, claims, or proceedings (civil or criminal) arising from Environmental Liability resulting from the Contractor’s conduct (GC 1.6.5a).\n*   **Survival Clause:** Environmental liabilities and obligations survive the expiry or termination of the contract (GC 1.7).\n*   **Baseline Risk:** Liability is tied to conditions occurring after the 1994/1997 Baseline Study. Any degradation from that state caused by the Contractor's occupancy triggers remediation obligations (GC 1.6.1a).\n*   **Language Compliance Risk:** The requirement for bilingual oral response *during every shift* represents a significant permanent operational staffing cost and recruitment risk." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Personnel**\n*   **Method and Manner:** Contractor is solely responsible for the method and manner of performing the Work (GC 1.8.3).\n*   **Contract Manager Management:** Must designate a Contract Manager within **ten (10) days** of signing or before starting work. Substitution requires prior advice to VAA. Removal and replacement must occur if VAA deems the manager unsuitable (GC 3.1.1–3.1.3).\n*   **Standards of Performance:** Work must be performed in a \"careful and workmanlike manner\" to the \"full and complete satisfaction\" of the VAA (GC 3.2.2).\n*   **Instruction Compliance:** Must promptly follow additional instructions issued by the VAA during performance (GC 2.1.1) and adhere to VAA decisions regarding contract interpretations (GC 2.4.2).\n\n**Compliance & Legal**\n*   **VAA Policies:** Must comply with VAA policies, security measures, safety laws, and environmental regulations (GC 1.8.3a).\n*   **Confidentiality:** Strict maintenance of confidentiality regarding VAA business, inventions, or secure data before, during, and after the contract term (GC 2.2.1).\n*   **Joint and Several Liability:** If the Contractor consists of multiple entities, they are jointly and severally liable (GC 1.10.1).\n\n**Reporting & Notification**\n*   **Labour Disputes:** Immediate notification of any current or threatened labour dispute. A full report is required within **eight (8) hours** of commencement (GC 3.3.2a, c).\n*   **Subcontractor Disclosure:** Must advise VAA in writing of intended subcontractors/suppliers within **ten (10) days** of contract signing (GC 3.4.1).\n\n**Assets & Intellectual Property (IP)**\n*   **Provision of Materials:** Contractor must provide all labor, materials, and services for complete performance (GC 1.9.1). All materials must be new and of merchantable quality (GC 3.2.3).\n*   **Property Return:** All VAA documentation/property must be returned immediately upon request or termination (GC 2.5.1).\n*   **IP Transfer:** Must transfer any produced IP to the VAA and cooperate in its defense/assertion (GC 2.5.3–2.5.4).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Self-Help Remedy (Cost Transfer):** If the Contractor fails to promptly resolve deficiencies or defects identified by VAA, the VAA may fix the problem themselves at the **Contractor’s cost and expense** (GC 2.3.3).\n*   **Contract Suspension/Termination:** If a labour dispute causes an interruption exceeding **seven (7) consecutive days**, VAA may suspend or terminate the contract immediately (GC 3.3.2 - Final Paragraph).\n*   **Forced Personnel Replacement:** VAA has the \"sole opinion\" right to force the replacement of the Contract Manager (GC 3.1.3).\n*   **Non-Waiver:** A waiver of one default does not prevent VAA from enforcing rights on subsequent defaults (GC 1.15.1).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **\"Sole Opinion\" Discretion:** The VAA holds broad discretionary power to determine if work is deficient (GC 2.3.2), if a Contract Manager is unsuitable (GC 3.1.3), or if produced documentation has IP value (GC 2.5.2). This creates risk of subjective enforcement.\n*   **Finality of VAA Decisions:** Questions regarding the Scope of Work or contract requirements are decided by the VAA, whose decision is \"final, binding and conclusive\" (though subject to arbitration) (GC 2.4.1).\n*   **Time of the Essence:** Every reference to time is a \"condition\" of the contract (GC 1.14.1), meaning even minor delays could technically be treated as material breaches.\n*   **Survival of Obligations:** Obligations survive the expiry or termination of the contract, potentially leading to long-term liabilities (GC 1.13.1).\n*   **Work Continuity Requirement:** In the event of labor disputes, the Contractor is obligated to help find and arrange for **substitute parking management providers** to ensure continuity (GC 3.3.2e), which could be operationally and financially burdensome during a strike.\n*   **Warranty Risks:** The Contractor provides an express warranty that all materials are new and fit for purpose, extending liability to the quality of goods used in performance (GC 3.2.3)." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Subcontractor Control:** The Contractor must ensure all subcontractors adhere to all contract obligations \"as if they were the Contractor themselves\" (GC 3.4.4).\n*   **Subcontractor Management:** The Contractor must enter into written contracts with all subcontractors/suppliers, incorporating all terms and conditions of the prime contract (GC 3.4.4 a, b).\n*   **Approval Requirements:** Consent from the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) is required before changing agreed-upon subcontractors or suppliers (GC 3.4.3).\n*   **Warranty Management:** For any parts or materials installed/replaced, the Contractor must obtain warranties in the name of the VAA and submit them to the VAA (GC 3.5.1).\n*   **Non-Interruption:** In the event of a dispute, the Contractor is prohibited from stopping or delaying work (GC 5.1.3).\n*   **Performance Standards:** Must supply \"enough competent personnel or management\" to ensure performance (GC 4.2.2 c).\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Payments:** Must promptly make payments to the VAA as referred to in Schedule 'C' (GC 4.2.1 f).\n*   **Financial Security:** Must provide and maintain a Letter of Credit and specific insurance coverage per Schedule 'D' (GC 4.2.1 g).\n*   **Cost Recovery:** Liability for all VAA costs if the VAA has to step in to perform work the Contractor failed to do (GC 4.1.2).\n\n**Compliance & Reporting:**\n*   **Non-Competition:** The Contractor and its non-arm’s length associates (directors, officers, etc.) are prohibited from operating or advertising any competing airport parking business within a **10-kilometer radius** of the Airport Lands (GC 4.5.2).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **VAA Intervention (Step-in Rights):** If the Contractor fails to comply with a VAA direction, the VAA may perform the work itself at the Contractor's \"cost and expense\" (GC 4.1.1).\n*   **Immediate Termination for Cause:** VAA may terminate \"forthwith without notice\" for insolvency, bankruptcy, failure to make payments, abandonment of work, or breach of a \"fundamental term\" (GC 4.2.1).\n*   **Termination for Unsatisfactory Performance:** Following a notice to remedy, if the Contractor fails to correct defaults (e.g., revenue loss risk, inadequate customer service, or insufficient staffing), the VAA may terminate (GC 4.2.2).\n*   **Financial Damages upon Termination:** The Contractor remains liable for all costs/damages resulting from termination, including the cost of a replacement contractor plus VAA administrative overhead (GC 4.2.3 a).\n*   **Extinguishment of Payments:** Upon termination, the Contractor’s right to any further payment is extinguished (GC 4.2.3 b).\n*   **Right of Set-Off:** The VAA may deduct any sums the Contractor owes from any money the VAA owes to the Contractor (GC 4.4.1).\n*   **Injunctive Relief:** If the non-competition clause is breached, the VAA may apply for an injunction, and the Contractor explicitly consents to such an application (GC 4.5.3, 4.5.4).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Full Vicarious Liability:** The Contractor is \"as fully responsible\" for the acts and omissions of subcontractors as they are for their own employees (GC 3.4.4 c).\n*   **Sole Discretion:** The VAA holds \"sole discretion\" in determining what constitutes a \"fundamental breach\" or \"unsatisfactory\" work, and in setting the timeline for remedying defaults (GC 4.2.1 k, 4.2.2).\n*   **Head Lease Risk:** The contract can be terminated immediately if the Head Lease between the VAA and the Crown is terminated for *any* reason, regardless of the Contractor’s performance (GC 4.2.1 j).\n*   **Arbitration Constraints:** Disputes involving confidentiality, fundamental breaches, or terminations cannot go to arbitration unless both parties agree, potentially forcing the Contractor into more public or expensive court proceedings (GC 5.2.2).\n*   **Restrictive Covenants:** The 10km non-compete radius significantly limits the Contractor’s ability to engage in other regional business opportunities during the term (GC 4.5.2)." "### 1) Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Safety Obligations:**\n*   **Damage Prevention:** Ensure no person, property, right, or easement is injured or infringed upon by Contractor activities (GC 6.1.1.a).\n*   **Hazard Elimination:** Eliminate fire and property damage hazards in/about Parking Facilities (GC 6.1.1.b).\n*   **Health and Safety:** Ensure methods of work do not endanger employees (GC 6.1.1.c).\n*   **Compliance with VAA Direction:** Promptly comply, at own expense, with VAA directions to remedy breaches of safety or damage precautions (GC 6.1.2, GC 6.2.2.a).\n*   **Incident Reporting:** Provide \"immediate written notice\" to VAA regarding any damage to the Airport, VAA property, or customer property, regardless of cause (GC 6.1.3).\n*   **Investigation Requirements:** Conduct immediate investigations into damages, obtain witness statements, employee duty statements, and police/insurer reports (GC 6.1.3).\n*   **Regulatory Compliance:** Fully comply with the *Workers’ Compensation Act* of BC and all Airport rules/operating procedures regarding security, safety, fire, sanitation, and traffic (GC 6.3.1, GC 6.4.1).\n*   **Non-Disparagement:** Refrain from making derogatory or negative comments about the VAA or its representatives (GC 6.5.1).\n\n**Financial & Legal Obligations:**\n*   **Cost Assumption:** Perform all safety and remedial work \"at its own expense\" (GC 6.1.1, GC 6.1.2).\n*   **Claim Responsibility:** Solely responsible for costs of investigation and defense for all claims involving personal injury, property damage, or rights infringement (GC 6.2.1).\n*   **Indemnification:** Indemnify VAA and the Crown for all liabilities, suits, damages, penalties, and fines arising from any act or omission by the Contractor (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Intellectual Property:** Indemnify VAA for any IP infringement claims arising from the performance of Work (GC 7.1.2).\n*   **Defense of VAA:** Defend any suits against the VAA caused by Contractor negligence, pay any resulting judgments/court costs, and pay for VAA’s legal counsel if VAA deems it necessary to hire their own (GC 7.2.1).\n\n### 2) Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Remediation at Contractor Cost:** If the Contractor fails to make good on loss/damage, the VAA may perform the work and charge the Contractor for all costs and expenses (GC 6.2.2.b).\n*   **Workers' Compensation Penalties:** The Contractor must pay all fines and financial assessments resulting from failure to comply with the *Workers’ Compensation Act* and indemnify VAA for the same (GC 6.3.2).\n*   **Contract Termination:** Breach of indemnity obligations does not restrict VAA’s right to terminate the Contract pursuant to GC 4.2 (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Loss of Settlement Authority:** If the Contractor fails to settle a suit within 30 days of notice and VAA believes it harms their reputation, VAA may settle the claim unilaterally and designate the Contractor’s share for immediate reimbursement (GC 7.2.3).\n\n### 3) Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Absolute Liability for Harm:** Contractor is liable for damages caused not just by negligence, but by acts that are \"purely accidental\" or \"deliberate\" (GC 6.2.1, GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Broad Indemnity:** The indemnity covers the \"Crown\" in addition to the VAA, significantly expanding the scope of entities the Contractor must protect (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **No Claim for Suspension:** The Contractor has no right to claim compensation or damages if the VAA deems it necessary to suspend Airport operations (GC 6.6.1.a).\n*   **Limited VAA Liability:** VAA is not liable for costs/damages from service interruptions unless caused by \"gross negligence\" (a high legal bar) (GC 6.6.1.b).\n*   **Theft Liability:** The Contractor bears the risk for theft of its own property AND theft of \"Monies collected... and held in trust for the VAA\" (GC 7.4.1.c, d).\n*   **Unilateral Settlement Power:** VAA reserves the right to settle legal claims at its \"sole discretion\" and force the Contractor to pay if the Contractor doesn't settle within a tight 10-day window following an initial 30-day period (GC 7.2.3).\n*   **Survival of Obligations:** Indemnity obligations survive the termination of the contract (GC 7.1.5)." "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Permits & Licenses:** Obtain all necessary federal, provincial, and municipal licenses, permits, or approvals required for the Work (GC 8.1.1).\n*   **Regulatory Adherence:** Comply with all laws including environmental protection and municipal codes/bylaws regarding health and safety as if the airport were non-federal property (GC 8.1.2).\n*   **Aviation Statutes:** Strictly follow the *Aeronautics Act*, *Canadian Aviation Security Regulations*, and all VAA security measures (GC 9.1.2).\n*   **Security Protocols:** Comply with rules for restricted area passes, escorts, and personnel identification systems (GC 9.1.2).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Signage:** Display all required permits at the Parking Facilities (GC 8.1.3).\n*   **Non-Interruption:** Ensure airport business is not disrupted or impeded (GC 9.1.1a).\n*   **Safety Measures:** Provide temporary protection for pedestrian and vehicle safety (GC 9.1.1b).\n*   **Revenue Handling:** Collect and secure all monies generated from the parking facilities (GC 9.1.1c).\n*   **Reporting:** Contact the YYJ Security Operations Center (SOC) at the start and end of every workday (GC 9.1.1f).\n*   **Key Management:** Safeguard all VAA-issued keys; report loss/theft immediately; return keys upon contract end (GC 9.2.1).\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Correction Costs:** Bear all expenses related to removing electronic interference or hazards to aircraft navigation (GC 9.1.1d).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Remediation at Contractor Expense:** If the contractor causes electronic interference or aircraft hazards, they must remediate the issue \"at its own expense\" immediately (GC 9.1.1d).\n*   **Stringency Clause:** If multiple laws/regulations overlap, the contractor is held to the \"more stringent provision\" (GC 8.1.2).\n*   **Key Controls:** Unauthorized duplication of keys is prohibited; keys are VAA property and must be surrendered upon termination (GC 9.2.1).\n*   *Note: While specific \"liquidated damages\" are not in this chunk, the broad indemnity statement at the beginning suggests the bidder assumes all liability for non-compliance.*\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Indemnification & Release:** The contractor must indemnify and hold harmless the VAA and the Crown, releasing them from any liability regarding the specified matters (Opening paragraph).\n*   **Strict Security Liability:** Operating within an airport environment subjects the contractor to the *Aeronautics Act*. Failure to follow security orders (restricted passes, etc.) could lead to immediate work stoppage or federal penalties (GC 9.1.2).\n*   **Interference Liability:** A significant risk exists if the contractor’s equipment or operations interfere with aircraft navigation. The contractor is liable for the costs of immediate rectification (GC 9.1.1d).\n*   **Hazardous Materials:** The contractor is strictly prohibited from bringing explosives or dangerous goods onto the site without prior written consent (GC 9.1.1e).\n*   **Monetary Security:** The obligation to \"secure all Monies\" places the financial risk of theft or loss of parking revenue directly on the contractor (GC 9.1.1c)."]}, :obligations "### 1. Financial Obligations\n*   **Revenue Remittance:** Must remit all Gross Revenue (less the Management Fee) and sales taxes to the VAA by the **5th business day** of the following month (GC 3.1.2).\n*   **Trust Responsibility:** All collected monies (cash/electronic) are the exclusive property of the VAA and must be held in trust (GC 3.1.1).\n*   **Fixed Fee Risk Management:** The \"Fixed Management Fee\" must cover all costs including snow removal, seasonal shuttles ($0 cost to VAA), and labor cost spikes/unionization (Sec 2.1.1, 2.1.2).\n*   **Security & Insurance:** Provide an Irrevocable Letter of Credit (ILOC) for **5% of the total management fee** (Sec 4) and maintain $5M-$10M in General Liability insurance (Sec 2.1.1).\n*   **Marketing Allocation:** Obligation to budget **0.5% of public parking revenues** toward marketing initiatives (Clause 2.1).\n\n### 2. Operational Obligations\n*   **Availability:** Provide continuous service 24/7, 365 days a year, covering all flight arrivals/departures, including delays (Sec 1.1, 2.6.2).\n*   **Staffing Minima:** Lot 1 booth (20 hrs/day), Curb Management Officer (15.5 hrs/day), and On-Site Manager (8 hrs/day) (Sec 2.6.3).\n*   **Curbside Management:** Develop and execute a mandatory \"Curb Management Program\" to manage terminal frontage traffic (Sec 1.3).\n*   **Facility Maintenance:** Responsible for snow/ice control across 95,000m², daily litter pickup, and cleaning booths/buildings (GC 4.1.3, Appx C).\n*   **Equipment Monitoring:** Must daily monitor and immediately report deficiencies in VAA-owned SKIDATA, FLOWBIRD, and Hesion LPR systems (Appx D).\n\n### 3. Compliance & Reporting Obligations\n*   **Official Languages:** Must provide all printed materials and maintain on-shift staff capable of oral response in both **English and French** (GC 1.5.1).\n*   **Regulatory Compliance:** Adhere to the *Aeronautics Act*, *Official Languages Act*, and *Workers’ Compensation Act* (BC) (GC 9.1.2, 6.3.1).\n*   **Reporting Cadence:** Weekly signed Revenue Statements (every Friday) and Monthly Statements of Account (5th business day) (Clauses 1.3.1, 1.3.2).\n*   **Environmental:** Remediate any \"Adverse Environmental Condition\" caused by operations to private commercial standards at the Contractor's cost (GC 1.6.3).\n\n### 4. Timeline Obligations\n*   **Contract Term:** Five-year term starting June 1, 2025, to May 31, 2030 (Sec 1.4).\n*   **Office Setup:** Establish a local office within **two months** of award (Sec 2.10.1).\n*   **Incident Reports:** Written notice of any damage or incident must be provided **immediately** (GC 6.1.3).", :generated-tree-raw [:sequence [:chunk-document {:from :yyj_rfp, :size 12000, :into :chunks}] [:map-each {:from :chunks, :as :chunk, :into :extracted_data, :max-concurrency 5} [:llm {:instruction "Analyze this RFP section for a bidder. Identify: 1) Specific Obligations (Financial, Operational, Compliance, Reporting, or Timeline). 2) Penalties or consequences for non-compliance (include clause citations). 3) Significant risks or liabilities. Focus on finding concrete details rather than generic terms.", :reads [:chunk], :writes [:analysis]}]] [:aggregate {:from :extracted_data, :writes [:combined_analysis]}] [:llm {:instruction "Based on the comprehensive analysis of all RFP sections, produce the final structured report. \n         \n         1. :obligations - A structured classification of what the bidder MUST do (Financial, Operational, Compliance, Reporting, Timeline).\n         2. :penalties - Detailed list of consequences for non-compliance (termination triggers, financial penalties, disqualification) with clause references.\n         3. :risk-matrix - Map major obligations to a risk level (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW). Justify levels by evaluating 'Difficulty of Execution' vs 'Severity of Consequence' based on the RFP text.\n         4. :executive-summary - A high-level strategic overview of the top concerns and actionable recommendations for the bidder's leadership.\n         \n         REASON about the risks. Provide analytical depth, not just a list of clauses.", :reads [:combined_analysis], :writes [:obligations :penalties :risk-matrix :executive-summary]}] [:final {:keys [:obligations :penalties :risk-matrix :executive-summary]}]], :executive-summary "### Strategic Overview\nThe Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) RFP for Parking Management Services is structured as a **low-risk/high-reward model for the Authority** and a **high-liability/fixed-upside model for the Bidder**. By utilizing a \"Fixed Management Fee\" structure, the VAA offloads systemic risks—including inflation, labor disputes (unionization), and environmental events (snow/ice)—entirely onto the Contractor.\n\n### Top Concerns for Leadership\n1.  **Revenue Accountability:** The definition of \"Gross Revenue\" includes funds lost to theft or employee defalcation. You are effectively acting as an insurance entity for the VAA’s parking cash flow.\n2.  **Labor Cost Rigidity:** Section 2.1.2 explicitly forbids fee increases due to collective bargaining. If the local labor market forces wages up or a union is formed, your profit margin will be the only source of funding for these increases.\n3.  **The \"27% Trap\":** The 2% per month compounded interest on late revenue remittance is aggressive. Administrative errors in the \"5th Business Day\" reporting window carry a disproportionate financial penalty.\n4.  **Forecast Disclaimer:** The RFP provides growth forecasts but explicitly disclaims their accuracy (GC 1.7). Bidders must conduct independent validation; relying on VAA data for staffing models is a significant financial risk.\n\n### Actionable Recommendations\n*   **Insurance/Bonding Audit:** Ensure your Employee Dishonesty ($2M) and Crime ($10K/occurrence) coverage is robust enough to offset the \"Theft/Defalcation\" liability mentioned in Schedule A.\n*   **Operational Contingency:** Build a significant \"Winter/Peak\" buffer into the Fixed Management Fee to account for the mandatory Dec 22 – Jan 15 shuttle services and the 95,000m² snow removal liability.\n*   **Bilingual Recruiting Plan:** Since the VAA demands bilingual staff on *every* shift, your proposal must include a premium for these roles to ensure compliance, as this is a high-risk area for \"Unsatisfactory Performance\" termination.\n*   **Audit Protection:** Implement a third-party accounting software integration with VAA’s systems (SKIDATA/FLOWBIRD) to minimize the risk of a $\\ge$ 1% revenue discrepancy, which triggers full audit costs.", :chunks ["\n--- PAGE 1 ---\n \n \n \nRequest for Proposal \n \nSubject: Parking Management Services \n \nVictoria International Airport \n \n \nDate of Issue: Thursday, February 13th, 2025 \n \nResponse due by: Monday, March 31th, 2025 \n 2:00 pm Pacific Standard Time \n \n \n--- PAGE 2 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 1 \n \nTABLE OF CONTENTS \n \nDEFINITIONS .................................................................................................................................................. 2 \n1.0 OVERVIEW ......................................................................................................................................... 3 \n2.0 PROPOSAL INFORMATION .............................................................................................................. 12 \n3.0 CONTRACT INFORMATION .............................................................................................................. 20 \n \nSCHEDULE ONE        RECEIPT CONFIRMATION FORM ................................................................................. 23 \nSCHEDULE TWO       SUBMISSION CHECKLIST ............................................................................................. 25 \nSCHEDULE THREE     COMPANY PROFILE .................................................................................................... 26 \nSCHEDULE FOUR      PROPOSAL RESPONSE DOCUMENT ............................................................................ 28 \nSCHEDULE FIVE        FINANCIAL PROPOSAL FORMS .................................................................................... 33 \nSCHEDULE SIX          PROPONENT’S DECLARATION ..................................................................................... 34 \nSCHEDULE SEVEN    CONTACT INFORMATION FORM ................................................................................. 35 \n \nAPPENDIX A-  YYJ PARKING FACILITIES ....................................................................................................... 36 \nAPPENDIX B-  PARKING LOT RATES ............................................................................................................. 38 \nAPPENDIX C-  ICE CONTROL AND SNOW REMOVAL MAP .......................................................................... 39 \nAPPENDIX D-  PARKING EQUIPMENT LIST................................................................................................... 41 \nAPPENDIX E-  SAMPLE REPORTS ................................................................................................................. 52 \nAPPENDIX F-  PASSENGER ACTIVITY AND MARKET INFORMATION ............................................................ 56 \nAPPENDIX G-  FLIGHT SCHEDULES .............................................................................................................. 64 \nAPPENDIX H-  DRAFT FORM OF MANAGEMENT CONTRACT ...................................................................... 68 \n \n \n \n  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 3 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 2 \n \nDEFINITIONS \n The following definitions apply: \n  \n“Airport” means the Victoria International Airport. “Airport”, “Victoria International Airport”, \nand “YYJ” shall have equivalent meanings. \n \n “Authority” means Victoria Airport Authority. “Authority”, “Airport Authority”, and “VAA” shall \n have equivalent meanings. \n \n “Authority’s Authorized Representative” means the person designated by the Authority from \ntime to time to act as the Authority’s representative for the purposes of this RFP, or his/her \ndesignate. \n  \n“Contract” has the meaning ascribed to it under Section 3.0 of this RFP and a draft of which \nContract is attached to this RFP at Appendix H. \n \n“Curb Management Program” is the system whereby Curb Management Officers monitor and \nmanage the flow of vehicles on the shared use curbs on the terminal frontage and in the \ncommercial lane of the short-term parking lot. \n \n“Must”, “mandatory”, “required”, or “shall” means a specific criteria or requirement essential to \nbe met for the Proposal to receive and continue to receive consideration. \n \n“Net Book Value” or “NBV” means the value of an asset calculated as the original cost of the \nasset minus any accumulated depreciation, amortization, or impairment costs. \n \n“Operator” means the entity that shall operate, manage and administer the Parking Facilities at \nVictoria International Airport.  \n \n“Parking Facilities” refers to any and all parking areas in the vicinity of the Air Terminal Building \nat the Victoria International Airport which is subject to change from time to time. \n \n“Proponent” means the person, firm or corporation receiving and responding to this RFP. \n \n“Proposal” means the Proponent’s response to this RFP. \n \n“Quality Standards” means those standards set out in Schedule 8 of this RFP- Operational \nProposal. \n \n“Revenue” means all payments received and collected form the operation of the Parking \nFacilities in the form of cash, credit cards, debit cards, cheques, electronic transactions, and any \nother form of legal payment. \n \n“RFP” means this Request for Proposals and includes any modifications or additions thereto \nincorporated by addenda (if any) issued by the Authority prior to the closing date and time. \n--- PAGE 4 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 3 \n \n“Sales Tax” means the sales tax at the retailer level, the amount which is determined by the \namount of sales made and which is required to be collected and accounted for to any provincial \nor federal authority. \n \n“Should” or “desirable”, “or preferred” means a requirement having a specific or significant \ndegree of importance to meet the RFP objectives \n \n1.0  OVERVIEW \n \n1.1 ABOUT VICTORIA INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT \nVictoria, the provincial c apital of British Columbia,  is located on the southern tip of Vancouver \nIsland off Canada’s Pacific Coast and enjoys one of Canada’s mildest climates .  Almost hal f of \nVancouver Island’s population of 800,000 lives around Victoria and the southern end of \nVancouver Island.   \n \nThe Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) respectfully acknowledges that our operations take place on \nthe traditional territories of the W̱SÁNEĆ people, whose deep connection to this land endures to \nthis day. We are committed to fostering strong, collaborative relationships with the Tseycum First \nNation, Tsartlip First Nation, Tsawout First Nation, and Pauquachin First Nation. This commitment \nincludes seeking meaningful opportunities to partner with these Nations in all aspects of the \nairport’s operations and future development, ensuring mutual benefits and shared success. \n \n• YYJ Victoria International Airport (YYJ ) is operated by Victoria Airport Authority \n(“Authority”), a not-for-profit corporation that manages the safe and secure  operations \nof YYJ. \n• Victoria Airport Authority is the entity that operates, manages, and develops Victoria \nInternational Airport serving the Greater Victoria region and the surrounding area, 24 \nhours a day, seven days a week. YYJ is primarily an O and D (Origin and Destination) \nairport and, prior to Covid-19, was the third busiest (based on passengers) in the \nProvince of British Columbia after Vancouver and Kelowna reaching 2 million passengers \nin 2018, and the eleventh busiest in Canada. \nParking at YYJ is comprised of a total of 3243 spaces – 2 public daily parking lots with 2686 spaces, \na short-term parking lot with 166 spaces and an employee lot with 391 spaces.   \n \n1.2 PURPOSE OF RFP \nThe Authority’s overall vision is to be the best airport anywhere by making every part of travel \ninteraction as easy as possible.  Parking is often the first and last service customers experience at \nthe airport and provides a lasting impression .  Therefore  it is essential that the experience is \nfriendly and seamless. \n \nVAA is seeking a qualified parking management company to provide the best overall value to the \nAuthority and the best overall service to the travelling public who choose to park their vehicle at \n--- PAGE 5 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 4 \n \nthe airport, including those that drop off and pick up travelers.   Proponents are encouraged to \npropose innovative ideas with respect to the operation and management of parking facilities. \n \nAs such, the parking management company should provide the following key attributes: \n \n• Experience in operating and managing parking facilities, ideally in an airport environment. \n• Experience in curb management. \n• Knowledge of current trends, best practices and new technologies. \n• Service, culture and experience that exemplifies outstanding customer service. \n \nThe Authority anticipates that the current parking configuration and product offerings will \ncontinue to evolve over time. \n \nA forthcoming terminal expansion project is expected to impact parking; however, the specifics \nof these impacts remain uncertain at this stage. \n \nVAA encourages innovation and Proponents are invited to present new or innovative solutions in \nresponse to this RFP or presented as alternatives to requirements \nThe information contained in this document is intended to assist P roponents in offering a cost -\neffective solution.  It is not intended to limit the scope of response and is open to interpretation \nas to how requirements are to be achieved. \nInstructions for submitting Proposals; the terms and conditions which would govern any Contract \nresulting from this Request for Proposals ; the procedure and criteria by which a P roponent will \nbe selected; and the specifications for the required goods and/or services are described herein.  \n \n1.3 BUSINESS OPPORTUNITY \n \nThe Authority invites all interested and qualified companies desiring to manage the Parking \nFacilities at Victoria International Airport to submit a detailed Proposal in response to this RFP.  \n \nSpecifically, the opportunity is for one (1) parking management company to operate each lot  \ndescribed below collectively as the Parking Facilities  \n \n• Lot One – 1,405 spaces (daily parking lot) \n• Lot Two – 1,281 spaces (daily parking lot) \n• Short-Term Lot – 166 spaces \n• Employee Lot – 391 spaces \n• Seasonal overflow parking in contingency areas \nDevelop and implement a Curbside Management Program  to monitor and manage curbside \ntraffic activities both along the terminal frontage and the commercial lane in the short -term \nparking lot.  \n  \n--- PAGE 6 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 5 \n \n1.4 DURATION OF CONTRACT \n \nThe Authority will enter into a Contract with the successful Proponent for a term of five (5) years \ncommencing June 1st, 2025, and ending on May 31st, 2030, with the option for one (1) renewal \nterm of two (2) years, at the sole discretion of the Authority. Refer to Section 3.0- Contract \nInformation for further details. \n \n1.5 SELECTION PROCESS \n \n Following the closing date and time, it is the intention of the Authority to evaluate all Proposals  \nreceived according to the evaluation criteria described in the RFP documents. In addition to \nSection 2.18- Reserved rights of the Authority, the Authority further expressly reserves the right \nin its sole discretion to: \n• Clarify any Proposal received without becoming obligated to offer the same opportunity \nto any or all other Proponents. \n• Negotiate with one or more Proponents prior to award without becoming obligated to \noffer the same opportunity to any or all other Proponents. \n• Waive any minor or technical non-compliance by a Proponent with the requirements of \nthis RFP without becoming obligated to wave the same or any other non-compliance by \nany other Proponent; and \n• Accept any Proposal which in the Author" "ity’s opinion offers the best overall value and is \nmost advantageous. \nThe Authority shall not be bound by this RFP to accept any or all Proposals and may cancel this \nRFP in whole or in part at any time without any award or further liability whatsoever. \n \n1.6  MINIMUM STANDARDS \n \n This section outlines the requirements regarding the operation and management of the Parking  \n Facilities the successful Proponent will be responsible for at the Victoria International Airport.    \n The Authority expects the successful Proponent, as a qualified expert, to identify a responsible \nand cost-effective way to manage and operate the Parking Facilities \n \nIn general, the successful Proponent will be responsible for: \n• Providing day-to-day operation and management of the Parking Facilities at the airport \nin a responsible and cost-effective manner. \n• Develop and implement a Curbside Management Program. \n• Ice control and snow removal of the Parking Facilities as depicted in Appendix C. \n• Meeting the specified key performance standards. \n• Providing a high level of customer service is all aspects of a public parking operation. \nAny Proposal submitted by a Proponent must demonstrate how the following requirements \nwill be met: \n \n--- PAGE 7 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 6 \n \nA. EMPLOYEES \nParking is often the first and last service customers experience at the airport.  It provides a \nlasting impression of the airport customer’s experience. It is important that the customer’s \nentrance and exit from the parking lots is as easy and stress free as possible and interaction \nwith parking lot employees is polite, helpful and courteous at all times. \n \nThe successful Proponent will be responsible for all aspects of employment which includes \nbut is not limited to, hiring, training, discipline and dismissal to meet the management, \noperation, customer service and performance requirements of the Contract. \n \nThe successful Proponent will be required to have or do the following: \n \n• Local office presence, either currently established or to be established within two \n(2) months of Contract award.  This is to include a qualified on-site manager, the \nresume for whom must be provided before the Contract start date of June 1, 2025.  \n• Lot Attendant(s) staffing the booth(s) to perform cashiering functions primarily in \nLot 1 for a minimum 20 hours per day, seven (7) days a week.  Lot 2 booth may \nrequire staffing during peak holiday periods such as Thanksgiving and Christmas. \nThe Lot Attendant is also responsible for routinely patrolling the lots, picking up \ntrash, assisting customer at the entrance gates and exit plazas and implementing \nenforcement activities in both the long-term lots and the short-term lot. \n• Proponents should identify opportunities for Indigenous business engagement, skills \ntraining and employment in their Proposals. \n• Curb Management Officer managing the shared-use curbs on the terminal frontage \nand the commercial lane in the short-term lot for minimum15.5 hours a day, seven \n(7) days a week with hours to be reviewed as the program develops. \n• Have the ability to bring in additional trained and experienced staff onsite during \npeak periods and overflow situations that can be unpredictable. \n• Pay employees greater that the BC provincial minimum wage, plus benefits. Detail \nhow will staff be retained and rewarded for their contributions over the Contract \nperiod. \n• Supply all employees with uniforms that are approved by the Authority.  \n• All employes must be legally able to work in Canada. \n• Employees must be fluent in spoken and written English and formal education \nsufficient for effective communication.  Employees having French language skills is \nconsidered an asset. \n• Provide job descriptions for all staff positions involved in the performance of the \nContract. \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 8 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 7 \n \nB. TRAINING \nEmployees will be trained in operational requirements, customer service, and sensitivity \ntraining for people with disabilities. Training is to be provided at the successful Proponent’s \nexpense and records will be requested by the Authority in preparation for periodic audits \nconducted by the Canadian Transportation Agency (CTA).  At a minimum, training needs to \ninclude: \n \n1. Customer Service Training (i.e. WorldHost Customer Service training or the \nequivalent). \n2. Sensitivity Training (i.e. WorldHost- Inclusive Service or the equivalent). \n3. A minimum of 12 hours of “on the job” training prior to placing staff in the field. \n4. Technical training on the operation of equipment and computer software programs. \n5. Additional VAA-required and administered training includes: \n• Accessibility Training \n• Landside ID (Security Training)- This is detailed in the Security section of \nthe RFP \n• Sunflower Program (hidden disabilities) \n• And other future training programs as required by VAA. \n \nC. RESPONDING TO CUSTOMER COMPLAINTS \nThe successful Proponent will develop and maintain a complaint resolution process for \ndealing with all types of customer complaints.  A customer complaint report must be \nmaintained and reviewed with the Authority on a regular basis.  A copy of the complaint \nresolution process must be submitted as part of this RFP submission. \n \nThe successful Proponent will have a manager onsite that can immediately respond to a \ncustomer services issue. \n \nD. ACCESSIBILITY \n \nFor VAA, accessibility and inclusion are about making our airport Better for Everybody. \nWe believe everyone should have access in order to enjoy a barrier-free and accessible \ntravel experience and we continually work to promote inclusivity at Victoria International \nAirport. \n \nE. SECURITY \nThe successful Proponent, while not responsible for general security of the Parking Facilities, \nwill accept responsibility for all Revenues collected on behalf of the Authority and for \nincidents of property damage and injury that occur within areas of their responsibility. \n--- PAGE 9 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 8 \n \nF. HEALTH AND SAFETY  \n \n1. The successful Proponent shall comply with all Work Safe BC rules and regulations, \nOccupational Health and Safety rules and regulations, including but not limited to: \nmaintaining safe working conditions, provision of personal protective equipment, \nprovision of first aid personnel and supplies, investigation of accidents/incidents, \nmaintenance of records and statistics, instruction of workers and adequate training in \nthe safe operation of machinery and equipment. \n \n2. The successful Proponent shall maintain, at its own expense, an Occupational Health \nand Safety Program that complies with applicable health and safety legislation, Victoria \nAirport Authority’s health and safety requirements, and good industry practices. \n \nG. FINANCIAL RESPONSIBILITIES \n \n1. Revenue Collection \nThe successful proponent will be responsible for: \ni. Invoicing, collection and security of all Revenues and Sales Taxes related to \nthe Employee Parking (Employee and Airline Commuter parking). \nii. Invoicing, collection and security of all Revenue and Sales Taxes related to \nmonthly parking permits issued for Lot 1 or Lot 2. \niii. Collection and security of all Revenue and Sales Taxes collected from the \nshort-term parking lot. \niv. Collection and Security of all Revenue and Sales Taxes collected from Lot 1 \nand Lot 2 (daily parking lots). \nRevenue collected will be counted and reconciled in a secure location.  All Revenue \ncollected above under point I to iv will be deposited into the successful Proponent’s \nbank account no less that one time weekly.  All Revenues and Sales Taxes collected \nwill be forwarded to VAA no later than the 5th business day of the following month, \nalong with the operator’s required monthly accounting to VAA.  VAA will be \nresponsible for remitting any required Sales Taxes to the taxing authority. \n \n2. Monthly Accounting Report and Related Requirements \nThe successful Proponent will be responsible, no later than the 5th business day of \nthe month following, for providing a monthly reconciliation report by parking lot \nand Revenue type, in the required format, which may change from time to time that \nwill include: \ni. All Revenue and Sales Taxes collected directly by the successful Proponent, \nii. All credit card processing fees incurred by the successful Proponent, \niii. All Revenue and Sales Taxes deposited directly into VAA’s bank account, \n--- PAGE 10 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 9 \n \niv. All credit card processing fees incurred by VAA for revenues deposited \ndirectly into VAA's bank account. \nThe successful Proponent will also be responsible for providing to the Authority the \nfollowing financial reports: \n \ni. Weekly Statement of Account providing details of all Revenues earned \nrelated to the parking facilities by Revenue type and lot, \nii. Employee Shift Schedules and Hours of Work (upon request), \niii. List of current employees (monthly), \niv. Additional revenue or expense reports as specified by VAA, \nv. Details of any collection or invoicing challenges encountered related to the \ninvoicing for Employee Parking or Monthly Parking passes in Lot 1 or Lot 2. \n \n3. Financial Controls and Audits \nThe Authority reserves the right to audit the following at any time without prior \nnotification to or consent of the Contractor: \n \ni. Any and all staff records. \nii. All performance requirements. \niii. The level of customer service provided by the successful Proponent. \niv. Secondary audits of parking transactions and related Revenues. \nv. Onsite employee timesheet and payroll records. \n \nH. PARKING EQUIPMENT, FACILITIES  \n \nAll parking equipment and maintenance thereof related to the operation of the Parking \nFacilities will be provided by the Authority or their agent.  These will include: \n• All Parking Revenue Control equipment (PARCS) \n• Kiosks \n• Utilities \n• Lighting \n• Fixed and dynamic signage \n• Digital gantry sign (to be installed in spring 2025) \n• CCTV \nA list and description of the current PARCS equipment in use is attached as Appendix D.  \n \nThe building and equipment provided by the Authority will be used for the operation of the \nParking Facilities and related services and for no other purposes unless prior written \napproval is obtained from the Authority.  \n \n--- PAGE 11 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 10 \n \n  \nI. STATISICAL REPORTING \nVAA developed and currently manages its own statistical reporting for parking such as daily \noccupancy reports and passage reports. The successful Proponent will be required to \nassume responsibility for these reports either in the current format or in a proposed format \nacceptable to the Authority.  Daily and monthly reports are automatically sent from the \nSkidata Parking System to the Authority in a PDF format. \nSamples of the statistical reports are attached as Appendix E. \n \nJ. MARKETING \nThe successful Proponent will implement a robust marketing plan to optimize parking \nRevenue, utilization, and customer service.  The marketing initiatives could include internet-\nbased parking marketing techniques, including pre-paid reservations. All marketing must be \nin both official languages (English and French) and be pre-approved by the Authority. It is \nexpected that the Proponent would budget 0.5% of public parking Revenues toward \nMarketing. \n \nK. YYJ PARKING PERMIT PROGRAMS \n \nCurrently, VAA oversees its Air Terminal Building employee parking, commuter parking for \npilots and flight attendants, and monthly parking permit programs. Under the new Contract, \nVAA requires the Contractor to assume resp" "onsibility for managing these programs, \nincluding all financial aspects such as invoicing, payment processing, and the collection of \noutstanding fees. \n \nL. INNOVATION \n \nVAA values innovation as a key driver of operational excellence and encourages Proponents \nto continuously identify and present creative solutions, industry innovations, and emerging \ntrends that can enhance the parking experience, enhance Revenue opportunities and \noperational efficiency. Proponents are expected to proactively bring forward value-added \ninitiatives throughout the term of the agreement, leveraging advancements in technology, \nsustainable practices, and customer-centric approaches to deliver exceptional results. New \nservices may require infrastructure spending which will be borne by the Contractor and \ncharged back to the Airport Authority under business terms that are mutually agreed upon. \nExamples of new services could include Valet Services and Public Parking Shuttles. \n \nM. TRANSITION PLAN \nThe Proposal must include a comprehensive transition plan outlining how the Proponent \nintends to assume responsibility for operating the Parking Facilities. If the incumbent \n--- PAGE 12 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 11 \n \nContractor is the successful Proponent, the transition plan should address how they will \nimplement any new requirements outlined in this RFP that differ from their current \nContract. Any costs associated with establishing operations in the Parking Facilities will be \nthe sole responsibility of the successful Proponent and must not be passed on to the \nAuthority. \n1.7 EVALUATION CRITERIA \n \n The evaluation will be conducted by an evaluation committee made up of Authority employees   \nand its agents.  The Authority will evaluate all Proposals and look for overall value and most \nadvantageous Proposal.  The Authority is not to be limited as to its criteria for evaluation of \nProposals. Criteria will include, but is not limited to: \n \n• The Proponent’s ability to deliver and perform a quality service. \n• The Proponent's ability to demonstrate relevant experience, qualifications, company \nphilosophy, staff compensation programs, staff training programs, and evidence of \nsuccess providing parking and curb management services. \n• The Proponent’s financial plan including capital investment potential and profit sharing. \n• The Proponent’s reputation for quality service. \n• The Proponent’s experience managing similar parking and curb management programs. \n• The Proponent’s presence in the local markets and its ability to support the operations \nwith staffing, supervision, administration and technology. \n• The Proponent’s ability to recruit and retain staff through innovative and effective \nmethods will be a key consideration.  \n• Proponents should identify opportunities for Indigenous business engagement, skills \ntraining and employment in their Proposals.  \n• The Proponent’s capability and willingness to work in partnership with the Authority to \ndeliver and maintain exemplary parking services. \n• The Proponent’s financial stability. \n• The Proponent’s ability to demonstrate knowledge of safety standards as required by \nthe Canadian Centre for Occupational Health and Safety (CCOHS). \n• The Proponent’s references. \n• The quality of the Proposal. \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 13 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 12 \n \n Weighting \nUnderstanding and Approach \nClear indication that the Proponent understand the scope of work and requirements and \nthat the Proposal is complete, easy to read, and flows well. \n \n25% \nDescription of how the Proponent will meet the requirements outlined in Section 1.6 of \nthis RFP \n25% \nFirst Nations Opportunities 5% \nPricing 30% \nOther Factors/Value Add 15% \n \n \n1.8 ONSITE PRESENTATION \n  \nAfter the Proposal due date, the Authority may require any Proponent, at the Proponent's cost, \nto make on onsite oral presentation.  Such presentation(s) will provide an opportunity for the \nProponent to clarify its Proposal to ensure a through and mutual understanding of its benefits.  \nProponents would be notified by email, and the onsite presentation would take place at the \nVictoria International Airport, 2\nnd floor of the Air Terminal Building (1640 Electra Blvd).  The \nAuthority may, following any such presentation(s) require that the information provided during \nsuch presentation(s) be confirmed in writing.  The written confirmation provided will then form \npart of the Proponent’s Proposal.  \n \n1.9 DEBRIEFING \n \nAt the conclusion of the RFP process, all Proponents will be notified.  Unsuccessful Proponents \nmay request a debriefing meeting within thirty (30) days of receiving notification.  This can be \narranged by contacting the Authority’s Authorised Representative. \n \n2.0 PROPOSAL INFORMATION \n2.1 ELIGIBILITY TO SUBMIT A PROPOSAL \n \nIn order to submit a Proposal, a Proponent must meet the following pre-qualification \nrequirements: \n \n• The Proponent or its master franchisor (including those third parties detailed under \nSection 2.15) shall have been in the parking management business for a minimum of \nfive (5) years immediately prior to June 1st, 2025. \n• The Proponent’s experience managing parking and curb management at a comparable \nor larger airport is desirable. \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 14 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 13 \n \n \n \n2.2 DEADLINE DATE AND TIME FOR RESPONSE TO RFP \n \nResponses to this RFP for Parking Management Services  are due  \nMonday, March 31\nst , 2025 no later than 2:00 pm Pacific Standard Time (PST). \n \n2.3 MANDATORY PRE-BID MEETING AND SITE TOUR \n \nA MANDATORY pre-bid meeting and site tour for companies intending to submit a Proposal in \nresponse to this RFP will take place on:  \n \nDate: Thursday, February 27\nth, 2025  \nTime: 1:30 pm PST \nPlace: Victoria International Airport- 2nd Floor Administration Office \n 201-1640 Electra Blvd, Sidney BC V8L 5V4 \n \nMeeting instructions will be provided once Schedule One - Receipt Confirmation/Intent to \nSubmit a Proposal/RSVP for Mandatory Pre-Bid Meeting and Site Tour has been submitted.   \n \n \nThe site tour requirements are as follows: \n• Valid government-issued photo ID for all visitors \n• CSA-certified High-visibility vests for all visitors \n• Flat footwear \nCompanies who do not attend the mandatory pre-bid site meeting and site tour will \nbe excluded from bidding on this RFP. \n \n \n2.4 ISSUING OFFICE / AUTHORITY’S REPRESENTATIVE \n \n Victoria Airport Authority \n 201-1640 Electra Blvd \nSidney, B.C. V8L 5V4 \n \nAttention:   David Parson, Commercial Development Officer \nPhone:  (250) 413.7897 \nEmail:  rfpparkingmgmt@yyj.ca\n \n \n \n2.5 INQUIRIES \n \nAll inquiries and other communications relating to this RFP and any subsequent agreements are \nto be directed in writing to the above named person only, who is the Authority’s Representative \nor his designate. \n--- PAGE 15 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 14 \n \nDepending on the nature of the inquiry, the Authority may respond to inquiries in writing or if \nappropriate, issue a written addendum to the RFP to all Proponents registered as having returned \ntheir RFP Receipt Confirmation Form. \n \nIt is the responsibility of each Proponent to inquire and clarify any requirements of this RFP which \nare not understood.   \n \nThe Authority shall have no responsibility for, and  the Proponent agrees not to rely upon \ncommunications, representations or statements regarding this RFP, its subject matter or any \nsubsequent agreements from any other persons other than the Authority’s Representative or his \ndesignate. \n \n2.6 PROPOSAL SUBMISSION DETAILS \n \nThe Proponent shall, before submitting its Proposal, thoroughly examine and assess the Proposal \ndocuments, the site, and the equipment and materials needed to carry out and perform the  \nservices.  The Proponent must also be knowledgeable of all relevant laws, rules, notices, \ndirectives, standards, orders and regulations, licensing and permit requirements, labo ur market, \nand other circumstances that may affect the Proposal. \n \nSubmission of a Proposal constitutes a representation by the Proponent that it is familiar with and \naccepts the foregoing. \n \nThe Proponent must submit one (1) original hard copy, and a digital copy on a USB stick \nof its completed Proposal including applicable appendices prior to  \nthe closing date and time to the attention of: \n \nDavid Parson – Commercial Development Officer \nVictoria Airport Authority \n201-1640 Electra Blvd. \n2\nnd Floor Administration Offices \nSidney, BC V8L 5V4 \n \nThe closing Date and Time is Monday , March 31st , 2025 no later than 2:00 pm Pacific Standard \nTime (PST). \n \nIt is the Proponent’s responsibility to ensure that their Proposal submission meets the deadline \nstipulated above, the time stamp by the administration office will be the official time received. \n \nThe Proponent’s Proposal must be signed by an authorized signatory of the Proponent.   \nThe Proponent must note on the outside envelope that the Proposal is for the Parking \nManagement Services at YYJ.  \n \nNo hand-written Proposals shall be accepted. \n \nProposals sent by facsimile or email will not be accepted; mis-delivered Proposals may not be  \n--- PAGE 16 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 15 \n \naccepted.  The Authority reserves the right to make additional copies of all or part of the \nProponent’s Proposal for internal use or for any other purpose required by law.  Proposals will \nNOT be publicly opened.  The Proponent will be advised of the results after the evaluation of all \nProposals received are complete. \n \nThe Authority reserves the right in its sole discretion, to extend the closing date prior to the closing \ndate and time and  will endeavor to notify the Proponent as soon as practically possible in the \nevent of any extension of the closing date. \n \nProposals received after the closing date and time will not be accepted. \n \n2.7 KEY TARGET DATES \n \nFollowing are the Key Target Dates and Events with respect to this RFP process.  Such dates are \nnot guaranteed and may change based on circumstances. \n \nA. Request for Proposals Issued February 13th, 2025  \nB. Receipt Confirmation Form due February 20th, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nC. RSVP for Pre-Bid Meeting and Site Tour February 20th, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nD. Pre-Bid Meeting and Site Tour (Mandatory) February 27th, 2025 1:30 pm PST \nE. Deadline for Questions March 6th, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nF. Question Response Deadline March 10th , 2025  \nG. Closing Date for Submission of Proposals March 31st, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nH. Award to Successful Proponent (if any) April 24th, 2025  \nI. Contract Commencement June 1st, 2025  \n              This schedule may be subject to change without liability to the Authority. \n \n2.8 PROPOSAL REQUIREMENTS \n \nProposals will remain  valid and open for acceptance by VAA for sixty (60) days following the \nclosing date.  \n \nSpecific detailed requirements are contained in each of the Schedules  attached to this RFP.  The \nProponent must include, but is not limited to the following ,within its Proposal: \n \n• Schedule One – Receipt Confirmation Form \nIn order to receive information regarding the mandatory pre-bid meeting and site tour, and \nany addenda or  other correspondence from the Authority in connection with this RFP , the \nProponent must complete and submit the Receipt Confirmation Form by email, courier, or \nhand delivery to the Authority by February 20\nth, 2025. \n \n• Schedule Two - Submission Checklist \nThis form is provided to assist the Proponent to ensure all Schedules have been submitted. \n \n \n--- PAGE 17 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES " "\n  \n  \nPage | 16 \n \n• Schedule Three - Company Profile \nThe Proponent must list its company information including officers, board of directors, \naffiliations, and/or partnerships contact information, address, telephone or cell phone \nnumbers and email addresses. \n \n \n• Schedule Four - Proposal Response Document \nIn order to evaluate all P roposals received, a standard response document is required.  To \nassist the Proponent in the submission, each section of the Proposal Response Document is \nlisted in Schedule Four along with the description of the content required.  Written responses \nare to be made in the same sequence indicated in Schedule Four using the same headings and \nnumbers. \n \n• Schedule Five -  Financial Proposal Form \nThe Financial Proposal Form is to be completed in its entirety and submitted in excel format. \n \n• Schedule Six - Proponent’s Declaration \nProponents must sign declaration. \n \n• Schedule Seven – Contact Information Form \nThe New Party Contact Information Form is to be completed and submitted as part of the \nProposal.  \n \n2.9 PROPOSAL COSTS \n  \nThis RFP does not obligate the  Authority to pay any costs the Proponent may incur in the \npreparation of their Proposal.  All costs  and expenses incurred by the Proponent  such as travel \nexpenses to YYJ by the Proponent for the purposes  of the mandatory pre -bid meeting and site \ntour, information gathering or presentations to VAA, will be at the sole cost of the Proponent. \n \nAll costs and expenses with respect to the submission of a Proposal pursuant to this RFP shall be \nthe sole responsibility of the Proponent and the Authority assumes no liability whatsoever for any \nProponent costs and expenses.    \n \n2.10 OWNERSHIP \n \n All Proposals and supporting material will become the property of VAA. \n \n2.11 WITHDRAWL OF PROPOSALS \n \nProposals may be withdrawn prior to the closing date and time only.  Withdrawal notification \nmust be in written form and may be attached to an email to the Authority’s Representative and \nreceived by VAA prior to the closing date and time. \n--- PAGE 18 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 17 \n \n2.12  ADDENDUM \n \nThe Authority may, at any time prior to the closing date and time, issue additional information, \nclarifications, or modifications to the RFP by written addenda issued by the Authority’s \nRepresentative or his/her designate only.   Any addenda shall be considered an integral part of \nRFP.  \n \nTo receive any addenda, the Proponent must complete and submit a copy of the completed \nAppendix A- RFP Receipt Confirmation Form to the Authority as set out therein.  \n \nThe Authority will post addenda to its website and will otherwise use reasonable efforts to notify \nProponents of any such addenda, but it is the Proponent’s sole responsibility to ensure receipt of \nall addenda before submitting their Proposal. \n \n \n2.13  OMMISSIONS AND DISCREPENCIES \n \nIf the Proponent is in doubt as to the meaning or interpretation of anything in the RFP, find any \ndiscrepancies in, or find omissions from the RFP, the Proponent should immed iately contact the \nAuthority’s Representative. \n \nThe Proponent shall be solely responsible for any error, omissions, discrepancies or \nmisunderstandings resulting from the Proponent’s failure to examine thoroughly the RFP and \nfrom the Proponent’s failure to enquire further with the Authority. \n \n2.14 INTERPRETATION \n \nNo oral interpretation of this RFP by anyone, whether or not employed by the Authority, shall be \neffective to alter or modify any of the provisions in the RFP. \n \nEvery request for interpretation of the meaning of any of the requirements of the RFP shall be \nmade in writing to the Authority’s Representative only. \n \n \n2.15 PARTNERING / STRATEGIC ALLIANCES / SUBCONTRACTING \n  \nThe Proponent may partner with other third parties in order to fulfill all of the requirements set \nout in this RFP, provided that all partners, joint venturers and the like: \n• sign the signatory page of the Proposal,  \n• provide similar company profiles for each organization,  and any other documents as may, \nfrom time to time, be required by the Authority. \nProposals that include partnerships must include how the partnership will function within the \ndelivery of the services. \n \n--- PAGE 19 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 18 \n \nThe use of a sub -contractor, who must be clearly identified, to provide a portion of the \nProponent’s service or product is acceptable.  This includes a joint submission of two or more \nfirms having no formal corporate links.  In either case, one Proponent must be prepared to assume \nprimary responsibility for successful delivery of the scope of work described and for statutory \nobligations under the Worker’s Compensation Act, etc.  This must be clearly defined in the \nProposal. \n \n2.16 NO COLLUSION \n \nExcept as specified within its Proposal, the Proponent declares that no other person, either \nnatural or corporate, has or will have any interest or share, directly or indirectly, in this Proposal \nor in the proposed Contract, which may be awarded.  By submitting a Proposal, the Proponent \nwarrants that there is no collusion or arrangement, formal or informal, between the Proponent \nand any other actual or prospective Proponent in connection with its Proposal submitted for this \nRFP; the Proponent has no knowledge of the contents of any other Proposal; and the Proponent \nhas made no comparison of figures, agreement or arrangement, express or implied, with any \nother party in connection with the making of its Proposal, except as declared within the Proposal. \n \n2.17 DISCLOSURE OF INTEREST \n \n The Proponent is required to fully disclose in its Proposal: \n \na) Any relationship the Proponent may have with any employee, officer or director of the \nAuthority; and \nb) The nature of that relationship. \nFailure to disclose, or false or insufficient disclosure of the nature and extent of the relationship \nthe Proponent may have with an employee, officer or director of the Authority shall be grounds \nfor termination of any Contract with the Authority in the A uthority’s sole discretion without \nfurther liability or notice. \n \n2.18 RESERVED RIGHTS OF THE AUTHORITY \n \nThe Authority reserves the right to request clarifications and/or additional information as is \nnecessary to properly evaluate a  Proposal, negotiate with any Proponent or with another \nProponent or Proponents concurrently.  The Authority is not required to offer any modified terms \nto other Proponents. The Authority shall incur no liability to any Respondents as a result of such \nnegotiations or modifications. \n \nThe Authority reserves the right to cancel this RFP, to reject any or all Proposals; to re -advertise \nfor Proposals if necessary; to waive minor irregularities and formalities; and to accept the Proposal \nwhich offers, in the Authority’s sole judgement, the best overall value for the Authority.  All \nexpenses incurred by the Proponents will be solely at its own cost. \n \nThis RFP does not constitute an offer.  No Contract shall result upon submission of Proposals.  The \nAuthority is not under obligation to enter into a Contract with anyone in connection with this RFP \n--- PAGE 20 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 19 \n \nor responses received, nor pay for any costs incurred in the preparation of P roposals submitted \nin response to this RFP. \n \nThe Authority will consider past performance of the Proponent on other agreements in terms of \nquality of work and compliance with terms and conditions of those agreements.  The Authority \nmay also utilize other available resources to determine the Proponent’s record of past \nperformance. \n \n2.19 WAIVER OF NON-COMPLIANCE \n \nProposals which contain qualifying conditions or otherwise fail to conform to the instructions may \nbe disqualified or rejected.  The Authority may, however, in its sole discretion, retain, for its \nconsideration, evaluation and potential award, Proposals which are non-conforming because they \ndo not contain the content or form required by the instructions in this RFP or because the Proposal \ndoes not comply with the process for submission set out in the instructions in this RFP. \n \n2.20 CONFIDENTIALITY \n \nNotwithstanding anything contained herein, the Proponent agrees that  it will not exploit  any \ninformation, whether delivered to the Proponent by the Authority, or whether retrieved by the \nProponent by any other means and will make no direct or indirect disclosure to any other party \nof said information without the prior, express written agreement of the Authority. \n \n2.21 APPLICABLE LAW \n \nThe laws and courts of British Columbia shall apply and have exclusive jurisdiction over this RFP \nand any subsequent Contract which may be awarded. \n \n2.22 NO LIABILITY \n \nBy submitting a Proposal, the Proponent agrees that in no event will the Proponent claim damages \nfor any amount whatsoever for any cost incurred by the Proponent in preparing its Proposal or \nfor matters relating to any agreement or matters concerning the competitive pr ocess, and, the \nProponent, by submitting a Proposal, waives any claim for loss of profits if no Contract is made \nwith the Proponent. \n \nAny information contained in this RFP and attachments is provided to assist the Proponent in the \npreparation and submission of its Proposal.  The Authority assumes no responsibility for the use \nof this information for any other purpose. \n2.23 CONSENT TO INVESTIGATION \n \nIn order to allow the Authority to properly determine the qualifications and capabilities of a \nProponent, the Authority reserves the right in its sole discretion to conduct such investigations of \na Proponent’s business experience, financial capability and business practices as it deems \nnecessary, and the Proponent agrees to permit and cooperate with such investigations. \n \n--- PAGE 21 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 20 \n \n2.24 ALTERING DOCUMENTS \n \nProponents must not electronically alter any portion of this RFP with the exception of adding the \ninformation requested.  To do so, will invalidate the Proponent’s Proposal or response. \n \n2.25 DISCLAIMER \n \nWhile precautions have been taken to ensure that this file will not interfere with or cause damage \nto your system or its existing data, the Authority accepts no responsibility for damages that may \nbe caused by this file and makes no other warranty or representation, either expressed or implied \nwith respect to this file.  This file is provided “as is” and you, as the user,  assume the entire risk \nwhen you use it. \n \n2.26 WAIVER \n \nDue to the vag aries of electronic transmissions, the Authority does not guarantee, nor will it be \nliable for the accuracy of what is read or what is downloaded in this file. \n \n \n3.0 CONTRACT INFORMATION \n \n3.1 AWARD OF CONTRACT \n \nThe Contract resulting from this RFP, if any,  will be awarded in accordance with the process set \nout in Section 1.7 of this RPF- Evaluation Criteria. \n \n3.2 FORM OF CONTRACT \n \nThe successful Proponent will be required to enter into a Parking Management Services Contract \nwith the Authority in a form su bstantially similar to the form of Contract attached to this RFP at \nAppendix H (the “Contract”).  The Authority reserves the right to negotiate, modify, and/or add \nany contract terms and conditions to the Contract. \n \nProponents are encouraged to familiarize themselves with the content of the Contract and not in \ntheir Proposals any objections  to the terms and conditions or any items to be discussed or \nnegotiated.  The Proponent must satisfy itself in all respects as to the risks and obligations to be \nundertaken under any Contract entered into, as a result of the RFP. \n \nAll or part of this RFP " "and all or part of the Proposal may be incorporated into and form an integral \npart of the Contract. \n \n \n3.3 CONTRACT NEGOTIATIONS \n  \nThe Authority intends to negotiate and conclude a Contract with the most qualified and \nresponsible Proponent offering the best overall value, quality, and most advantageous Proposal. \n--- PAGE 22 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 21 \n \n \nA Contract must be concluded with the Authority based on the proposed (or negotiated) Proposal \nno later than thirty (30) business days from the official notification by the Authority of award to \nthe successful Proponent or the rights and privileges of this  opportunity may be forfeited unless \notherwise agreed to in writing by the Authority. \n \nIn the event a Proponent and the Authority fail to reach an agreement , negotiations may be \nterminated by the Authority , without any compensation whatsoever payable to the Proponent.  \nAn alternate Proponent may then be invited to  participate in the negotiation process.  This \nprocess may be repeated as often as necessary. \n \n3.4 REJECT AND RE-NEGOTIATE \n \n The Authority may reject all Proposals received and re-advertise for Proposals if necessary.  Such  \n cancellation of the RFP process does not preclude the Authority from subsequently meeting with \n any Proponent to negotiate a Contract that best suits the needs of the Authority. \n \n3.5 NO CONTRACTURAL OBLIGATION  \n \nThe Authority shall not be obligated in any manner to any Proponent whatsoever until a written \nContract has been negotiated and duly executed related to any Authority accepted Proposal. \n \n3.6 CONTRACT OFFER \n \nA Contract offer for Parking Management Services will only be made in writing by the Authority’s \nPresident and CEO. \n \n3.7 REQUIRED COMPLIANCE \n \nThe Proponent with whom the Authority chooses to enter into a Contract, if any, must comply \nwith all federal, provincial, and local laws, regulations, requirements and orders applicable to the \nperformance of any Contract which may result from this RFP process, including but not limited to, \nand Federal, Provincial, or Municipal occupational health and safety regulations or codes, \nelectrical and building codes, Work Safe BC regulations , and rules and regulations of any \ngovernment entities that have jurisdiction.  \n \n3.8 EXCLUSIVITY \n  \nThe Authority will not enter into an exclusive Contract with any successful Proponent during the \nterm of the Contract.  At any time, the Authority may at its discretion enter into other Contracts \nfor services similar to those of the successful Proponent.  It is understood and agreed t hat the \nAuthority will discuss any plans with the existing successful Proponent but cannot grant the right \nto any exclusivity to any individual successful Proponent. \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 23 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 22 \n \n3.9 PERMITS \n \nThe successful Proponent will be responsible to obtain and maintain all permits, licenses, and \napprovals required by Federal, Provincial, and Municipal or other government agencies to enable \nit to operate at the Airport. \n \n \n3.10 HOURS OF OPERATION \n \nThe Authority will require the successful Proponents to provide continuous service to the \ntravelling public by staffing the Parking Facilities on a full-time basis, with their hours of operations \nsufficient to provide service for all arriving and departing  flights. Sample flight schedules can be \nreviewed in Appendix G. \n \nThe Air Terminal Building is currently closed between 01:00 am and 03:30 am. \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 24 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 23 \n \n \n \nSCHEDULE ONE \nRECEIPT CONFIRMATION FORM/INTENT TO SUBMIT A PROPOSAL \nRSPVP FOR MANDATORY PRE-BID MEETING AND SITE TOUR \n \nProponents intending to submit a Proposal in response to this Request for Proposal must complete this \nform and return it no later than February 20th, 2025, to receive any further distribu