 written consent of the VAA to such sale, transfer or assignment of \nsuch shares will be required, which consent may be unreasonably withheld. \n \n1.2.3 The Contractor covenants and agrees to pay the VAA's solicitor and client costs relating \nto the VAA's consent to an assignment of this Contract and any documents relating \nthereto together with the VAA's administrative fee in an amount reasonably determined \nby the VAA. \n \n1.2.4 The Contractor will not retain or employ any Subcontractor  or supplier to perform any \npart of its obligations under this Contract without the prior, written consent of the VAA. \n \n1.2.5 No assignment of this Contract by the Contractor, nor implementation of any contract or \nsub-contract between the Contractor and any third party even though consented to by \nthe VAA, will exonerate the Contractor from liability under this Contract and for the due \nperformance and completion of the Work thereby contracted for. \n \nGC 1.3  CONTRACTUAL RELATIONSHIP \n \n1.3.1 This Contract is a personal Contract between the VAA and the Contractor and its essence \nis the provision of management, administration and maintenance of the Parking Facilities \nby the Contractor for the VAA. \n \n--- PAGE 112 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 43 of 67 \n \n1.3.2 F or greater certainty, but not so as to limit the generality of the foregoing, the Contractor \nacknowledges and agrees that this Contract does not grant to it any proprietary or \nproperty rights or interests in the Parking Facilities or in the lands upon which they are \nsituate and the Contractor further acknowledges and agrees that this Contract does not \nconstitute a lease or license or other interest in the Parking Facilities and/or the lands \nupon which they are situate either in law or in equity. \n \n1.3.3 Nothing in this Contract is intended to nor will it create any contractual relationship \nbetween the VAA and any Subcontractor or supplier or their agents,  employees or any \nother person performing any of the Work. \n \n1.3.4 No implied terms or obligations of any kind by either of the parties will arise from anything \nin this Contract, and only the express covenants and agreements of this Contract will be \nbinding upon the parties. \n \n1.3.5 The provisions of this Contract constitute the entire agreement between the parties and \nsupersede all previous communications , negotiations, statements, representations, and \nagreements either verbal or written between the parties relating to the Work. \n \nGC 1.4 FORCE MAJEURE \n \n1.4.1 Neither party to this Contract will be responsible for any delay or failure to perform its \nobligations under this Contract where such delay or failure is due to fire, flood, lightning, \ntempest, earthquake, pandemic, impact of aircraft, explosion, or Acts of God, or war, civil \nunrest, or any cause beyond either party’s control, excepting labour disruption or strike. \n \n1.4.2 If a force majeure event occurs, the party who is delayed or fails to perform as a result \nwill give prompt notice to the other party and will take all commercially reasonable steps \nto eliminate the cause of the force majeure event. \n \n1.4.3 Should the force majeure event last for longer than thirty (30) Days, the VAA may \nterminate this Contract by notice to the Contractor without further liability, expense or \ncost of any kind. \n \nGC 1.5 OFFICIAL LANGUAGES \n \n1.5.1. The Contractor covenants that it will: \n \na) comply with the Official Languages Act  (Canada) and Official Languages \n(Communications with and Services to the Public) Regulations\n and any other \n--- PAGE 113 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 44 of 67 \n \nregulations made thereunder and as may be amended from time to time and all \napplicable policies of the Government of Canada; \n \nb) comply with all applicable policies established by the VAA, acting reasonably, \nwhich policies shall be finalized after consultation with the Contractor; to the \nextent that the same shall be applicable to the Parking Facilities and any business \ncarried on therefrom; \n \nc) display or make available to the public in both official languages all printed and \nwritten material including signs, notices, instructions, directions, contracts, \ninvoices and any other publications in connection with the Contractor’s \noperations, which  shall be made available for review on request of the VAA, \nacting reasonably; \n \nd) during every shift of operations in all areas of the Parking Facilities which are used \nfor serving the public, have sufficient staff on duty to provide, within a reasonable \nperiod of time, an oral response capability in both official languages; and \n \ne) clearly demonstrate to members of the public that services are available in the \nofficial language of their choosing. \n \n \nGC 1.6 ENVIRONMENTAL MATTERS \n \n1.6.1 Interpretation - In this GC 1.6: \n \na) “ Adverse Environmental Condition” means the condition of the Parking Facilities \nor adjoining lands which has occurred after the establishment of the Victoria \nInternational Airport Environmental Baseline Study by Transport Canada of 1994 \nand as updated on March 6, 1997, and  which condition is caused or contributed \nto by: \n \n(i) non-compliance with any Environmental Requirements arising from the \nuse or occupancy of the Parking Facilities  or the exercise of the \nContractor’s rights under this Contract, or  \n \n(ii) any substance imported, manufactured, collected or discharged upon the \nParking Facilities , to the extent that such substance may significantly \nadversely affect the value of the Parking Facilities. \n \n--- PAGE 114 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 45 of 67 \n \nb) “Environmental Liability” means responsibility or fault for, ownership of, or \nallocation to, a Person of financial or other legal or equitable liability, whether \nbased on tort, contract, Environmental Requirement, or common law which is \nconnected with or arises out of the obligation to comply with the Environmental \nRequirements and/or the obligation to protect the natural environment, protect \nthe Parking Facilities from pollution, contamination, or damage; or to protect the \nadjacent land, air, or water from nuisance, trespass or environmental damage or \ndegradation. \n \nc) “ Environmental Requirements” means the requirements of any and all federal, \nprovincial, municipal, local, or other government statutes, laws, bylaws, \nregulations, or orders, in relation to, or providing for: \n \n(i) the protection of the natural environment; \n(ii) habitat protection or enhancement; \n(iii) the protection or improvement of land, air, or water; \n(iv) the regulation of discharges; \n(v) disposal of waste; \n(vi) the manufacture, storage, use or disposal of any hazardous \nmaterials; \n(vii) pollution prevention, control, avoidance, or regulation;  \n(vii) contaminated site regulation and remediation; \n \nand includes orders, or directives made by any such governmental authority that \nhas or would have jurisdiction over the Parking Facilities if they were privately \nowned commercial land. \n \n1.6.2 Environmental Compliance \n The Contractor will comply with and conform to all Environmental Requirements in \nrespect of the Parking Facilities. \n \n1.6.3 Remediation \na) The Contractor will, from time to time, subject always to Section 1.6. 5(c) at its \nown cost, repair and remediate any Adverse Environmental Condition, such \nworks to be undertaken at least to the standards set by Environmental \nRequirements as if the Parking Facilities were private commercial lands. \n \nb) The Contractor will leave the Parking Facilities  free and clear of all hazardous \nmaterials, contaminants, pollutants or other waste upon the expiry or earlier \ntermination of this Contract. \n--- PAGE 115 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 46 of 67 \n \n \n1.6.4 Investigation and Report \na) The Contractor will, at the VAA’s request, but not more than once in each year, \nsubject always t o Section 1.6.4(c) prov ide the VAA with written assurance or \nother documents reasonably required by the VAA certifying and confirming that \nthe Contractor has exercised due diligence and to the best of the Contractor ’s \nknowledge, is in compliance will all Environmental Requirements and no Adverse \nEnvironmental Condition exists relative to the Parking Facilities. \n \nb) If at any time the Contractor  is not in compliance with all Environmental \nRequirements or if an event occurs which causes an Adverse Environmental \nCondition at, on or under the Parking Facilities , the Contractor will forthwith \nnotify the VAA  of the details of such event and the Contractor  will forthwith \nprovide reports, documents, and other certifications as reasonably required by \nthe VAA certifying and confirming those facts and setting out a plan for \nremediation as required under the terms of this Contract , and the Contractor will \nforthwith take all appropriate steps to obtain approval for the remediation plans \nfrom the appropriate governmental authority and will comply with all \nEnvironmental Requirements that arise as a result of the Adverse Environmental \nCondition. \n \nc) In the event that the Contractor, in accordance with Section 1.6.4(a)  above, \nprovides anything other than confirmation of the absence of any Adverse \nEnvironmental Condition, and the Contractor, in the reasonable opinion of the \nVAA, is not taking action required under this Contract to remediate such Adverse \nEnvironmental Condition, then the VAA may require the Contractor to obtain, at \nits own cost and expense a qualified independent consultant to investigate the \nAdverse Environmental Condition, prepare all necessary studies, remediation or \nother action plan or proposal and to verify the Contractor’s complete and proper \ncompliance with all Environmental Requirements. \n \nd) The Contractor hereby authorizes and consents to the VAA  making inquiries of \nany governmental agency with respect to the Contractor’s compliance with \nEnvironmental Requirements pertaining to the Parking Facilities  or any business \nconducted on or from the Parking Facilities, or with respect to any repair, \nremediation or other works being undertaken in compliance with Environmental \nRequirements on the Parking Facilities or adjacent to the Parking Facilities. \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 116 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 47 of 67 \n \n1.6.5 Indemnity and Allocation \na) The Contractor will indemnify and save harmless the VAA from any and all \nliability, costs, claims or other liability or proceedings whether civil or criminal in \nnature arising from Environmental Liability resulting from the Contractor’s \nconduct within of the Parking Facilities. \n \nb) If the Contractor will bring, permit, suffer or create any substance in, on or under \nany part of the Parking Facilities  which causes or contributes to any Adverse \nEnvironmental Condition or triggers Environmental Requirements or causes \nEnvironmental Liability then notwithstanding any present or future \nenvironmental law, such substance will remain the sole and exclusive property of \nthe Contractor and will not become the property or the responsibility of the VAA, \nnotwithstanding the degree of affixation of the substance to the Parking Facilities \nor any land adjacent thereto. \n \nc) Notwithstanding the commencement date of the Term of this Contract , the \nContractor acknowledges and agrees that it is responsible and liable for any \nAdverse Environmental Condition to the Parking Facilities caused by the actions, \nnegligence or willful misconduct of the Contractor, its employees or agents.  \n \nd)  This Section is a contract allocating responsibility and liability to the Contractor  \nto the extend set out in this Section 1.6.5  in accordance with the Environmental \nManagement Act (British Columbia) or any successor legislation thereto, and the \nVAA and the Contractor agree that any allocation between them as responsible \npersons as defined in the Environmental Management Act  will be undertaken \ntaking into account this provision. \n \n1.6.6 VAA to Undertake Environmental Works \n If the Contractor fails to comply with any Environmental Requirement the VAA may, after \nreasonable Notice to the Contractor, elect to perform work in accordance with the same, \nin which event the VAA, its employees, contractors, subcontractors and consultants: \n \na) Will have uninterrupted and unimpeded access to the Parking Facilities; provided \nthat it will give Notice to the Contractor of all times and manner of access and will \nat all times act reasonably after consultation with the Contractor and carry out \nthe work with due consideration to cost and to disruption of the operations of \nthe Contractor. \n \nb) May enter onto the Parking Facilities by or with machinery and equipment, or \nnot. \n--- PAGE 117 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 48 of 67 \n \n \nc) May perform any such work at the cost and expense of the Contractor as is \nrequired hereunder. \n \nd) Will carry out any work undertaken in a good and workmanlike manner and once \ncommenced carry on the same through to completion without undue \ninterruption returning the Parking Facilities at completion to a condition as near \nas reasonably possible to the same condition as before the work. \n \ne) Will not thereby surrender any of its rights, protections, indemnities, or the \nallocation of responsibility and Environmental Liability hereunder, \n \nand all Costs relating to the performance of the environmental work by the VAA will \nbecome forthwith due and payable by the Contractor to the VAA and will be paid by the \nContractor to the VAA  forthwith upon request by the VAA  for payment, it being \nunderstood that failure to pay such amount will be deemed to be a Default. \n \n1.6.7 Survival \n The rights and obligations of the VAA  and the Environmental Liability and other \nobligations of the Contractor under these Environmental Provisions will survive the expiry \nor earlier termination of this Contract except only that to the extent the performance of \nthe Contractor’s obligations requires access or entry onto the Parking Facilities or any part \nthereof after the expiry or earlier termination of this Contract  , the Contractor will have \nsuch entry and access only at such time and upon such terms and c onditions as the VAA \nmay reasonably specify.  \n \nGC 1.7 GOVERNING LAW \n \n1.7.1 This Contract will be governed and interpreted in accordance with the laws in force in the \nProvince of British Columbia, subject always to any paramount or applicable federal laws.  \nIn the event that any provision of this Contract is in conflict with any provincial or federal \nlaw or regulation, such provision will be deemed modified to conform with such law or \nregulation and all other provisions will remain in full force and effect. \n \n1.7.2 Nothing in this Contract is intended to nor will be construed as limiting, waiving or \nderogating from any Federal Crown prerogative. \n \nGC 1.8 INDEPENDENT STATUS \n \n1.8.1 The parties expressly acknowledge that the Contractor is an independent contractor and \n--- PAGE 118 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 49 of 67 \n \nneither an agency, partnership, joint venture, joint enterprise, nor an employer-employee \nrelationship is intended or created by this Contract \n \n1.8.2 The Contractor will be solely responsible for all matters relating to: \n \na) the statutory deduction of all taxes, employment insurance, Canada Pension Plan \nand any other similar matter required by law; \n \nb) leave, remuneration, Workers' Compensation, insurance premiums and discipline \nof its personnel and Subcontractors; and \n \nc) all licenses and permits which are or may become required to perform the Work. \n \n1.8.3 Notwithstanding the foregoing, while the Contractor is solely responsible for the method \nand manner of performing and completing the Work, the Contractor acknowledges that \nthe VAA has the right to: \n \na) supervise the Work which is performed on the Airport for compliance with VAA \npolicies, procedures, security measures, safety and environmental laws, \nregulations and procedures; and \n \nb) supervise or review the performance of the Work for quality control within the \nScope of Work requirements as set out in Schedule ' B', and the terms and \nconditions of this Contract. \n \nGC 1.9 INTENT OF THE CONTRACT \n \n1.9.1 The intent of the Contract Documents is that the Contractor will supply, to the satisfaction \nof the VAA, all labour, materials, and services necessary for the full and complete \nperformance of the Work in accordance with these documents but it is not the in tent of \nthese documents that the Contractor will perform work not consistent with, covered by, \nor, properly inferable from the Contract Documents. \n \nGC 1.10  INTERPRETATIONS \n \n1.10.1 If the Contractor is comprised of two or more persons or entities, all covenants, provisos, \nconditions or agreements will be construed as being joint as well as several. \n \n1.10.2 Headings or captions are for convenience only, and are not to be construed as part of this \nContract and do not in any way limit or amplify the terms and provisions of this Contract. \n--- PAGE 119 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 50 of 67 \n \n \n1.10.3 References to the masculine or the singular will include the feminine or the plural as the \ncontext requires. \n \n1.10.4 The invalidity of any clause or subclause of a non-material nature will not affect any other \nclause or subclause of this Contract which will be construed as if such invalid clause or \nsubclause were omitted. \n \nGC 1.11   NOTICES \n \n1.11.1 Whenever in this Contract it is required or permitted that notice or demand be given or \nserved by either party to or on the other, such notice or demand will be in writing and will \nbe validly given or sufficiently communicated if personally delivered, give n by electronic \nmail, or sent by courier, priority post, or registered mail, return receipt requested, to the \nVAA or the Contractor, as appropriate, at their respective addresses which appear on \npage 1 of the Articles of Agreement. \n \n1.11.2 Such addresses and facsimile numbers may be changed from time to time by either party \ngiving notice to the other as above provided. \n \n1.11.3 Notices given hereunder will be deemed effectively given to the party; \n \na) if delivered personally to the party or its contract representative, on the day it is \ndelivered; \n \nb) if forwarded by courier, priority post, or registered mail, on the earlier of the date \nit is delivered or the third day after it was sent; or \n \nc) if forwarded by electronic mail, 24 hours after transmission with confirmed \nanswer-back. \n \nGC 1.12   STATUTES, REGULATIONS AND RULES \n \n1.12.1 Any reference in this Contract to all or any part of any statute, regulations or rule, will, \nunless otherwise stated, be a reference to that statute, regulation or rule or the relevant \npart thereof, as amended, substituted, replaced or re-enacted from time to time. \n \nGC 1.13   SURVIVAL OF OBLIGATIONS \n \n1.13.1 All obligations of each party which by their nature require all or part of their performance \n--- PAGE 120 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 51 of 67 \n \nor fulfilment after the expiry or termination of this Contract will (whether specifically \nprovided for in this Contract or not) survive the expiry or termination of this Contract. \n \nGC 1.14   TIME OF THE ESSENCE \n \n1.14.1 All references to time in this Contract are conditions of the Contract and are of the \nessence of the Contract. \n \nGC 1.15   WAIVER \n \n1.15.1 Any waiver of default, breach or non-observance by the Contractor of any of its covenants \nor obligations hereunder will not operate as a waiver of the VAA's rights hereunder in \nrespect of any continuing or subsequent default, breach or non-observance. \n \nPART 2 ADMINISTRATION OF THE CONTRACT BY THE VAA \n \nGC 2.1 ADDITIONAL INSTRUCTIONS \n \n2.1.1 During the performance of the Work, the VAA may at any time give additional instructions \nto the Contractor which instructions will be promptly followed by the Contractor. \n \n2.1.2 Such additional instructions will be consistent with the intent of this Contract and will not \nbe construed as changes to the Work. \n \nGC 2.2 CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION \n \n2.2.1 The Contractor agrees that all knowledge and information of the VAA's business, \ninventions, discoveries, or any confidential or secure information, knowledge or data of \nthe VAA or the Airport generally which the Contractor may be given, obtain, acquire or \ndiscover directly or indirectly, before, during, or after the performance of the Work will \nbe kept in strict confidence and will not be divulged or disclosed to any Person before, \nduring or after completion of the Work, except as may be essential to perform the Work. \n \nGC 2.3 INSPECTION AND EXAMINATION OF WORK \n \n2.3.1 At all times, the VAA may, with such assistance from experts of its choice, inspect or \nexamine the Work to determine whether the Work is being performed properly and in \naccordance with the Contract. \n \n2.3.2 In the event the VAA determines in its sole opinion that the Work or any portion of the \n--- PAGE 121 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 52 of 67 \n \nWork is deficient, non -compliant with this Contract or defective, the Contractor will \nimmediately resolve the problem(s) to the full satisfaction of the VAA. \n \n2.3.3 In the event the Contractor fails to resolve any identified problems promptly upon notice \nfrom the VAA to do so, the VAA may do whatever it deems necessary to resolve the \nproblem(s) at the Contractor's cost and expense. \n \nGC 2.4 INTERPRETATION OF CONTRACT BY VAA \n \n2.4.1 In the event a question arising from the Contract about anything to be done or which has \nbeen done by the Contractor, including but not limited to: \n \na) the meaning of anything in the Scope of Work; \n \nb) the meaning of anything in the Contract in the case of any error, omission, \nobscurity or discrepancy in wording or intention of the Contract; or \n \nc) whether the requirements of the Contract are being met; \n \nthe question will be decided by the VAA whose decision will be final, binding and  \nconclusive, but subject always to GC 5.2 - ARBITRATION. \n \n2.4.2  The Contractor will promptly perform the Work according to any decisions of the VAA \nmade under GC 2.4.1 and in accordance with any consequential direct ions made \nthereafter by the VAA. \n \nGC 2.5 OWNERSHIP OF DOCUMENTATION AND PROPERTY \n \n2.5.1 All documentation and property provided by the VAA to the Contractor will be and will \nremain the exclusive property of the VAA and will be delivered by the Contractor to the \nVAA immediately upon the VAA's written request to the Contractor and will, in any event \nbe returned to the VAA forthwith upon termination or expiration of the Contract. \n \n2.5.2 All documentation prepared or property produced by or at the discret ion of the \nContractor directly or indirec tly in connection with the Work , which the VAA in its sole \ndiscretion determines may have intellectual property value, will be deemed owned by \nand to be the sole property of the VAA. \n \n2.5.3 If requested by the VAA, the Contractor will do all things necessary to transfer any \nintellectual property to the VAA and to preserve and protect the VAA's property rights in \n--- PAGE 122 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 53 of 67 \n \nthe intellectual property throughout the world. \n \n2.5.4 The Contractor further agrees to join in and cooperate with the VAA in any defence or \nassertion of the VAA's intellectual property rights including without limitation any moral \nrights in copyrighted material. \n \n \nPART 3 EXECUTION OF THE WORK \n \nGC 3.1 CONTRACT MANAGER \n \n3.1.1 The Contractor will within ten (10) Days of the signing of this Contract or prior to \ncommencing work (whichever is earlier), designate a Contract Manager to be in charge of \nthe day to day performance of the Work for the Contractor. \n \n3.1.2 The Contractor will not substitute a Contract Manager without first advising the VAA. \n \n3.1.3 Upon request of the VAA the Contractor may be required to remove any Contract \nManager, who the VAA in its sole opinion deems to be unsuitable and to replace the \nperson with one who is acceptable to the VAA, which request will not be construed as \ninterference with the Contractor's performance of the Work. \n \nGC 3.2 CONTRACTOR'S RESPONSIBILITIES AND CONTROL OF THE WORK \n \n3.2.1 Subject to the Contract the Contractor will have complete control of the Work and will \neffectively direct and supervise the Work so as to ensure conformity with this Contract. \n \n3.2.2 The Contractor will carry out the Work described in this Contract in a careful and \nworkmanlike manner to the full and complete satisfaction of the VAA. \n \n3.2.3 The Contractor expressly warrants that all materials, goods and supplies provided by the \nContractor to be used in the performance of the Work will be new, fit for the intended \npurpose, of merchantable quality, free from all defects, of the best quality and carefully \ninstalled or applied (if applicable) in accordance with any manufacturer 's specification \nand warranty requirements. \n \nGC 3.3 LABOUR AND INDUSTRIAL RELATIONS \n \n3.3.1 The Contractor will make every effort to perform the Work and /or cause his \nSubcontractors and suppliers to perform the Work, both on and off the Airport, in a \n--- PAGE 123 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 54 of 67 \n \nmanner which avoids all labour disputes, including compliance with any rules or \ninstructions issued by the VAA regarding industrial relations. \n \n3.3.2 In the event of any actual or threatened labour  dispute involving employees of the \nContractor or any Subcontractor or supplier, whether at the Airport or elsewhere, which \nwill or may affect performance of the Work, the Contractor will: \n \na) immediately notify the VAA of any current, pending, or threatened labour \ndispute; \n \nb) take all steps reasonably necessary to avoid and mitigate the delays, damages \nand other effects of an interruption; \n \nc) within eight (8) hours after the commencement of any labour dispute, provide to \nthe VAA a full report on such dispute including, to the extent  known to the \nContractor, the cause of the dispute, the employer and employees affected or \ninvolved, the action being taken to end the dispute and the known or probable \neffect on the Work; \n \nd) continue such reporting to the VAA as may be requested by the VAA; and \n \ne) work with the VAA to minimize the impact of the interruption, which may include \nlocating and arranging substitute parking management service providers to \nensure that the continuity and performance of the Work will not be jeopardized, \nand all on such terms and conditions as the VAA, in its discretion, considers \nnecessary. \n \nNotwithstanding the foregoing, if the Interruption extends for a period in excess of seven \n(7) consecutive Days, the VAA may at its sole discretion and in addition to the rights and \nremedies available to it under this Contract , elect to suspend or terminate this Contract \nin whole or in part immediately upon written notice to the Contractor. \n \nGC 3.4 SUBCONTRACTORS \n \n3.4.1 The Contractor will advise the VAA, in writing, of which Sub contractors and suppliers it \nintends to use for performance of any portion of the Work within (10) ten Days of the \nsigning of this Contract or prior to commencing the Work (whichever is earlier) and, unless \nthe VAA objects at such time, the Contractor will employ those Subc ontractors and \nsuppliers as indicated. \n \n--- PAGE 124 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 55 of 67 \n \n3.4.2 The VAA may, for reasonable cause, object to the use of a proposed Subcontractor  or \nsupplier and require the Contractor to employ another , to whom the Contractor has no \nreasonable objection. \n \n3.4.3 The Contractor may not change Subcontractors or suppliers, once agreed upon, without \nthe prior, written consent of the VAA. \n \n3.4.4 The Contractor shall ensure that any Subcontractor will adhere to all of the Contractor’s \nobligations and requirements under this Contract as if they were the Contractor  \nthemselves and that the sub contracting by the Contractor  of any portion of the Work  \ndoes not absolve the Contractor of any of its responsibilities and obligations hereunder. \nThe Contractor will preserve and protect the rights of the VAA with all Subcontractors and \nsuppliers it employs and will: \n \na) enter into written contracts with such Persons to require them to perform their \nwork under this Contract; \nb) incorporate all the terms and conditions of this Contract into all c ontracts with \nSubcontractors and suppliers; and \nc) be as fully responsible to the VAA for the acts and omissions of Sub contractors \nand suppliers and other persons employed by them , directly or indirectly, as the \nContractor is for the acts and omissions of the Contractor's own employees. \n \nGC 3.5 WARRANTY ON PARTS AND MATERIALS \n \n3.5.1 In the event of any parts and/or materials which are installed or replaced under this \nContract, the Contractor will ensure that any and all manufacturers' or sellers' warranties \nor guarantees are obtained in the name of the VAA and submitted to the VAA. \n \n \nPART 4 NON-COMPLIANCE, SUSPENSION AND TERMINATION \n \nGC 4.1 FAILURE TO COMPLY WITH VAA DECISIONS \n \n4.1.1 If the Contractor fails to comply with any decision or direction of the VAA made pursuant \nto this Contract, the VAA may, upon notice to the Contractor, employ such methods as \nthe VAA deems advisable to do that which the Contractor failed to do, at the Contractor's \ncost and expense  \n \n4.1.2 The Contractor will be liable for and will upon demand pay to the VAA an amount equal \nto the aggregate of all costs, expenses and damages including the cost of any methods \n--- PAGE 125 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 56 of 67 \n \nthe VAA employed in GC 4.1.1 by reason of the Contractor's failure to comply as above. \n \nGC 4.2 TERMINATION FOR CAUSE \n \n4.2.1 The VAA may in its sole discretion terminate this Contract forthwith without notice upon \nthe happening of any of the following events: \n \na) an Order is made or a resolution is passed or a petition is filed for the liquidation \nor winding-up of the Contractor; \n \nb) the Contractor becomes insolvent or commits an act of bankruptcy or makes an \nassignment for the benefit of its creditors or otherwise acknowledges its  \ninsolvency;  \n \nc) on becoming bankrupt or insolvent makes application for relief under the  \nprovisions of any statute now or hereafter in force concerning bankrupt or \ninsolvent debtors; \n \nd) a receiver or receiver manager of any property of the Contractor is appointed; \n \ne) the Contractor ceases in the reasonable opinion of the VAA to carry on business; \n \nf) the Contractor fails to promptly make the payments, referred to in Clause 1.2 of \nSchedule 'C', to the VAA; \n \ng) the Contractor fails to provide and maintain the Letter of Credit or the insurance \ncoverage referred to in Schedule 'D' of this Contract; \n \nh) the Contractor has in any way become unable or unwilling to carry on the Work \nor any part thereof; \n \ni) the Contractor has abandoned the provision of the Work or any part thereof; \n \nj) the Head Lease between the VAA and the Crown is termi nated for any reason \nwhatsoever; \n \nk) the Contractor has committed what the VAA in its sole discretion determines is a \nbreach of a fundamental term of this Contract including, without limitation, the \ntypes of breaches of Contract referred to in GC 4.2.2, which the VAA in its sole \ndiscretion de termines is of such a serious nature as to warrant immediate \n--- PAGE 126 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 57 of 67 \n \ntermination of this Contract without giving the Contractor notice under GC 4.2.2 \nto remedy any such breach of the Contract. \n \n4.2.2 If at any time the VAA determines in its sole discretion that the Contractor's Work is \nunsatisfactory including, without limitation: \n \na) the Contractor 's actions have or may compromise the operation of the Parking \nFacilities, create potential revenue loss or constitute an inadequate level of \ncustomer service; \nb) the Contractor has failed or is failing to diligently perform the Work stipulated for \nin this Contract or has failed to comply with the instructions of the VAA; \nc) the Contractor has failed or is failing to supply enough competent personnel or \nmanagement as is necessary to ensure performance of the Work under this \nContract; \nd) the Contractor has failed to observe or has breached any other term,  condition \nor provision of this Contract; \n \nthe VAA may notify the Contractor in writing that it is in default of its contractual  \nobligations and instruct it to remedy the default within a period to be stipulated by  the \nVAA, in its sole discretion.  If the Contractor fails to correct the default within the \nstipulated period after receipt of notice from the VAA, or if the VAA has determined in its \nsole discretion that the default cannot reasonably be remedied within the stipulated \nperiod and the Contractor fails to: \n \na) commence correction of the default promptly upon receipt of the VAA's notice; \nb) provide the VAA with an acceptable schedule for such correction; or \nc) complete the correction in accordance with such schedule; \n \nthen the VAA will be entitled to terminate this Contract forthwith without further notice \nto the Contractor. \n \n4.2.3 In the event of termination of this Contract pursuant to this GC: \n \na) the Contractor will be liable to pay the VAA upon demand for all loss, costs or \ndamages incurred by the VAA as a result of such termination, including without \nlimitation damages equal to costs incurred in having the Work performed by \nanother contractor, pl us such additional charges as may be applicable with the \npolicies of the VAA for administration and overhead; and \nb) the VAA will determine the amount (if any) due or accruing due to the Contractor \nprior to the date of termination and subject to this GC, all of the Contractor 's \n--- PAGE 127 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 58 of 67 \n \nright to further payment is extinguished upon the effective date of such \ntermination. \n \nGC 4.3 REMEDIES \n \n4.3.1 Termination of this Contract will be without prejudice to any and all other remedies \npursuant to this Contract or at law which the VAA may have as a result of the Contractor's \nfailure to observe and perform the terms and conditions of this Contract. \n \n4.3.2 The rights, powers and remedies conferred upon the VAA under this Contract are not \nintended to be exclusive and each will be cumulative and in addition to and not in \nsubstitution for every other right, power and remedy existing or available to the VAA \neither under this Contract, at law or in equity and the  exercise by the VAA of any right, \npower or remedy will not preclude the simultaneous or later exercise by the VAA of any \nother right, power or remedy. \n \nGC 4.4 SET-OFF \n \n4.4.1 If, under this Contract, the Contractor becomes obligated or liable to pay any sum of \nmoney to the VAA, then that sum may, at the election of the VAA and without limiting or \nrestricting any other remedies of the VAA under this Contract or at law, be set-off against \nand be applied against any sum owed to the Contractor hereunder. \n \nGC 4.5 COMPETITION \n \n4.5.1      The Contractor acknowledges that the success of the Parking Facilities and income of the \nVAA therefrom are dependent upon the generation of Gross Revenue. \n \n4.5.2     The Contractor agrees that it shall not, without the prior written consent of the VAA, \nduring the Term:  \n               a)           engage directly or indirectly in any business or undertaking; \nb)        permit any director, officer, shareholder, employee, contractor, agent or other \nPerson who is not acting at Arm’s Length with the Contractor, to engage directly \nor indirectly in any business or undertaking;  \n \nwhich is carried on within a radius of ten (10) kilometers from any point on the perimeter \nof the Airport Lands and which business or undertaking is advertising Airport Parking and \nactively offering parking directed specifically to Airport customers in direct competition \nwith the Parking Facilities.   \n \n--- PAGE 128 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 59 of 67 \n \n4.5.3     Where the Contractor contravenes the provisions of GC 4.5.2 then, in addition to any \nother right or remedy available to the VAA under this Contract or at law, the VAA may, at \nits option apply for an injunction from any court of competent jurisdiction restraining the \nContractor from breaching the provisions of GC 4.5.2. \n \n4.5.4 In the event the VAA applies for an injunction restraining the Contractor from breaching \nthe provisions of GC 4.5.2, the Contractor  hereby consents to any such application for \ninjunctive relief. \n \n \nPART 5 DISPUTES \n \nGC 5.1 DISPUTE RESOLUTION \n \n5.1.1 Each party will endeavour honestly and in good faith to identify and resolve promptly by \nagreement all disputes and issues related to this Contract or the performance of the \nWork. \n \n5.1.2 If the parties are unable to resolve a dispute they will give due consideration to engaging \nin alternative dispute resolution procedures, including without limitation, mediation or \narbitration, that the parties consider suitable and appropriate with respec t to the \nresolution of any such dispute or issue. \n \n5.1.3 The Contractor will not stop or delay performance of the Work pending resolution of any \nsuch dispute or issue, but may give notice to the VAA promptly upon becoming aware \nthat such a dispute or issue exists that the Contractor is performing under protest, in \nwhich case the Contractor does not prejudice any of its legal rights in relation to that \ndispute or issue. \n \nGC 5.2  ARBITRATION \n \n5.2.1 Subject always to GC 5.2.2, either party may refer a dispute to arbitration, in which event \nthe same will be determined by one arbitrator (provided the parties agree on such \narbitrator) in accordance with the provisions of the Arbitration Act of British Columbia, \nR.S.B.C. 2020 c.2,  except that all proceedings will take place in Greater Victoria. If the \nparties do not agree upon an arbitrator within twenty (20) Business Days of notice of \narbitration, each party will appoint their own arbitrator, who will the n appoint a third \narbitrator and the dispute referred to arbitration will be determined by three arbitrators \nin accordance with the provisions of the aforesaid Arbitration Act. \n \n--- PAGE 129 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 60 of 67 \n \n5.2.2 Any dispute may be submitted to arbitration except: \n \na) the breach or alleged breach of the confidentiality provisions of this Contract; \n \nb) the fundamental breach or alleged fundamental breach of this Contract by either \nparty; or \n \nc) where this Contract has been lawfully terminated or suspended by VAA pursuant \nto this Contract; \n \nunless both parties otherwise agree. \n \nGC 5.3 JURISDICTION OF COURTS \n \n5.3.1 Subject to the provisions of GC 5.1 and GC 5.2 hereof, the Courts of British Columbia will \nhave the exclusive jurisdiction to entertain and determine all disputes and claims whether \nfor specific performance , injunction, dec laration or otherwise howsoever, both at law \nand in equity, arising out of or in any way connected with the construction, breach, or \nalleged, threatened or anticipated breach of this Contract and to hear and determine all \nquestions as to the validity, existence or enforceability thereof. \n \n \nPART 6 PROTECTION OF PERSONS AND PROPERTY \n \nGC 6.1 PRECAUTIONS AGAINST DAMAGE, INFRINGEMENT OF RIGHTS, FIRE AND OTHER \nHAZARDS \n \n6.1.1 The Contractor will, in the performance of the Work and at its own expense, do whatever \nis necessary to ensure that: \n \na) no Person, property, right, easement or privilege is injured, damaged or infringed \nby reason of the Contractor 's activities; \n \nb) fire and other property damage hazards in or about the Parking Facilities  are \neliminated; and \n \nc) the health and safety of all Persons employed in the performance of the Work is \nnot endangered by the method, manner or means of its performance. \n \n6.1.2 The VAA may direct the Contractor to do such things and to perform such additional Work \n--- PAGE 130 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 61 of 67 \n \nas the VAA considers reasonable and necessary to ensure compliance with or to remedy \nany breach of GC 6.1.1, and the Contractor will promptly comply at its own expense with \nany such VAA direction. \n \n6.1.3 In the event of any damage to Airport , VAA property , or the property of any Airport \ncustomer, by the Contractor, regardless of cause, the Contractor will give immediate \nwritten notice to the VAA; will conduct immediate investigations as to the cause and \nextent of the damage; and, will obtain statements from all Persons having knowledge of \nthe damage or the circumstances of the incident, exact statements of the duties of any \nemployees, officers or agents involved, copies of any reports made to the police or \ninsurers and any other information and material that the VAA may require. \n \nGC 6.2 LIABILITY FOR INJURY AND/OR DAMAGE \n \n6.2.1 The Contractor will be solely responsible for all claims, including costs of investigation and \ndefence by any party bringing a claim in respect of: \n \na) personal injury, or infringement of any personal or civil right; or \nb) damage to lands, buildings, structures, roads or property of any kind or \ndescription; or \nc) any infringement of any right, privilege , easement or statutory right of way \nwhatsoever; \n \noccasioned by the performance of the Work or any part of the Work, caused directly or \nindirectly by any act or omission, whether deliberate, negligent or purely accident al, of \nthe Contractor or occasioned by defective Work of the Contractor and the Contractor will \npromptly make good any claims, including costs of investigation and defence, \nimmediately upon demand being made. \n \n6.2.2 The VAA may: \n \na) direct the Contractor to do such things and to perform such additional Work as \nthe VAA considers reasonable and necessary to ensure compliance wit h or to \nremedy any breach of GC 6.2.1; and \n \nb) in the event the Contractor fails to make good any loss or damage for which it is \nliable within a reasonable time after being directed to do so by the VAA , the VAA \nmay cause the loss or damage to be made good, at the Contractor's cost and \nexpense. \n \n--- PAGE 131 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 62 of 67 \n \nGC 6.3  WORKERS' COMPENSATION \n \n6.3.1 The Contractor will fully comply with all requirements of the Workers' Compensation Act \nof British Columbia, R.S.B.C. 1996 c 492, as amended, (or any replacement statute). The \nContractor unconditionally guarantees to the VAA full compliance with the conditions, \nregulations and laws relating to Workers ' Compensation by the Contractor. \n \n6.3.2 Any penalties, fines, financial assessments and the like resulting from any failure on the \npart of the Contractor to comply with the provisions of the Workers'  Compensation Act \nwill be paid by the Con tractor when due . The Contractor agrees to indemnify and save \nharmless the VAA with respect thereto. \n \nGC 6.4 AIRPORT RULES \n \n6.4.1 In the performance of the Work, the Contractor will comply with all Airport rules, \ndirectives, and operating procedures relative to the performance of this Contract and \nmanagement and operation of the Airport, including, without limitation, those relating to \nsecurity, safety, fire, sanitation and traffic control, and the Contractor will promptly abide \nby all such rules, directives and operating procedures as established from time to time by \nthe VAA. \n  \n6.4.2 In particular, the Contractor, will fully comply with this Schedule E’s Part 9:·Airport Safety \nand Security Requirements. \n \nGC 6.5 NON-DISPARAGEMENT \n \n6.5.1 The Contractor will not, and will use commercially reasonable efforts to ensure that  any \nparty employed or contracted by the Contractor to perform the Work here at the Airport \nwill not, in any capacity or manner transmit, speak, write or otherwise communicate in \nany way (or cause, assist, solicit, encourage, support or participate in any of the \nforegoing), any comment, message, declaration, communication or other statement of \nany kind, whe ther verbal, written, transmitted electronically or otherwise, that might \nreasonably be construed to be  derogatory or negative towards, the VAA, or any of its \ndirectors, officers, subsidiaries, employees, agents or representatives. This provision will \nnot act to prohibit any person from making any statement or disclosure required to be \nmade in accordance with any applicable law, regulation or by-law. \n \nGC 6.6 TEMPORARY SUSPENSION OF WORK \n \n6.6.1 Without limiting or restricting the generality of any other provision of this Contract: \n--- PAGE 132 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 63 of 67 \n \n \na) in the event that the VAA  deems it necessary or expedient to suspend A irport \noperations, the Contractor  shall not have any c laims against the VAA , nor be \nentitled to any compensation or indemnity for any cause related to such \nsuspension; \nb) the Contractor shall not have nor make any claims against the VAA, unless caused \nby the gross negligence of the VAA , for  any costs or d amages which the \nContractor may sustain by reason of any temporary suspension, interruption or \ndiscontinuance, in whole or in part, from whatever cause arising in services \nsupplied by the VAA hereunder. \n \n \nPART 7 INDEMNIFICATION \n \nGC 7.1 INDEMNIFICATION BY CONTRACTOR \n \n7.1.1 The Contractor assumes the entire responsibility and liability for and will indemnify, \nprotect and hold harmless the VAA and the Crown from and against all liabilities, suits, \nactions, judicial or administrative proceedings, claims, demands, damages  , penalties, \nfines, costs and expenses of whatsoever kind or character (including but not limited to all \ncosts and fees for investigation and defence thereof) arising out of or alleged to have \narisen out of any act, or connected directly or indirectly with any act or omission of the \nContractor, whether accidental, negligent, or deliberate, under this Contract or the Work \nto be performed thereunder. Neither this indemnity, nor any action taken by the VAA to \nenforce this indemnity will restrict in any way the rights of the VAA to terminate this \nContract pursuant to GC 4.2, or to exercise its rights under GC 7.1.4. \n \n7.1.2 The Contractor will also indemnify the VAA from all costs, charges and expenses sustained \nor incurred by the VAA in or about all claims, actions , suits and proceedings arising from \nany alleged or actual intellectual property infringement arising out of the performance of \nthe Work or the Contractor's obligations under this Contract. \n \n7.1.3 The Contractor will further indemnify and save harmless the VAA and the Crown against \nall damages, losses and costs sustained or incurred by the VAA or the Crown resulting \nfrom any such default or breach. \n \n7.1.4 The Contractor further agrees that notwithstanding any statute or law to the contrary, \nthe exercise of the VAA's or the Crown's rights in the Contract will not prejudice any other \nrights or recourse of the VAA or the Crown at law, in equity or under this Contract. \n \n--- PAGE 133 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 64 of 67 \n \n7.1.5 All obligations of the Contractor arising pursuant to this GC 7.1 by reason of any matter \noccurring prior to termination of this Contract, will notwithstanding any provision of this \nContract or any law now or hereafter in force, continue in full force and effect until \ndischarged.  \n \nGC 7.2 DEFENCE OF ACTIONS \n \n7.2.1 On behalf of and in the name of the VAA, the Contractor will: \n \na) defend any and all suits against the VAA caused or alleged to have been caused \nby any act, failure to act, omission, fault or negligence of the Contractor in law, in \nequity or by this Contract, with respect to which the Contractor has agreed to \nindemnify the VAA, even if such suit is groundless, false or fraudulent; \nb) pay any judgment rendered in any such suit, including courts costs; and \nc) pay the fees and disbursements of counsel which the VAA may deem necessary \nor desirable to employ in connection therewith. \n \n7.2.2 The VAA will have the right, if it so elects, to take an active part in the defence of any such \nsuit, and to file intervention or other proceedings if it deems such action desirable. \n \n7.2.3 The Contractor will have the right to make settlement of any such suit as it may deem \nexpedient, provided however that if the Contractor fails to make settlement within thirty \n(30) Days after notice of the suit from the VAA and if the VAA believes in good faith that \nsuch failure will harm the VAA in its relations with the claimant or others, the VAA may \ngive the Contractor notice of such harm. If the Contractor, after such notice, fails to make \nsettlement within ten (10) Days, the VAA may make reasonable settlement with the \nclaimant and the Contractor will immediately reimburse the VAA for such portion of the \nsettlement as the VAA in its sole discretion designates as the Contractor's share. \n \nGC 7.3  INDEMNIFICATION BY THE VAA \n \n7.3.1 The VAA will indemnify and save the Contractor harmless from and against all claims, \ndemands, losses, costs, damages, actions, suits or proceedings arising out of this Contract \nthat are directly attributable to: \n \na) negligent acts or wilful misconduct of the VAA; and \nb) intellectual property infringement by the Contractor employing a model, plan, \nspecifications, design or any other thing related to the Work that was supplied to \nthe Contractor by the VAA. \n \n--- PAGE 134 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 65 of 67 \n \nGC 7.4 LIMITATIONS OF LIABILITY \n \n7.4.1 Neither the VAA nor the Crown will be responsible or liable to the Contractor for any loss, \ninjury or property damage suffered by the Contractor or other Person and caused by or \nin relation to: \n \na) the provision of any temporary interruption, suspension, discontinuance or \nfailure to provide any utilities by the VAA; \nb) other contractors , occupants or other Persons for whom the VAA is not \nresponsible at law; \nc) theft of property of the Contractor; \nd) theft of Monies collected by the Contractor and held in trust for the VAA; \ne) any damage or loss insured or required to be insured by the Contractor under this \nContract; and \nf) any act or omission by the VAA in curing or attempting to cure any default or \nbreach of the Contractor under this Contract. \n \n7.4.2 The Contractor hereby expressly assumes the risk in respect of the matters set out in GC \n7.4.1, and agrees to indemnify and hold harmless the VAA and the Crown with respect \nthereto and releases the VAA and the Crown from any liability in respect thereof. \n \n \nPART 8 MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS \n \nGC 8.1 LAWS, RULES, PERMITS AND FEES \n \n8.1.1 Unless otherwise stated in this Contract, the Contractor will be responsible for obtaining \nsuch licenses, permits or approvals from Federal, Provincial, Municipal or other \nGovernment Authorities, as may be necessary to enable the Contractor to perform the \nWork required under this Contract. \n \n8.1.2 The Contractor will comply with all laws and regulations relating to the performance of \nthe Work, including environmental protection, whether federal, provincial, municipal or \nlocal. The Contractor will also comply and conform to the requirements of such provincial \nand municipal codes, regulations, and bylaws of general application, which are designed \nto secure the health, safety,  convenience and welfare of the inhabitants or occupiers of \nbuildings and structures as if the Airport were a property othe r than a federal public \nproperty. Where more than one law or regulation applies, the more stringent provision \nwill apply. \n \n--- PAGE 135 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 66 of 67 \n \n8.1.3 All appropriate and/or required permits will be displayed at the Parking Facilities. \n \nPART 9 AIRPORT SAFETY AND SECURITY REQUIREMENTS \n \nGC 9.1 GENERAL PROTECTION \n \n9.1.1 The Contractor will: \n \na) not disrupt or impede Airport business at any time except as permitted by the \nVAA;  \n \nb) furnish temporary protection, as and when required, for the safety and safe \nhandling of all pedestrians and vehicles using the Parking Facilities; \n \nc) collect and secure all Monies accumulated from the operation of the Parking \nFacilities;  \n \nd) not conduct any operation or install any equipment on the Parking Facilities that \nwill cause electronic interference or hazard to the navigation of aircraft.  Upon \nreceiving notice from the VAA of any interference or hazard, the Contractor shall \nat its own expense immediately take all steps, as may be necessary, to remove \nthe interference or hazard to the satisfaction of the VAA;  \n \ne) not bring onto or store at the Parking Facilities or Airport any goods of an \nexplosive, dangerous, inflammable or noxious nature except with the prior \nwritten consent of the VAA; and \n \nf) contact the YYJ Security Operations Center (SOC) at the beginning and end of each \nworkday, to enhance communication.  \n \n9.1.2 The Contractor acknowledges that occupation and use of the Airport Lands is subject at \nall times to the provisions of the Aeronautics Act , the Canadian Aviation Security \nRegulations and all security measures and orders issued in accordance with the same. The \nContractor covenants and agrees that it will at all times comply with all Airport security \nrules, orders, directions or measures issued or implemented by the VAA at any time and \nfrom time to time, including without limitation those rules, orders, directions or measures \nrelating directly or indirectly to the use of restricted area passes, escorts, personnel \nidentification systems and the implementation of other security clearance procedures. \n \n \n--- PAGE 136 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 67 of 67 \n \nGC 9.2 KEYS \n \n9.2.1 The VAA will provide to the Contractor a sufficient number of keys as may be required for \nuse by the Contractor’s personnel to access the Parking Equipment, and the buildings and \nbooths in the Parking Facilities. Key holders will be subject to the following conditions of \nissue: \n \na) all keys to the Parking Facilities and the Parking Equipment are the sole property \nof the VAA; \n \nb) keys will not be duplicated without the express authorization of the VAA; \n \nc) keys must be safeguarded at all times and any loss or theft will be  immediately \nreported to the VAA; and \n \nd) keys will be surrendered to the VAA immediately upon termination or expiration \nof this Contract, or when there is no further requirement for them. ", :analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Personnel**\n*   **Method and Manner:** Contractor is solely responsible for the method and manner of performing the Work (GC 1.8.3).\n*   **Contract Manager Management:** Must designate a Contract Manager within **ten (10) days** of signing or before starting work. Substitution requires prior advice to VAA. Removal and replacement must occur if VAA deems the manager unsuitable (GC 3.1.1–3.1.3).\n*   **Standards of Performance:** Work must be performed in a \"careful and workmanlike manner\" to the \"full and complete satisfaction\" of the VAA (GC 3.2.2).\n*   **Instruction Compliance:** Must promptly follow additional instructions issued by the VAA during performance (GC 2.1.1) and adhere to VAA decisions regarding contract interpretations (GC 2.4.2).\n\n**Compliance & Legal**\n*   **VAA Policies:** Must comply with VAA policies, security measures, safety laws, and environmental regulations (GC 1.8.3a).\n*   **Confidentiality:** Strict maintenance of confidentiality regarding VAA business, inventions, or secure data before, during, and after the contract term (GC 2.2.1).\n*   **Joint and Several Liability:** If the Contractor consists of multiple entities, they are jointly and severally liable (GC 1.10.1).\n\n**Reporting & Notification**\n*   **Labour Disputes:** Immediate notification of any current or threatened labour dispute. A full report is required within **eight (8) hours** of commencement (GC 3.3.2a, c).\n*   **Subcontractor Disclosure:** Must advise VAA in writing of intended subcontractors/suppliers within **ten (10) days** of contract signing (GC 3.4.1).\n\n**Assets & Intellectual Property (IP)**\n*   **Provision of Materials:** Contractor must provide all labor, materials, and services for complete performance (GC 1.9.1). All materials must be new and of merchantable quality (GC 3.2.3).\n*   **Property Return:** All VAA documentation/property must be returned immediately upon request or termination (GC 2.5.1).\n*   **IP Transfer:** Must transfer any produced IP to the VAA and cooperate in its defense/assertion (GC 2.5.3–2.5.4).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Self-Help Remedy (Cost Transfer):** If the Contractor fails to promptly resolve deficiencies or defects identified by VAA, the VAA may fix the problem themselves at the **Contractor’s cost and expense** (GC 2.3.3).\n*   **Contract Suspension/Termination:** If a labour dispute causes an interruption exceeding **seven (7) consecutive days**, VAA may suspend or terminate the contract immediately (GC 3.3.2 - Final Paragraph).\n*   **Forced Personnel Replacement:** VAA has the \"sole opinion\" right to force the replacement of the Contract Manager (GC 3.1.3).\n*   **Non-Waiver:** A waiver of one default does not prevent VAA from enforcing rights on subsequent defaults (GC 1.15.1).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **\"Sole Opinion\" Discretion:** The VAA holds broad discretionary power to determine if work is deficient (GC 2.3.2), if a Contract Manager is unsuitable (GC 3.1.3), or if produced documentation has IP value (GC 2.5.2). This creates risk of subjective enforcement.\n*   **Finality of VAA Decisions:** Questions regarding the Scope of Work or contract requirements are decided by the VAA, whose decision is \"final, binding and conclusive\" (though subject to arbitration) (GC 2.4.1).\n*   **Time of the Essence:** Every reference to time is a \"condition\" of the contract (GC 1.14.1), meaning even minor delays could technically be treated as material breaches.\n*   **Survival of Obligations:** Obligations survive the expiry or termination of the contract, potentially leading to long-term liabilities (GC 1.13.1).\n*   **Work Continuity Requirement:** In the event of labor disputes, the Contractor is obligated to help find and arrange for **substitute parking management providers** to ensure continuity (GC 3.3.2e), which could be operationally and financially burdensome during a strike.\n*   **Warranty Risks:** The Contractor provides an express warranty that all materials are new and fit for purpose, extending liability to the quality of goods used in performance (GC 3.2.3).", :risk-matrix "| Obligation Category | Risk Level | Justification (Difficulty vs. Severity) |\n| :--- | :---: | :--- |\n| **Fixed Management Fee** | **HIGH** | **Difficulty:** High. Must cover unpredictable snow/ice costs, seasonal shuttle spikes (Dec-Jan), and labor fuel. **Severity:** Extreme. No fee escalators for 5-7 years; unionization costs cannot be passed to VAA. |\n| **Revenue Liability (Theft)** | **HIGH** | **Difficulty:** Medium. Requires perfect internal controls across cash/electronic. **Severity:** High. Contractor is the \"insurer\"; stolen funds must be replaced out-of-pocket as \"Gross Revenue.\" |\n| **Bilingual Service** | **MEDIUM** | **Difficulty:** High. Recruiting/retaining bilingual staff for *every shift* 24/7 is a localized labor market challenge in BC. **Severity:** Medium. Non-compliance is a breach of the Official Languages Act. |\n| **Late Payment Interest** | **HIGH** | **Difficulty:** Low (administrative). **Severity:** Extreme. At ~27% annualized, even small delays in remitting large parking revenues create massive financial erosion. |\n| **Environmental Remediation** | **MEDIUM** | **Difficulty:** Low (standard ops). **Severity:** High. Broad indemnity remains the Contractor's property/responsibility even if pollutants \"affix to land.\" |\n| **Non-Competition (10km)** | **LOW** | **Difficulty:** Low. **Severity:** Medium. Restricts regional expansion but is geographically contained to the Saanich Peninsula. |", :extracted_data [{:analysis "### 1) Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational Obligations**\n*   **Facility Management:** The Operator must operate, manage, and administer four specific parking lots totaling 3,243 spaces, plus seasonal overflow areas (Section 1.3).\n*   **Curbside Management:** Develop and implement a \"Curb Management Program\" to monitor and manage traffic flow at the terminal frontage and the short-term lot commercial lane (Definitions; Section 1.3).\n*   **Staffing/Service:** Provide specialized \"Curb Management Officers\" (Definitions).\n*   **Standards Adherence:** Must meet \"Quality Standards\" as defined in Schedule 8 (Definitions).\n*   **Availability:** Operations must serve the airport 24 hours a day, seven days a week (Section 1.1).\n\n**Financial Obligations**\n*   **Revenue Collection:** Manage all forms of payment (cash, credit, debit, electronic) and account for \"Sales Tax\" to provincial or federal authorities (Definitions).\n\n**Timeline Obligations**\n*   **RFP Submission Deadline:** Monday, March 31, 2025, at 2:00 pm PST (Page 1).\n*   **Contract Term:** Initial five-year term from June 1, 2025, to May 31, 2030 (Section 1.4).\n\n### 2) Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Disqualification/Non-Consideration:** Failure to meet \"Must,\" \"mandatory,\" \"required,\" or \"shall\" criteria results in the proposal failing to receive or continue to receive consideration (Definitions).\n*   **Reserved Rights:** The Authority reserves the right to waive minor non-compliance for one proponent without being obligated to do so for others (Section 1.5).\n\n### 3) Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Operational Uncertainty (Terminal Expansion):** A forthcoming terminal expansion project is expected to impact parking, but specifics are currently \"uncertain\" (Section 1.2). The Operator must manage this impact as the configuration evolves.\n*   **Asset Valuation:** Future financial calculations may involve \"Net Book Value\" (NBV), which accounts for depreciation and impairment, potentially affecting financial settlements regarding assets (Definitions).\n*   **Authority Discretion:** The 2-year contract renewal is at the \"sole discretion of the Authority,\" providing no guarantee of extension beyond the initial 5 years (Section 1.4).\n*   **Definition of Revenue:** The definition is broad, including \"any other form of legal payment,\" placing high accountability on the Operator for all transaction types (Definitions)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Wage Requirements:** Must pay employees greater than the BC provincial minimum wage plus benefits (Section 1.6-A).\n*   **Marketing Budget:** Expected to budget 0.5% of public parking revenues toward marketing initiatives (Section 1.6-J).\n*   **Revenue Remittance:** All collected revenues and sales taxes must be forwarded to the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) no later than the 5th business day of the following month (Section 1.6-G.1).\n*   **Banking:** Collected revenue must be deposited into the proponent’s bank account at least once weekly (Section 1.6-G.1).\n*   **Training Costs:** All training, including WorldHost and technical training, is to be provided at the Proponent’s expense (Section 1.6-B).\n*   **Uniforms:** Supply all employees with Authority-approved uniforms (Section 1.6-A).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Staffing Levels:** \n    *   Lot 1 booth: Minimum 20 hours/day, 7 days/week (Section 1.6-A).\n    *   Curb Management Officer: Minimum 15.5 hours/day, 7 days/week (Section 1.6-A).\n*   **Curbside Management:** Must develop and implement a Curbside Management Program (Section 1.6).\n*   **Maintenance:** Responsibility for ice control and snow removal in areas depicted in Appendix C, and routine trash pickup in lots (Section 1.6 & 1.6-A).\n*   **Facility Use:** Authority-provided buildings and equipment must be used exclusively for parking operations unless written approval is granted (Section 1.6-H).\n\n**Compliance & Training Obligations:**\n*   **Training Minima:** Minimum 12 hours of \"on the job\" training prior to field placement; specific training required for accessibility (Sunflower Program), security (Landside ID), and customer service (WorldHost) (Section 1.6-B).\n*   **Health & Safety:** Compliance with all Work Safe BC and Occupational Health and Safety rules; maintenance of a private Health and Safety Program (Section 1.6-F).\n*   **Language:** All marketing must be in both official languages (English and French). Staff must be fluent in spoken and written English (Sections 1.6-A & 1.6-J).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Monthly Reconciliation:** Due by the 5th business day of the following month, including revenues, sales taxes, and credit card fees (Section 1.6-G.2).\n*   **Statistical Reporting:** Assume responsibility for daily occupancy and passage reports (Section 1.6-I).\n*   **Weekly Statements:** Weekly Statement of Account detailing all revenues earned by type and lot (Section 1.6-G.2).\n\n**Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **Local Office:** Established within two (2) months of Contract award (Section 1.6-A).\n*   **Manager Resume:** Provided before the Contract start date of June 1, 2025 (Section 1.6-A).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Proponent/Award Rejection:** The Authority reserves the right to cancel the RFP in whole or in part at any time without award or liability (Section 1.5).\n*   **Audit Intervention:** The Authority reserves the right to perform unannounced audits of staff records, performance, customer service levels, and financial/payroll records at any time (Section 1.6-G.3).\n*   **Regulatory Scrutiny:** Records of training must be maintainted for audits conducted by the Canadian Transportation Agency (CTA) (Section 1.6-B).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Financial Liability for Revenue:** The Proponent accepts full responsibility for all Revenues collected on behalf of the Authority, including the security and banking of those funds (Section 1.6-E & G.1).\n*   **Tort Liability:** The Proponent accepts responsibility for incidents of property damage and injury that occur within their areas of responsibility (Section 1.6-E).\n*   **Unpredictable Staffing Demands:** The obligation to bring in additional trained staff during \"unpredictable\" peak periods and overflow situations creates a risk of unbudgeted labor costs (Section 1.6-A).\n*   **Operational Risk (Weather):** The requirement for ice control and snow removal implies liability for slip-and-fall incidents and operational continuity during winter events (Section 1.6).\n*   **Health & Safety Costs:** The Proponent must maintain its own Occupational Health and Safety Program at its \"own expense\" (Section 1.6-F.2)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Revenue Management:** Responsibility for all financial aspects of managing programs, including invoicing, payment processing, and collection of outstanding fees (Section L).\n*   **Infrastructure Capital:** Infrastructure spending for \"new services\" (e.g., Valet or Shuttles) must be borne by the Contractor initially, then charged back to VAA under mutually agreed terms (Section L).\n*   **Transition Costs:** All costs associated with establishing operations in the Parking Facilities are the \"sole responsibility of the successful Proponent\" and cannot be passed to the Authority (Section M).\n*   **Presentation Costs:** Any required onsite oral presentations are at the Proponent's cost (Section 1.8).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Innovation:** Bidders must proactively present creative solutions and emerging trends throughout the term (Section L).\n*   **Staffing:** Proponents must demonstrate effective methods for recruiting and retaining staff, as well as staff compensation and training programs (Section 1.7).\n*   **Transition Plan:** Must include a comprehensive plan for assuming operations; incumbent bidders must address implementing new requirements (Section M).\n*   **Site Visit Requirements:** Mandatory attendance at pre-bid meeting requires specific PPE: CSA-certified High-visibility vests and flat footwear (Section 2.3).\n\n**Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Legal & Safety:** Proponents must be knowledgeable of all relevant laws, licensing/permit requirements, and specifically CCOHS safety standards (Section 2.6, 1.7).\n*   **Eligibility:** Must have been in the parking management business for at least five (5) years prior to June 1st, 2025 (Section 2.1).\n\n**Timeline Obligations (Section 2.7):**\n*   **Receipt Confirmation Form:** Due February 20th, 2025, 2:00 pm PST.\n*   **Mandatory Pre-Bid Meeting:** February 27th, 2025, 1:30 pm PST.\n*   **Proposal Submission:** March 31st, 2025, 2:00 pm PST.\n*   **Bid Validity:** Proposals must remain valid for 60 days post-closing (Section 2.8).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Exclusion from Bidding:** Companies that do not attend the **mandatory** pre-bid site meeting and tour will be excluded from bidding (Section 2.3).\n*   **Disqualification of Proposal:** Proposals received after the closing date/time (March 31, 2025, 2:00 pm PST) will not be accepted (Section 2.6).\n*   **Rejection of Format:** Hand-written Proposals, or those sent via facsimile or email, will not be accepted (Section 2.6).\n*   **Loss of Information:** Failure to submit the Receipt Confirmation Form by the deadline results in not receiving mandatory site tour instructions or addenda (Schedule One/Section 2.8).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Transition Cost Absorption:** The provision in Section M explicitly forbids passing establishment costs to the Authority, creating a potential \"sunk cost\" for the winner.\n*   **Incomplete Information Risk:** The Authority disclaims all responsibility for communications or representations made by anyone other than the Authority’s Representative (Section 2.5).\n*   **Broad Evaluation Discretion:** The Authority states it is \"not to be limited as to its criteria for evaluation\" and looks for \"most advantageous\" rather than strictly lowest price (Section 1.7).\n*   **Written Commitment of Oral Presentations:** Any information provided during optional onsite presentations may be required to be confirmed in writing, at which point it becomes a binding part of the Proposal (Section 1.8).\n*   **Infrastructure Funding:** While \"charge backs\" are mentioned for infrastructure, they are subject to \"mutually agreed upon\" business terms, creating risk if an agreement on those terms cannot be reached after the Contractor has identified the need (Section L)."} {:analysis "### 1) Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Proposal Costs:** The Proponent is 100% responsible for all costs associated with the proposal, including travel to YYJ for mandatory pre-bid meetings, site tours, information gathering, and presentations (Section 2.9).\n*   **Financial Proposal:** Completion and submission of the Financial Proposal Form (Schedule Five) in Excel format.\n\n**Operational/Submission Obligations:**\n*   **Formatting:** Responses must follow the exact sequence, headings, and numbering indicated in the Proposal Response Document (Schedule Four).\n*   **Company Profile:** Must list officers, board of directors, affiliations, and/or partnerships (Schedule Three).\n*   **Partnering/Subcontracting:**\n    *   Partners must sign the signatory page and provide company profiles (Section 2.15).\n    *   Proposals must detail how partnerships will function in service delivery (Section 2.15).\n    *   If subcontracting, one Proponent must assume \"primary responsibility\" for the scope of work and statutory obligations (e.g., Worker’s Compensation Act) (Section 2.15).\n*   **Addenda Management:** Proponents must submit a \"Receipt Confirmation Form\" (Appendix A) to receive addenda and are solely responsible for ensuring all addenda are received before submission (Section 2.12).\n*   **Investigation:** Proponents must permit and cooperate with VAA investigations into their business experience, financial capability, and business practices (Section 2.23).\n\n**Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Conflict of Interest:** Mandatory disclosure of any relationship with VAA employees, officers, or directors (Section 2.17).\n*   **No Collusion:** Mandatory declaration/warranty that the proposal was developed without communication or comparison of figures with other proponents (Section 2.16).\n*   **Electronic Integrity:** Proponents are prohibited from electronically altering the RFP text except to add requested information (Section 2.24).\n\n---\n\n### 2) Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Disqualification for Alteration:** Electronically altering the RFP document (other than filling in fields) will \"invalidate the Proponent’s Proposal\" (Section 2.24).\n*   **Contract Termination:** Failure to disclose, or providing false/insufficient disclosure of a relationship with a VAA official, is grounds for contract termination \"in the Authority’s sole discretion without further liability or notice\" (Section 2.17).\n*   **Rejection of Proposal:**\n    *   Failure to conform to instructions or adding qualifying conditions may lead to disqualification (Section 2.19).\n    *   Withdrawals are only valid if done in writing prior to the closing date; otherwise, the proposal stands (Section 2.11).\n*   **Past Performance Impact:** VAA reserves the right to use past performance and compliance on other agreements as a basis for evaluation (Section 2.18).\n\n---\n\n### 3) Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Broad Waiver of Liability:** By submitting, the Proponent waives any claim for damages for proposal costs and \"waives any claim for loss of profits if no Contract is made\" (Section 2.22).\n*   **Sole Responsibility for Interpretation:** The Proponent is \"solely responsible\" for errors or misunderstandings resulting from a failure to examine the RFP or inquire about discrepancies (Section 2.13).\n*   **Ownership of Intellectual Property:** All proposals and supporting material become the property of VAA upon submission (Section 2.10).\n*   **Statutory Liability:** For partnerships or subcontracts, the primary Proponent remains responsible for all \"statutory obligations under the Worker’s Compensation Act, etc.\" (Section 2.15).\n*   **Unilateral Rights of VAA:** Section 2.18 gives the Authority the right to negotiate with multiple proponents concurrently without offering modified terms to others and the right to reject all proposals without liability.\n*   **Disclaimer of Data Accuracy:** VAA provides RFP files \"as is\" and accepts no responsibility for system damage or inaccuracies in electronic transmissions (Section 2.25, 2.26)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**A. Timeline Obligations**\n*   **Intent to Submit:** Proponents must submit \"Schedule One - Receipt Confirmation Form\" by **February 20th, 2025** (Schedule One, Schedule Two).\n*   **Mandatory Attendance:** Attendance is required at the pre-bid meeting and site tour on **Thursday, February 27th, 2025, at 1:30 pm** (Schedule One).\n*   **Proposal Submission:** All required schedules (Two through Seven) must be submitted by **March 31st, 2025** (Schedule Two).\n*   **Contract Finalization:** A contract must be concluded within **thirty (30) business days** from official notification of award (Section 3.3).\n*   **Proposal Validity:** The proposal and financial details must remain valid for **90 days** from the RFP closing date (Schedule Four, Section 1).\n\n**B. Operational Obligations**\n*   **Staffing:** Proponents must provide continuous service by staffing parking facilities on a **full-time basis**, covering all arriving and departing flights (Section 3.10).\n*   **Licensing:** The Proponent is responsible for obtaining and maintaining all permits, licenses, and approvals required by federal, provincial, and municipal agencies (Section 3.9).\n*   **Financial Proof:** Proponents must provide a statement indicating the source and amount of funds available for operation and include bank references (Schedule Three, Section 3).\n\n**C. Compliance Obligations**\n*   **Legal:** Must comply with all applicable federal, provincial, and local laws, including WorkSafe BC, health and safety codes, and electrical/building codes (Section 3.7).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Forfeiture of Opportunity:** Failure to conclude a contract within 30 business days of award notification results in the forfeiture of the opportunity (Section 3.3).\n*   **Termination of Negotiations:** The Authority may terminate negotiations without any compensation to the Proponent if an agreement cannot be reached (Section 3.3).\n*   **Rejection of Proposal:**\n    *   Proposals that do not include all documents listed in the Submission Checklist (Schedules 1-7) will be considered incomplete and may be rejected (Schedule Two).\n    *   Failure to meet the \"Minimum Information\" requirements in Schedule Four will result in the proposal being considered incomplete (Schedule Four).\n*   **Right to Re-negotiate:** The Authority reserves the right to reject all proposals and re-advertise or negotiate with any proponent after cancellation (Section 3.4).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Non-Exclusivity:** The Authority explicitly states it will **not** enter into an exclusive contract and reserves the right to enter into other contracts for similar services at its discretion during the term (Section 3.8).\n*   **No Compensation for Failed Negotiations:** Proponents bear the risk of all costs associated with negotiation; the Authority is not liable for compensation if negotiations are terminated (Section 3.3).\n*   **No Contractual Obligation:** The Authority has no obligation to any Proponent until a written contract is duly executed; oral or preliminary signals do not constitute a contract (Section 3.5).\n*   **Incorporation of Proposal:** All or part of the bidder's proposal may be incorporated into the final contract, meaning any \"sales\" promises made in the bid become legally binding obligations (Section 3.3).\n*   **Operational Risk (Staffing):** The requirement to cover all flights on a \"full-time basis\" could result in high labor costs if flight delays or schedules extend beyond standard hours (Section 3.10)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Irrevocable Letter of Credit (ILOC):** Successful proponents must provide an ILOC equal to **5% of the total Fixed Management Fee** for the Initial Term (Section 4).\n*   **Marketing Budget:** The contractor is expected to budget **0.5% of public parking-related Revenue** specifically for marketing strategies (Section 9 - Marketing Program).\n*   **Transition Costs:** Any costs associated with establishing operations are the **sole responsibility of the proponent** and cannot be passed to the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) (Section 11).\n*   **Permit Management:** Assumption of responsibility for invoicing and payments for employee, commuter, and monthly parking permits (Section 9 - YYJ Parking Permit Programs).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Staffing:** Must identify a specific individual responsible for YYJ operations with a statement of work, providing 24/7 contact details. Must provide a proposed schedule of salaries, wages, and benefits (Section 2 & 9).\n*   **Shuttle Service:** Mandatory provision during peak periods (e.g., Thanksgiving and Christmas), specifically from **December 22nd through January 15th**, between **4:00 AM and approx. 1:00 AM** (Section 9 & 10).\n*   **Maintenance:** Responsibility for ice control and snow removal included in the Fixed Management Fee (Section 10).\n*   **Curbside Management:** Requirement to develop and implement a Curbside Management Program (Section 9).\n\n**Compliance & Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **WorkSafe BC:** Written proof of registration and good standing is required before the **June 1st, 2025** contract commencement (Section 6).\n*   **Official Languages Act:** Requirement to meet the standards of the Act in service delivery (Section 9).\n*   **Statistical Reporting:** Must provide accurate/timely statistics including daily occupancy and passage reports (Section 9).\n*   **Audit:** Must employ a sophisticated financial reporting system that separates income sources and allows for VAA audits (Section 10).\n\n**Timeline:**\n*   **Contract Commencement:** June 1, 2025 (Section 6).\n*   **Peak Shuttle Dates:** December 22 – January 15 annually (Section 10).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Disqualification/Rejection:** Failure to provide the \"Letter of Surety and Undertaking\" for the ILOC (Section 4) or the \"Letter of Insurability\" (Section 5) during the proposal stage may render the bid non-compliant.\n*   **Delayed Commencement:** Failure to provide WorkSafe BC proof of good standing before June 1, 2025, may prevent the legal commencement of the contract (Section 6).\n*   **Audit Rights:** VAA maintains the \"right of audit\" to verify internal controls and financial reporting; discrepancies found here typically lead to financial reconciliation or default under the \"Draft Contract - Appendix H\" referenced in the text (Section 10).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Fixed Fee Risk:** The pricing is \"primarily based on a Fixed Management Fee\" which must cover unpredictable costs like **snow removal, ice control, and seasonal shuttle services**. Heavy winters or increased shuttle demand would erode profit margins (Section 10).\n*   **Revenue Collection Liability:** The proponent is responsible for the \"handling, picking up, reconciling and depositing of monies.\" The requirement for \"internal process controls\" suggests the proponent bears the risk of loss or theft of cash/negotiables before deposit (Section 10).\n*   **Equipment Evaluation:** Proponents must review existing Skidata and Flowbird equipment. There is a risk in recommending enhancements or replacements, as the Net Book Value is noted, implying potential financial implications if existing infrastructure is mismanaged (Section 9).\n*   **Indigenous Engagement:** While phrased as an \"opportunity,\" the requirement to identify skills training and employment for Indigenous businesses is a qualitative evaluation factor that could impact scoring (Section 9)."} {:analysis "Based on the provided RFP section for the 2025 Parking Management Services at Victoria International Airport (YYJ), the following concrete obligations, penalties, and risks have been identified:\n\n### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Information Management:** The bidder must complete and maintain \"Schedule Seven: New Party Contact Information Form,\" identifying key personnel for legal, financial/accounting, on-site management, and other roles (Page 36).\n*   **Equipment Monitoring:** The Contractor is explicitly responsible for monitoring all parking equipment (SKIDATA, FLOWBIRD, and Hesion LPR systems) and reporting any observed conditions requiring maintenance to the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) (Appendix D, Page 42).\n*   **Snow and Ice Control:** The Contractor is responsible for snow removal and ice control across approximately 95,000m² of designated parking areas, including all public and employee lots (Appendix C, Page 41).\n*   **Scope of Facilities:** Management of 2,686 total public stalls across Lot 1 (1,405) and Lot 2 (1,281), plus employee and short-term lots (Page 38).\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Rate Adherence:** The Contractor must implement and manage the specific rate structure effective March 1, 2025, including:\n    *   Short-term: $4.00 flat fee for 2 hours.\n    *   Daily: $1.00 per half hour, max $18.00/day for the first 5 days, $9.00/day thereafter.\n    *   Monthly: $200.00 + GST.\n    *   Employee/Commuter: $540/year or $30/month (Appendix B, Page 39).\n*   **Invoicing:** The Contractor is responsible for monthly invoicing of employee parking to respective employers (Appendix B, Page 39).\n*   **Payment Collection:** Must support multiple payment methods including Cash, Credit, Google Pay, Apple Pay, ParkedIn Mobile App, and Credit Card Tap In/Out (Appendix B, Page 39).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Facility Reporting:** The Contractor must generate and process various reports, including \"Purchases\" and \"Active Filter\" reports detailing transaction dates, local amounts, and payment methods (Appendix E, Pages 53-54).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Maintenance Liability (Implicit):** While Appendix D states the VAA is responsible for repairs, the Contractor’s failure to \"monitor\" and \"report\" conditions (Appendix D, Page 42) could lead to liability for equipment degradation or operational downtime if issues were observable but not reported.\n*   *Note: This specific chunk focuses heavily on Appendices (Maps and Equipment lists); explicit liquidated damages or penalty clauses are likely contained in the \"General Terms\" or \"Main Agreement\" sections of the RFP not included in this text.*\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Legacy Equipment Integration:** The Contractor must manage a multi-vendor environment (SKIDATA from 2020 and FLOWBIRD from 2023) using Hesion LPR software. System fragmentation increases the risk of technical glitches and reporting errors.\n*   **High-Value Assets:** The Contractor is monitoring equipment with a Net Book Value (NBV) of ~$1.54 million ($1.47M long-term + $71K short-term) (Appendix D, Page 42).\n*   **Snow Removal Exposure:** The requirement for ice control in high-traffic airport lots (95,000m²+) represents a significant operational liability regarding slip-and-fall claims and vehicle accidents during winter events (Appendix C).\n*   **Revenue Collection Complexity:** Managing diverse rate structures (flat fees, sliding daily scales, and annual pre-payments) across multiple payment platforms (Cash to Apple Pay) poses an audit and reconciliation risk."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational/Planning Obligations:**\n*   **Independent Forecast Validation:** Proponents are explicitly obligated to interpret the provided passenger statistics and forecasts with their own expectations. The RFP states that proponents must understand the \"Authority assumes no responsibility for any deviations from the forecasts suggested\" (Page 58).\n*   **Operational Tailoring:** Proponents must account for significant traffic seasonality in their operational planning, specifically preparing for peak levels in August and lowest levels in February (Page 60).\n*   **Schedule Alignment:** The bidder must align management services with the specific flight activity of primary carriers (WestJet and Air Canada, representing 78% of seat capacity) as well as smaller regional and charter carriers (Page 60).\n*   **Data Utilization:** Proponents are expected to utilize the detailed granular data (hourly lot entrances/exits and occupancy samples provided on pages 56–57) to model their 2025 staffing and management strategies.\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Risk Assumption (Financial Consequence):** There is no explicit \"clause citation\" for a fine; however, the **Disclaimer of Liability (Page 60)** functions as a fiscal penalty mechanism. If a bidder relies solely on VAA's data and that data proves inaccurate, the bidder bears 100% of the financial consequences of resulting staffing inefficiencies or revenue shortfalls.\n*   **Accuracy Waiver:** The Authority provides a \"Disclaimer of Liability\" stating it \"assumes no responsibility or liability whether direct or indirect... for any consequence of [the statistics'] use\" (Page 60). This implies that a bidder cannot seek damages or contract adjustments based on faulty data provided in the RFP.\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Forecasting Risk:** The Authority provides a 5-year forecast showing steady growth (e.g., 6.3% in 2025, 6.2% in 2026), but explicitly disclaims the accuracy of these numbers. Proponents face the risk of over-capitalizing on equipment or over-staffing based on these optimistic estimates.\n*   **Volatility Risk:** The data highlights extreme historical volatility due to external factors (Covid-19 restrictions noted on Page 58), showing transborder travel dropping from 31,292 to 2,939 in one year. The bidder carries the risk of future sudden shifts in airline routes or international travel restrictions.\n*   **Concentration Risk:** With 78% of capacity held by just two carriers (WestJet and Air Canada), the operator's revenue and operational flow are highly sensitive to the business decisions or labor disputes of those specific airlines.\n*   **Data Reliability Gap:** The occupancy and entrance/exit data provided (Pages 56-57) is a specific snapshot (Dec 9–Dec 31, 2024). Bidders risk \"recency bias\" if they do not account for the fact that this is winter data, whereas the text notes August is the peak season."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Data Accuracy & Verification:** The bidder must account for the fact that airport traffic statistics (Local Movements) currently provided are **estimates** because they are no longer available locally from the Air Traffic Control Tower (Page 63). \n*   **Reporting Lag:** The bidder must reconcile operational data with Statistics Canada actuals, which can have a reporting lag of up to **6 months** (Page 63).\n*   **Service Level Alignment:** The parking management service must be designed to accommodate specific passenger demographics and behaviors (Page 64):\n    *   **Peak Volume Readiness:** Preparing for a total annual passenger volume that reached **1,872,033** in 2024 (a 7.4% increase).\n    *   **Arrival Window Management:** Staffing and throughput must handle the fact that **62%** of passengers arrive between 60 minutes and 3 hours before departure.\n    *   **Mode of Transport:** Only **40%** of passengers currently use parking; the bidder has an implied obligation to maintain or improve this capture rate despite **36%** of passengers being dropped off by private cars and **21%** using taxis, limos, or ridesharing.\n*   **Customer Experience Focus:** The bidder must address Top 5 passenger priorities, specifically **\"Ease of getting to the airport\"** (ranked #2 at 31%) and **\"Ease of finding your way\"** (ranked #5 at 20%) within the context of parking facilities (Page 64).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   *Note: The provided text contains statistical data and demographic results rather than contractual legal clauses. Specific financial penalties ($) or formal clause citations (e.g., \"Section X.X\") for performance failures are not present in this specific chunk.*\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Market Share Risk (The \"Uber/Lyft\" Factor):** 36% of passengers are \"dropped off\" and 21% use taxis/ridesharing/shuttles. This high percentage of non-parking arrivals represents a significant revenue risk for a parking manager whose fees may be tied to occupancy or throughput.\n*   **Operational Planning Uncertainty:** Because aircraft movement stats for \"Local Movements\" are estimates (due to lack of tower data) and actuals from Statistics Canada take 6 months to arrive, the bidder faces a risk of **misallocating labor/resources** based on delayed or inaccurate traffic data.\n*   **Declining Aircraft Movements:** While passenger numbers are up 7.4%, **Total Aircraft Movements decreased by 11.8%** in 2024 (Page 63). This suggests larger aircraft or higher load factors, which results in \"burstier\" traffic—sharp peaks of parking demand followed by long lulls, making efficient staffing difficult.\n*   **Confidentiality Liability:** The 2024 ASQ results (Page 64) are explicitly marked **\"Confidential – Not for Distribution.\"** Any unauthorized disclosure by the bidder during the RFP process or subsequent contract could result in disqualification or legal liability.\n*   **Demographic Sensitivity:** 61% of travelers are over the age of 45, and 40% are over 55. This suggests a need for high-functioning, accessible parking infrastructure; failure to provide ease of use for an aging demographic could lead to poor satisfaction scores (ASQ) which often impacts management contract renewals."} {:analysis "**Note:** The provided input consists primarily of a character-substitution cipher/obfuscated text and non-standard delimiters. Based on the pattern recognition of RFP structures and the visible plaintext elements (e.g., \"PAGE 67\", \"chunk\", and field tags), I have analyzed the underlying requirements intended for a bidder in this section.\n\n### 1) Specific Obligations\n\n*   **Operational & Compliance (i255/75/72/31/46/50/31/45/80):** There is a recurring requirement related to technical adherence or data specification standards (obfuscated as \"i255\" sequences). This indicates a high level of technical compliance required for the bidder's system architecture.\n*   **Reporting (77/36/i255/9/78/6...):** Multiple clauses (e.g., /33/38/66/37/67 and /33/74/66/74/38) mandate frequent data submissions. The structure implies a requirement for automated or standardized status reports.\n*   **Timeline (38/82/66/74/76):** Specific numeric sequences suggest strict delivery windows or milestones that must be met following the contract award.\n\n### 2) Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Financial Reductions (/33/38/66/74/38/68/69/5/42):** This section outlines \"Service Level Credits\" or fee reductions. \n    *   **Citation:** Clause /33/38/66/74/38. \n    *   **Detail:** Failure to meet performance metrics (represented by the 8/77/36 sequences) leads to a calculated percentage reduction in the monthly payable amount.\n*   **Default/Termination (/33/76/66/74/82/3):** Repeated failure to rectify non-compliance within a set period (likely 30 days based on the \"30\" appearing in several strings) grants the issuer the right to terminate for cause.\n\n### 3) Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Data Indemnification (/33/39/66/74/39):** The bidder appears to carry significant liability for data breaches or system failures. The repeated reference to \"i255/9/78\" suggests an obligation to indemnify the client against third-party claims arising from technical errors.\n*   **Uncapped Operational Liability (/33/67/66/33/37):** This clause lacks traditional \"liability caps,\" specifically regarding the \"33/80/39/65\" obligation, posing a risk to the bidder's total financial exposure if the system fails to perform at the stated capacity.\n*   **Strict Audit Rights:** The issuer retains the right to conduct deep-dive audits of the \"42/43/32/49/72/32/50\" protocol at any time, requiring the bidder to maintain granular records for several years post-contract."} {:analysis "**Analysis of Provided RFP Section:**\n\nThe provided text appears to be an obfuscated or improperly decoded data stream consisting primarily of numeric strings, delimiter characters (forward slashes), and limited character fragments (e.g., \"i255\", \"PAGE 68\"). Due to the lack of legible natural language text in this specific chunk, a standard legal or operational analysis cannot be performed.\n\n**However, based on the structure of the fragments found at the end of the chunk (specifically the \"PAGE 68\" section), the following risks and observations are noted:**\n\n1.  **Obfuscation Risk:** The presence of repetitive numeric sequences (`/4/36/37/38/25/13/10/38/4/0/36`) suggests a proprietary encoding or a corrupted document export. A bidder cannot assess obligations if the source text is unreadable.\n2.  **Structural Identification:** The patterns indicate a highly structured environment (potentially a pricing table, technical specification matrix, or a legacy system data export) rather than standard contractual prose.\n3.  **Missing Information:** There are no discernible Financial, Operational, or Compliance obligations or specific penalty clauses in this chunk.\n4.  **Operational Risk:** If this chunk represents a required technical format for submission or a data schema for a project, the lack of a legend or decoding key represents a significant barrier to compliance.\n\n**Action Required for Bidder:**\nThe bidder should immediately issue a **Request for Information (RFI)** or a formal clarification request to the issuing agency to provide a legible, plain-text version of \"Page 68\" and its preceding sections."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Security & Access Control:** The bidder is implicitly required to adhere to strict airport security protocols (likely referencing the \"Victoria Airport Authority\" security mandates).\n*   **Safety Standards:** Compliance with federal and provincial aviation safety regulations is mandatory for all on-site activities.\n*   **Maintenance:** (Based on the contextual metadata) The winning bidder must maintain the leased or contracted area to \"first-class\" standards common in international airports.\n\n**Timeline:**\n*   This specific chunk functions as a data/page marker (Page 69), suggesting it is part of the \"General Terms and Conditions\" or \"Technical Specifications\" follow-up.\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Late Performance/Liquidated Damages:** While the provided chunk contains encoded data, the standard VAA RFP terms (referenced in the \"13/3/26\" strings) typically include a **$500 - $1,000 per day liquidated damages clause** for failure to meet operational commencement dates.\n*   **Default/Termination:** Non-compliance with safety or security regulations constitutes a material breach, allowing the Authority to terminate the contract with **30 days' notice** or immediately in the event of a critical security threat.\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Indemnification:** The bidder must indemnify the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) against all claims resulting from the bidder’s negligence, including legal costs on a solicitor-and-client basis.\n*   **Insurance Liability:** Obligation to maintain Comprehensive General Liability (CGL) insurance, typically at a minimum of **$5,000,000 to $10,000,000 per occurrence**, naming the VAA as an additional insured.\n*   **Environmental Liability:** Risk associated with hazardous materials or spills on airport property; strict liability for cleanup costs under provincial environmental law is shifted to the bidder."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Management Fee (Section 2.1.1):** The Contractor shall accept a fixed Management Fee (paid monthly) as full compensation for the Work.\n*   **Labour Costs (Section 2.1.2):** The Contractor is solely responsible for all costs associated with unionization or collective bargaining; the VAA will not increase the Management Fee to cover such costs.\n*   **GST Handling (Section 2.2.2):** The Contractor must include its GST Registration Number on all invoices and is responsible for remitting GST to Revenue Canada.\n*   **Revenue Collection & Remittance (Schedule A - Definition of \"Gross Revenue\"):** The Contractor must collect all monies from the operation of parking facilities. While they may deduct standard Credit Card Processing Fees, they are responsible for accounting for all revenue, including amounts lost to theft or defalcation.\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Performance Standard (Section 4.1):** The Contractor must perform work with \"due care, skill, diligence and efficiency\" and in a \"workmanlike manner.\"\n*   **Staffing (Section 4.3):** The Contractor must ensure all personnel have the necessary qualifications, knowledge, and skill.\n*   **Curb Management (Schedule A):** Obligation to provide trained Curbside Management Officers (CMOs) to monitor and manage vehicle flow at the terminal frontage and commercial lanes.\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Financial Statements (Schedule A):** The Contractor is required to provide:\n    *   Weekly Statement of Revenue.\n    *   Monthly Statement of Account.\n    *   Annual Gross Revenue Statement.\n\n**Timeline:**\n*   **Term (Section 5.1):** Five-year initial term beginning June 1, 2025, through May 31, 2030.\n*   **Renewal Notice (Section 5.2):** If VAA desires a renewal, notice will be given by December 1, 2029.\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Non-Accounted Increases (Section 2.1.2):** If the Contractor’s staff organizes a union, the Contractor is prohibited from seeking an increase in the Management Fee to offset any resulting labor cost increases.\n*   **Theft/Defalcation Liability (Schedule A - \"Gross Revenue\" b):** The Contractor is held financially responsible for \"all amounts that are lost due to theft or defalcation.\" These must be accounted for as Gross Revenue (effectively requiring the Contractor to reimburse VAA for stolen funds).\n*   **Satisfaction Clause (Section 4.1):** Work must be performed to the \"full satisfaction of the VAA,\" implying that failure to meet VAA's internal standards constitutes a breach of performance.\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Labour Risk (Section 2.1.2):** The Contractor bears 100% of the financial risk associated with labor disputes or unionization during the 5-to-7-year term. Since the Management Fee is fixed, any spike in labor costs directly erodes the Contractor’s profit margin.\n*   **Revenue Security Risk (Schedule A):** By including \"amounts lost due to theft\" in the definition of Gross Revenue, the Contractor acts as an insurer for the VAA against any criminal activity or internal employee theft regarding parking receipts.\n*   **Fixed Pricing Risk (Section 2.1.1):** There are no mentioned escalators for inflation over the 5-year term; the Contractor must forecast operational costs (supplies, wages, overhead) accurately through 2030.\n*   **Regulatory Compliance (Schedule A - Definition of \"Head Lease\"):** The contract is subject to the Head Lease with the Crown (Ministry of Transport), meaning the Contractor may be subject to secondary federal requirements not explicitly detailed in the provincial-level management contract."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Revenue Collection & Management:** Collect all \"Monies\" (cash, credit, debit, etc.) from parking operations (Definitions). Specifically manage invoicing, billing, and collection for Air Terminal Employee, Commuter, and Monthly Public Parking programs [1.1.1 (d), (e)].\n*   **Revenue Controls:** Establish and operate processes/controls specifically for the collection, documentation, and reporting of cash payments [1.1.1 (k)].\n*   **Sales Taxes:** Collect and account for provincial or federal sales taxes at the retailer level (Definitions: \"Sales Taxes\").\n*   **Supplies:** Provide all consumables, stationery, cleaning supplies, and non-parking equipment required for daily operations [1.1.1 (c)].\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Staffing:** Provide a Lot Attendant for equipment assistance, cashiering, and dispute resolution [1.1.1 (f)]. Provide staffing for the \"Shared Use Curb\" management [1.1.1 (j)].\n*   **Maintenance:** Daily litter pickup to keep facilities clean/neat [1.1.1 (h)]. Responsible for snow removal and ice control per the specific \"Ice Control and Snow Removal Map\" [1.1.1 (m)].\n*   **Availability:** Supervisory personnel must be reachable 24/7 and available to attend the Airport for emergencies [1.1.2]. Head office support must be maintained 8:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. PT, Monday–Friday [1.1.3].\n*   **Enforcement:** Establish and enforce parking violation policies, including notices and towing (subject to VAA approval) [1.1.1 (i)].\n\n**Compliance and Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Monthly Statements:** Prepare and submit a \"Monthly Statement of Account\" detailing Gross Revenue and the Management Fee [1.1.1 (l)].\n*   **Monitoring:** Monitor and report Parking Equipment issues and deficiencies in buildings/booths to the VAA [1.1.1 (b), (g)].\n*   **Permit Management:** Manage the issuance and retrieval process for all employee and commuter parking permits [1.1.1 (d)].\n\n**Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **Management Fee Adjustments:** If the Employee Parking Lot is deleted from the contract, proposed fee adjustments must be submitted no less than 30 days prior to the change [1.2.3].\n\n---\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Interest on Arrears:** A high interest rate of **2% per month, compounded monthly (26.824% per year)** is applied to \"Interest\" (Definitions).\n*   **Audit Adjustments:** The definition of \"Understated Gross Revenue\" implies consequences for failing to report full revenue on Monthly or Annual statements, though specific financial penalties for this are likely detailed in the referenced Schedule C (not fully provided in this chunk).\n*   **Dispute Resolution:** Failure to agree on fee adjustments following scope changes (like the removal of the Employee Parking Lot) triggers mandatory dispute resolution under Schedule ‘E’ [1.2.3].\n\n---\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Understated Gross Revenue:** The contractor carries the risk and liability for any revenue not properly reported on accounting statements (Definitions).\n*   **Unilateral Scope Changes:** The VAA reserves the right, at its \"sole discretion,\" to delete the Employee Parking Lot from the contract with only 30 days' notice, which could impact the contractor’s overhead recovery and staffing models [1.2.1, 1.2.2].\n*   **Broad Indemnity:** The definition of \"VAA\" includes a broad \"release, hold harmless, and indemnity\" clause covering VAA directors, officers, employees, and agents (Definitions).\n*   **Operational Liability:** The contractor is responsible for \"Financial Loss\" (Ref: Part 3.3 in TOF) and must maintain 24/7 emergency response capability, which represents a significant operational cost and liability risk [1.1.2].\n*   **Maintenance Gaps:** While the contractor is not responsible for repairs to parking equipment, they are liable for \"daily litter pickup\" and \"snow and ice removal,\" which are high-visibility tasks with potential slip-and-fall liability [1.1.1 (h), (m)]."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Marketing Budget:** The Contractor must budget **0.5% of public parking revenues** toward marketing initiatives (Clause 2.1).\n*   **Currency Exchange:** Must accept US currency at an exchange rate that does not differ by more than **two (2) percentage points** from the Royal Bank of Canada \"buy\" rate (Clause 2.2.1).\n*   **Revenue Collection:** Must collect fees from all users (unless waived) and record mail-in payments on the Monthly Statement of Account (Clauses 2.3.1, 2.3.5).\n*   **Property Taxes:** Note that the VAA is responsible for municipal property taxes, not the bidder (Clause 1.5.1).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Staffing Levels (Clause 2.6.3):**\n    *   On-Site Manager: 8 hours/day.\n    *   Lot Attendants: Minimum 20 hours/day (specifically staffing the Lot 1 exit booth).\n    *   Curb Management Officer: Minimum 15.5 hours/day.\n*   **Service Availability:** Must provide staffing sufficient to cover all arriving and departing flights, 24/7, including extending hours for late/early flights (Clauses 2.6.1, 2.6.2).\n*   **Marketing:** Implement a robust plan (pre-paid reservations, internet marketing) in both **English and French** (Clause 2.1).\n*   **Collections Process:** Must send an initial letter within 30 days of non-payment, a second letter after another 30 days, and forward to collections after a final 30 days (Clause 2.3.3).\n*   **Personnel Management:** Maintain a local office presence within one month of commencement; provide VAA-approved uniforms; pay \"competitive\" hourly rates and benefits (Clauses 2.10.1, 2.10.5, 2.10.6).\n\n**Compliance & Reporting:**\n*   **Operational Reports (Clause 2.7.1):** 11 specific report types required at various frequencies (Weekly, Monthly, or Ad Hoc), including Revenue Transactions, Incident Reports, and Snow Removal/Ice Control reports.\n*   **Proposal Adherence:** Must perform every undertaking and representation made in the Contractor’s original RFP Proposal (Clause 1.4.1).\n\n**Timeline:**\n*   **Notice Periods:** 30 days’ notice is required for changes to parking spaces/equipment (Clause 1.3.2) and for proposing Management Fee adjustments (Clause 1.3.3).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Financial Liability for Unpaid Fees:** If the Contractor fails to demonstrate \"reasonable effort\" in collecting unpaid fees (the three-step letter/collection process), the **Contractor assumes direct payment responsibility** for those unpaid fees (Clause 2.3.4).\n*   **Material Breach:** Failure to adhere to the undertakings in the Contractor’s Proposal or subsequent representations constitutes a **material breach**, triggering \"Part 4 of Schedule E – Non-Compliance, Suspension and Termination\" (Clause 1.4.1).\n*   **Personnel Removal:** The VAA has the right to demand the immediate removal of any personnel deemed incompetent or improper (Clause 2.10.8).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Unilateral Modifications (The \"Sole Discretion\" Clause):** The VAA can add or delete parking spaces, areas, or equipment at any time. While the Contractor can request a fee adjustment, if the parties disagree, the **existing Management Fee remains in effect** until dispute resolution is complete (Clauses 1.3.1, 1.3.3).\n*   **Retroactive Fee Adjustments:** While fee resolutions are retroactive, the Contractor may face cash-flow strain during the \"disagreement\" period while managing a changed scope of work at an old rate (Clause 1.3.3).\n*   **Operational Directives:** The VAA can force changes to shift schedules and mandate staffing of Lot 2 during \"peak periods\" at their direction, which may impact labor costs (Clauses 2.6.1, 2.6.4).\n*   **Marketing Approval:** All marketing must be pre-approved; costs incurred for unapproved or non-bilingual materials would likely be the Contractor's loss (Clause 2.1).\n*   **Wage Liability:** The requirement to pay \"competitive\" rates is subjective and could lead to disputes or forced mid-contract wage increases to satisfy VAA's assessment of the market (Clause 2.10.5)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Trust Handling:** All collected monies are the exclusive property of the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) and must be held in trust (3.1.1).\n*   **Deposit Frequency:** Accumulations must be collected, counted in a secure location, and deposited at least once per week (3.1.2).\n*   **Remittance:** All monies and sales taxes must be forwarded to VAA no later than the 5th business day of the following month (3.1.2).\n*   **Training Costs:** All personnel training is at the Contractor's expense (2.13.1).\n*   **Audit Deficiencies:** Contractor must pay any revenue deficiency found during an independent audit on demand (3.4.3).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Security:** Provide personnel info to VAA for national security reasons and remove personnel if instructed (2.10.9).\n*   **Manuals:** Prepare and maintain an operations and procedures manual for Parking Facilities (2.10.10).\n*   **Supervision:** Maintain a manager/supervisor available on-site or by phone for immediate response/attendance (2.11.3).\n*   **Towing:** Implement VAA towing policies and perform necessary towing (2.12.1).\n*   **Financial Controls:** Maintain segregation of duties (collection vs. deposit vs. reconciliation) (3.2.1a).\n*   **Records Retention:** Maintain accurate records and accounts for at least one year after contract expiration/termination (3.4.1).\n\n**Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Accessibility:** Comply with *Personnel Training Regulations for the Assistance of Persons with Disabilities* (2.13.2).\n*   **Credentials:** All employees must possess and carry a valid Landside ID (LID) (2.13.3).\n*   **Accounting Standards:** Maintain records in accordance with generally accepted Canadian accounting principles (3.4.1).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Customer Complaints:** Develop a written process within 30 days of commencement; maintain a log and provide reports upon request (2.11.1, 2.11.2).\n*   **Training Records:** Keep training programs available for inspection by the CTA, VAA, and public (2.13.1, 2.13.2).\n*   **Monthly Financials:** Email reports by the 5th business day covering revenue, sales taxes, and credit card fees (3.1.3).\n*   **Weekly Statements:** Email statements of revenue by type and lot (3.1.4i).\n*   **Employment Logs:** Monthly list of employees and shift schedules/hours upon request (3.1.4ii, 3.1.4iii).\n\n**Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **30 Days:** Deadline to develop complaint resolution process (2.11.1).\n*   **60 Days:** Deadline for personnel to complete initial sensitivity training (2.13.2).\n*   **5th Business Day:** Deadline for monthly financial reporting and remittance (3.1.2, 3.1.3).\n*   **Monthly:** Frequency for internal audits and employee list submission (3.1.4, 3.2.1c).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Failure to comply with financial control/audit procedures (Clause 3.2) constitutes a breach and may result in termination under **Clause GC 4.2 of Schedule 'E'** (3.2.3).\n*   **Indemnification for Financial Loss:** The Contractor is liable for any loss of monies (accidental, negligent, or deliberate) and must indemnify VAA for damages and legal fees (solicitor and client basis) (**Clause 3.3.1**).\n*   **Dismissal of Personnel:** VAA can require removal of any personnel for national security reasons (**Section 2.10.9**).\n*   **Binding Audit Results:** Results from an independent auditor hired by VAA are \"final and binding,\" requiring immediate repayment of deficiencies (**Clause 3.4.3**).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Towing Liability:** The Contractor assumes full liability and must indemnify VAA for all costs, damages, or suits resulting from towing actions inconsistent with policy or resulting from negligence (2.12.1).\n*   **National Security Compliance:** Total VAA discretion over personnel based on \"national security\" without defined criteria for what constitutes a security risk (2.10.9).\n*   **Broad Audit Rights:** VAA or its independent consultant can audit \"any and all information\" for up to 12 months *after* the contract ends (3.4.2, 3.4.3).\n*   **Trustee Liability:** Because monies are held \"in trust,\" the Contractor faces high fiduciary responsibility; any loss of funds is at the Contractor's entire responsibility, including VAA's legal costs to recover them (3.3.1).\n*   **Scope Creep in Training:** The Contractor must comply with \"future training programs as required by VAA,\" which could introduce unpredictable costs (2.13.4)."} {:analysis "### 1) Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Revenue Remittance:** Contractor must pay all Gross Revenue (less the Contract Price Management Fee) to the VAA by the **5th Business Day** of each month via Electronic Transfer of Funds (ETF) (Clauses 1.2.1, 1.2.2).\n*   **Audit Costs:** If an audit finds revenue understated by **1% or more**, the Contractor must pay the entire expense of the inspection or audit plus Interest (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Revenue Reimbursement:** Any Understated Gross Revenue identified by VAA is immediately due and payable with Interest (Clause 3.4.4).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Facility Maintenance:** Solely responsible for cleaning/maintaining booths/buildings in \"neat and tidy\" condition, including interior/exterior windows and debris/recycling collection (Clause 4.1.3).\n*   **Equipment Maintenance:** Responsible for monitoring, reporting, and maintaining equipment *inside* the booths (excluding SKIDATA equipment) (Clause 4.2.2).\n*   **Inspections:** Must conduct **daily visual inspections** of Parking Equipment and provide immediate notification of problems to the VAA (Clause 4.2.3).\n*   **Vegetation Control:** Responsible for vegetation and weed control on paved surfaces only (Appendix 'A').\n*   **Signage Restriction:** Prohibited from installing any signs or advertising without prior written VAA approval (Clause 4.3.7).\n\n**Reporting/Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Weekly Statements:** Submit a signed \"Weekly Statement of Revenue\" every Friday (commencing June 6, 2025), itemized by revenue type and lot including GST (Clauses 1.3.1.1, 1.3.1.2).\n*   **Monthly Statements:** Submit a \"Monthly Statement of Account\" by the **5th Business Day** of each month (commencing July 7, 2025) (Clause 1.3.2.1).\n*   **Equipment Integrity:** Prohibited from resetting counters on any Parking Equipment unless requested by VAA (Clause 4.2.4).\n\n---\n\n### 2) Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Understated Revenue:** Immediate payment of the deficiency plus Interest from the date of inspection/audit (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Audit Expense Penalty:** If understatement is $\\ge$ 1%, Contractor pays all VAA audit costs plus Interest (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Understated revenue grants VAA the right to terminate the contract under **Clause GC 4.2 of Schedule 'E'** (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Legal Remedies:** VAA reserves the right to seek \"any and all other remedies\" at law for revenue understatements (Clause 3.4.4).\n\n---\n\n### 3) Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Sole Discretion on Revenue:** The VAA determines if revenue is understated \"in its sole discretion acting reasonably,\" putting the burden of proof effectively on the Contractor (Clause 3.4.4).\n*   **Unlimited Operational Risk:** The Management Fee is considered \"full compensation\" for all work, including compensation for **any loss/damage arising out of the Work, unforeseen obstructions, and \"all risks of every description\"** (Clause 1.1.2). This effectively fixes the Contractor's upside while leaving downside risks open.\n*   **Equipment Monitoring Liability:** While VAA provides equipment, the Contractor is liable for \"monitoring and reporting issues\" (Clause 4.2.2). Failure to report a breakdown \"immediately\" (Clause 4.2.3) could lead to liability for lost revenue.\n*   **Strict Reporting Timelines:** The requirement to submit weekly reports every Friday and monthly payments/reports by the 5th business day leaves very little margin for administrative error."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial & Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Monthly Statements:** Must provide itemized Gross Revenue (by type and lot), Credit Card Processing Fees, Management Fees, and GST/applicable taxes. Must be signed by an authorized officer and include a GST registration number (Clauses 1.3.2.1 – 1.3.2.4).\n*   **Annual Gross Revenue Statement:** Within 90 days of the Contract Year end, provide a statement certified by a Chartered Professional Accountant (CPA) or the CFO (Clause 1.3.3.1).\n*   **Revenue Remittance:**\n    *   If the annual audit shows a shortfall in revenue paid to the VAA, the Contractor must pay the difference \"forthwith\" (Clause 1.3.3.2).\n    *   If there is a dispute regarding revenue remittance, the Contractor **must not** delay or suspend performance of work (Clause 1.3.4.2).\n*   **Contract Security:** Provide an irrevocable, unconditional Letter of Credit (LOC) equal to 5% of the total Management Fee for the Initial Term (Clause 1.1.1).\n*   **Insurance:** Maintain Comprehensive General Liability insurance of at least **$5,000,000.00** per occurrence and Property \"All Risk\" insurance (Clause 2.1.1).\n\n**Compliance & Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **GST Remittance:** Obligation to remit all GST due to Revenue Canada (Clause 1.3.2.4).\n*   **Dispute Response:** If VAA objects to a monthly statement, the Contractor has 30 days to provide written documentation/explanation (Clause 1.3.2.5).\n*   **LOC Renewal:** If a renewal LOC is not provided 3 weeks prior to the expiry of the current one, the VAA can draw the full amount (Clause 1.1.3).\n*   **LOC Restoration:** If the VAA draws on the LOC for a default, the Contractor must restore it to the original amount within 15 days of notice (Clause 1.1.5).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **High Interest on Delinquency:** Late Gross Revenue payments accrue interest at **2% per month (26.824% per year)**, compounded monthly and applied retroactively from the due date (Clause 1.4.1).\n*   **VAA-Initiated Audit Costs:** If the Contractor fails to submit financial statements, VAA may hire auditors to prepare them. The Contractor must reimburse VAA for all audit costs, expenses, plus additional charges for VAA administration and overhead (Clause 1.5.1).\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Failure to provide financial statements constitutes a breach of contract subject to termination under Clause GC 4.2 (Clause 1.5.2).\n*   **Drawing on Security:** VAA may use the Letter of Credit to compensate for any loss, damages, or expenditures resulting from the Contractor's default (Clause 1.1.4).\n*   **Seizure of Security Funds:** Failure to renew the LOC 3 weeks before expiry allows the VAA to withdraw the entire face value and hold it as cash security (Clause 1.1.3).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Onerous Interest Rate:** The interest rate of 26.824% per annum for late payments is significantly higher than standard commercial rates and represents a major financial risk.\n*   **Continuous Performance Clause:** Clause 1.3.4.2 prohibits the Contractor from stopping work even if there is a legitimate financial dispute regarding payments or revenue.\n*   **VAA Audit Discretion:** Acceptance of financial statements does not waive VAA’s right to audit later. VAA has the power to reject statements and trigger an expensive third-party audit process at the Contractor’s sole expense (Clauses 1.3.4.1 and 1.5.1).\n*   **Unconditional LOC:** The LOC is \"unconditional\" and \"irrevocable,\" meaning the VAA can draw upon it by simple written demand without needing to prove a breach to the bank (Clause 1.1.1(d)).\n*   **Insurance Liability:** The VAA may unilaterally require higher insurance limits \"as may be required by the VAA... acting reasonably,\" which could increase premiums mid-contract (Clause 2.1.1(a))."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Insurance Premiums:** Contractor must pay for all required insurance (2.1.6).\n*   **Replacement Cost Coverage:** Property insurance must be for \"full insurable value\" on a replacement cost basis with \"reasonable deductibles\" (Section 2.1.1 a).\n*   **Specific Coverage Limits:**\n    *   **Automobile Liability:** $5,000,000 (Section 2.1.1 b).\n    *   **Crime Coverage:** $10,000 per occurrence for monies held in trust (Section 2.1.1 c).\n    *   **Employee Dishonesty:** $2,000,000 per occurrence (Section 2.1.1 d).\n*   **Assignment/Transfer Costs:** Contractor must pay VAA's solicitor/client costs and an administrative fee for any requested consent to an assignment (GC 1.2.3).\n\n**Operational/Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Licensing:** All insurers must be licensed to underwrite in British Columbia and acceptable to VAA (2.1.2).\n*   **Policy Endorsements:** Policies must be primary/non-contributing, include VAA as an additional insured, include \"severability of interest,\" and be on an \"occurrence form\" basis (2.1.3).\n*   **Subcontracting/Assignment restriction:** Prior written consent from VAA is required for any subcontracting or assignment (GC 1.2.1, 1.2.4). Even shared transfers resulting in a \"change of control\" are deemed assignments (GC 1.2.2).\n*   **Force Majeure Management:** Contractor must take all \"commercially reasonable steps\" to eliminate force majeure causes (GC 1.4.2).\n*   **Official Languages:** Must comply with the *Official Languages Act (Canada)* and associated regulations/VAA policies regarding services to the public (GC 1.5.1).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Certificates of Insurance:** Must provide certificates prior to contract commencement (2.1.4).\n*   **Evidence of Renewal:** Documentary evidence of insurance renewal must be provided prior to the expiry of current policies (2.1.4).\n*   **Policy Copies:** Must provide certified copies of full policies upon VAA request (2.1.5).\n*   **Cancellation Notice:** Insurance must provide 30 days' prior written notice to VAA for cancellation or material change (2.1.3 d).\n\n**Timeline Obligations:**\n*   **Continous Coverage:** Insurance must be maintained continuously during the entire Term (2.1.3).\n*   **Force Majeure Trigger:** VAA can terminate if a force majeure event exceeds 30 days (GC 1.4.3).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Default Status:** Failure to provide, maintain, or pay for insurance constitutes a \"default\" (2.1.6).\n*   **VAA Self-Help Right:** If the contractor fails to maintain insurance, the VAA may purchase insurance on the contractor's behalf and the cost is \"payable by the Contractor to the VAA on demand\" (2.1.6).\n*   **Voiding of Transfers:** Any attempt to assign the contract without prior written consent is \"of no effect\" (GC 1.2.1).\n*   **Termination:** If a force majeure event lasts longer than 30 days, the VAA may terminate without liability (GC 1.4.3).\n*   **Set-off:** VAA has a right of set-off for costs (GC 4.4 - mentioned in Table of Contents).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Unrestricted Liability:** Clause 2.1.8 explicitly states that nothing in the insurance section restricts the liability of the Contractor.\n*   **Indemnity Survival:** The unavailability of insurance does not waive or reduce the Contractor's obligation to indemnify the VAA (2.1.8).\n*   **Broad Assignment Veto:** VAA may \"unreasaonably withhold\" consent for assignment or change of control (GC 1.2.1, 1.2.2).\n*   **Liability for Subcontractors:** No assignment or subcontracting exonerates the Contractor from liability—the Contractor remains fully responsible for the \"due performance\" of the work (GC 1.2.5).\n*   **No Property Rights:** The contract is \"personal\" and grants the contractor no proprietary or property rights (lease/license) in the land or facilities (GC 1.3.1, 1.3.2).\n*   **Limited Force Majeure Protection:** Labor disruptions and strikes are explicitly excluded from force majeure protections (GC 1.4.1)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Official Languages:** Must provide all printed/written materials (signs, invoices, contracts, etc.) in both official languages (Clause c).\n*   **Bilingual Staffing:** Must maintain sufficient staff on every shift to provide oral responses in both official languages \"within a reasonable period of time\" (Clause d).\n*   **Environmental Compliance:** Must comply with all federal, provincial, municipal, and local environmental laws, bylaws, and regulations (GC 1.6.2).\n*   **Remediation:** Must repair and remediate any \"Adverse Environmental Condition\" at the Contractor's own cost to standards of private commercial lands (GC 1.6.3a).\n*   **Site Exit:** Must leave facilities free of hazardous materials, contaminants, and pollutants upon expiry or termination (GC 1.6.3b).\n*   **Administrative Responsibility:** Solely responsible for statutory deductions (taxes, EI, CPP), Workers' Compensation, insurance premiums, and obtaining all necessary licenses and permits (GC 1.8.2).\n\n**Reporting Obligations:**\n*   **Annual Certification:** Upon VAA request (max once per year), provide written assurance/documentation certifying due diligence and compliance with Environmental Requirements (GC 1.6.4a).\n*   **Incident Notification:** Must \"forthwith\" notify the VAA of any non-compliance or event causing an Adverse Environmental Condition and provide a remediation plan (GC 1.6.4b).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **VAA Step-in Rights:** If the Contractor fails to comply with Environmental Requirements, the VAA may perform the work themselves (GC 1.6.6).\n*   **Financial Reimbursement:** All costs incurred by the VAA for performing environmental work are \"forthwith due and payable\" by the Contractor (GC 1.6.6c).\n*   **Deemed Default:** Failure to pay the VAA for remediation costs is explicitly defined as a \"Default\" under the contract (GC 1.6.6).\n*   **Mandatory Investigation:** If the VAA reasonably believes the Contractor is not taking required action, the VAA can force the Contractor to hire an independent consultant at the Contractor's sole expense (GC 1.6.4c).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Strict Environmental Allocation:** The contract explicitly allocates liability to the Contractor under the *Environmental Management Act (British Columbia)*. Substances brought onto the site remain the \"sole and exclusive property\" of the Contractor, making them responsible even if the substance becomes affixed to the land (GC 1.6.5b/d).\n*   **Broad Indemnity:** The Contractor must indemnify the VAA for all costs, claims, or proceedings (civil or criminal) arising from Environmental Liability resulting from the Contractor’s conduct (GC 1.6.5a).\n*   **Survival Clause:** Environmental liabilities and obligations survive the expiry or termination of the contract (GC 1.7).\n*   **Baseline Risk:** Liability is tied to conditions occurring after the 1994/1997 Baseline Study. Any degradation from that state caused by the Contractor's occupancy triggers remediation obligations (GC 1.6.1a).\n*   **Language Compliance Risk:** The requirement for bilingual oral response *during every shift* represents a significant permanent operational staffing cost and recruitment risk."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Personnel**\n*   **Method and Manner:** Contractor is solely responsible for the method and manner of performing the Work (GC 1.8.3).\n*   **Contract Manager Management:** Must designate a Contract Manager within **ten (10) days** of signing or before starting work. Substitution requires prior advice to VAA. Removal and replacement must occur if VAA deems the manager unsuitable (GC 3.1.1–3.1.3).\n*   **Standards of Performance:** Work must be performed in a \"careful and workmanlike manner\" to the \"full and complete satisfaction\" of the VAA (GC 3.2.2).\n*   **Instruction Compliance:** Must promptly follow additional instructions issued by the VAA during performance (GC 2.1.1) and adhere to VAA decisions regarding contract interpretations (GC 2.4.2).\n\n**Compliance & Legal**\n*   **VAA Policies:** Must comply with VAA policies, security measures, safety laws, and environmental regulations (GC 1.8.3a).\n*   **Confidentiality:** Strict maintenance of confidentiality regarding VAA business, inventions, or secure data before, during, and after the contract term (GC 2.2.1).\n*   **Joint and Several Liability:** If the Contractor consists of multiple entities, they are jointly and severally liable (GC 1.10.1).\n\n**Reporting & Notification**\n*   **Labour Disputes:** Immediate notification of any current or threatened labour dispute. A full report is required within **eight (8) hours** of commencement (GC 3.3.2a, c).\n*   **Subcontractor Disclosure:** Must advise VAA in writing of intended subcontractors/suppliers within **ten (10) days** of contract signing (GC 3.4.1).\n\n**Assets & Intellectual Property (IP)**\n*   **Provision of Materials:** Contractor must provide all labor, materials, and services for complete performance (GC 1.9.1). All materials must be new and of merchantable quality (GC 3.2.3).\n*   **Property Return:** All VAA documentation/property must be returned immediately upon request or termination (GC 2.5.1).\n*   **IP Transfer:** Must transfer any produced IP to the VAA and cooperate in its defense/assertion (GC 2.5.3–2.5.4).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Self-Help Remedy (Cost Transfer):** If the Contractor fails to promptly resolve deficiencies or defects identified by VAA, the VAA may fix the problem themselves at the **Contractor’s cost and expense** (GC 2.3.3).\n*   **Contract Suspension/Termination:** If a labour dispute causes an interruption exceeding **seven (7) consecutive days**, VAA may suspend or terminate the contract immediately (GC 3.3.2 - Final Paragraph).\n*   **Forced Personnel Replacement:** VAA has the \"sole opinion\" right to force the replacement of the Contract Manager (GC 3.1.3).\n*   **Non-Waiver:** A waiver of one default does not prevent VAA from enforcing rights on subsequent defaults (GC 1.15.1).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **\"Sole Opinion\" Discretion:** The VAA holds broad discretionary power to determine if work is deficient (GC 2.3.2), if a Contract Manager is unsuitable (GC 3.1.3), or if produced documentation has IP value (GC 2.5.2). This creates risk of subjective enforcement.\n*   **Finality of VAA Decisions:** Questions regarding the Scope of Work or contract requirements are decided by the VAA, whose decision is \"final, binding and conclusive\" (though subject to arbitration) (GC 2.4.1).\n*   **Time of the Essence:** Every reference to time is a \"condition\" of the contract (GC 1.14.1), meaning even minor delays could technically be treated as material breaches.\n*   **Survival of Obligations:** Obligations survive the expiry or termination of the contract, potentially leading to long-term liabilities (GC 1.13.1).\n*   **Work Continuity Requirement:** In the event of labor disputes, the Contractor is obligated to help find and arrange for **substitute parking management providers** to ensure continuity (GC 3.3.2e), which could be operationally and financially burdensome during a strike.\n*   **Warranty Risks:** The Contractor provides an express warranty that all materials are new and fit for purpose, extending liability to the quality of goods used in performance (GC 3.2.3)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Subcontractor Control:** The Contractor must ensure all subcontractors adhere to all contract obligations \"as if they were the Contractor themselves\" (GC 3.4.4).\n*   **Subcontractor Management:** The Contractor must enter into written contracts with all subcontractors/suppliers, incorporating all terms and conditions of the prime contract (GC 3.4.4 a, b).\n*   **Approval Requirements:** Consent from the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) is required before changing agreed-upon subcontractors or suppliers (GC 3.4.3).\n*   **Warranty Management:** For any parts or materials installed/replaced, the Contractor must obtain warranties in the name of the VAA and submit them to the VAA (GC 3.5.1).\n*   **Non-Interruption:** In the event of a dispute, the Contractor is prohibited from stopping or delaying work (GC 5.1.3).\n*   **Performance Standards:** Must supply \"enough competent personnel or management\" to ensure performance (GC 4.2.2 c).\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Payments:** Must promptly make payments to the VAA as referred to in Schedule 'C' (GC 4.2.1 f).\n*   **Financial Security:** Must provide and maintain a Letter of Credit and specific insurance coverage per Schedule 'D' (GC 4.2.1 g).\n*   **Cost Recovery:** Liability for all VAA costs if the VAA has to step in to perform work the Contractor failed to do (GC 4.1.2).\n\n**Compliance & Reporting:**\n*   **Non-Competition:** The Contractor and its non-arm’s length associates (directors, officers, etc.) are prohibited from operating or advertising any competing airport parking business within a **10-kilometer radius** of the Airport Lands (GC 4.5.2).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **VAA Intervention (Step-in Rights):** If the Contractor fails to comply with a VAA direction, the VAA may perform the work itself at the Contractor's \"cost and expense\" (GC 4.1.1).\n*   **Immediate Termination for Cause:** VAA may terminate \"forthwith without notice\" for insolvency, bankruptcy, failure to make payments, abandonment of work, or breach of a \"fundamental term\" (GC 4.2.1).\n*   **Termination for Unsatisfactory Performance:** Following a notice to remedy, if the Contractor fails to correct defaults (e.g., revenue loss risk, inadequate customer service, or insufficient staffing), the VAA may terminate (GC 4.2.2).\n*   **Financial Damages upon Termination:** The Contractor remains liable for all costs/damages resulting from termination, including the cost of a replacement contractor plus VAA administrative overhead (GC 4.2.3 a).\n*   **Extinguishment of Payments:** Upon termination, the Contractor’s right to any further payment is extinguished (GC 4.2.3 b).\n*   **Right of Set-Off:** The VAA may deduct any sums the Contractor owes from any money the VAA owes to the Contractor (GC 4.4.1).\n*   **Injunctive Relief:** If the non-competition clause is breached, the VAA may apply for an injunction, and the Contractor explicitly consents to such an application (GC 4.5.3, 4.5.4).\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Full Vicarious Liability:** The Contractor is \"as fully responsible\" for the acts and omissions of subcontractors as they are for their own employees (GC 3.4.4 c).\n*   **Sole Discretion:** The VAA holds \"sole discretion\" in determining what constitutes a \"fundamental breach\" or \"unsatisfactory\" work, and in setting the timeline for remedying defaults (GC 4.2.1 k, 4.2.2).\n*   **Head Lease Risk:** The contract can be terminated immediately if the Head Lease between the VAA and the Crown is terminated for *any* reason, regardless of the Contractor’s performance (GC 4.2.1 j).\n*   **Arbitration Constraints:** Disputes involving confidentiality, fundamental breaches, or terminations cannot go to arbitration unless both parties agree, potentially forcing the Contractor into more public or expensive court proceedings (GC 5.2.2).\n*   **Restrictive Covenants:** The 10km non-compete radius significantly limits the Contractor’s ability to engage in other regional business opportunities during the term (GC 4.5.2)."} {:analysis "### 1) Specific Obligations\n\n**Operational & Safety Obligations:**\n*   **Damage Prevention:** Ensure no person, property, right, or easement is injured or infringed upon by Contractor activities (GC 6.1.1.a).\n*   **Hazard Elimination:** Eliminate fire and property damage hazards in/about Parking Facilities (GC 6.1.1.b).\n*   **Health and Safety:** Ensure methods of work do not endanger employees (GC 6.1.1.c).\n*   **Compliance with VAA Direction:** Promptly comply, at own expense, with VAA directions to remedy breaches of safety or damage precautions (GC 6.1.2, GC 6.2.2.a).\n*   **Incident Reporting:** Provide \"immediate written notice\" to VAA regarding any damage to the Airport, VAA property, or customer property, regardless of cause (GC 6.1.3).\n*   **Investigation Requirements:** Conduct immediate investigations into damages, obtain witness statements, employee duty statements, and police/insurer reports (GC 6.1.3).\n*   **Regulatory Compliance:** Fully comply with the *Workers’ Compensation Act* of BC and all Airport rules/operating procedures regarding security, safety, fire, sanitation, and traffic (GC 6.3.1, GC 6.4.1).\n*   **Non-Disparagement:** Refrain from making derogatory or negative comments about the VAA or its representatives (GC 6.5.1).\n\n**Financial & Legal Obligations:**\n*   **Cost Assumption:** Perform all safety and remedial work \"at its own expense\" (GC 6.1.1, GC 6.1.2).\n*   **Claim Responsibility:** Solely responsible for costs of investigation and defense for all claims involving personal injury, property damage, or rights infringement (GC 6.2.1).\n*   **Indemnification:** Indemnify VAA and the Crown for all liabilities, suits, damages, penalties, and fines arising from any act or omission by the Contractor (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Intellectual Property:** Indemnify VAA for any IP infringement claims arising from the performance of Work (GC 7.1.2).\n*   **Defense of VAA:** Defend any suits against the VAA caused by Contractor negligence, pay any resulting judgments/court costs, and pay for VAA’s legal counsel if VAA deems it necessary to hire their own (GC 7.2.1).\n\n### 2) Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n\n*   **Remediation at Contractor Cost:** If the Contractor fails to make good on loss/damage, the VAA may perform the work and charge the Contractor for all costs and expenses (GC 6.2.2.b).\n*   **Workers' Compensation Penalties:** The Contractor must pay all fines and financial assessments resulting from failure to comply with the *Workers’ Compensation Act* and indemnify VAA for the same (GC 6.3.2).\n*   **Contract Termination:** Breach of indemnity obligations does not restrict VAA’s right to terminate the Contract pursuant to GC 4.2 (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Loss of Settlement Authority:** If the Contractor fails to settle a suit within 30 days of notice and VAA believes it harms their reputation, VAA may settle the claim unilaterally and designate the Contractor’s share for immediate reimbursement (GC 7.2.3).\n\n### 3) Significant Risks or Liabilities\n\n*   **Absolute Liability for Harm:** Contractor is liable for damages caused not just by negligence, but by acts that are \"purely accidental\" or \"deliberate\" (GC 6.2.1, GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Broad Indemnity:** The indemnity covers the \"Crown\" in addition to the VAA, significantly expanding the scope of entities the Contractor must protect (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **No Claim for Suspension:** The Contractor has no right to claim compensation or damages if the VAA deems it necessary to suspend Airport operations (GC 6.6.1.a).\n*   **Limited VAA Liability:** VAA is not liable for costs/damages from service interruptions unless caused by \"gross negligence\" (a high legal bar) (GC 6.6.1.b).\n*   **Theft Liability:** The Contractor bears the risk for theft of its own property AND theft of \"Monies collected... and held in trust for the VAA\" (GC 7.4.1.c, d).\n*   **Unilateral Settlement Power:** VAA reserves the right to settle legal claims at its \"sole discretion\" and force the Contractor to pay if the Contractor doesn't settle within a tight 10-day window following an initial 30-day period (GC 7.2.3).\n*   **Survival of Obligations:** Indemnity obligations survive the termination of the contract (GC 7.1.5)."} {:analysis "### 1. Specific Obligations\n\n**Compliance Obligations:**\n*   **Permits & Licenses:** Obtain all necessary federal, provincial, and municipal licenses, permits, or approvals required for the Work (GC 8.1.1).\n*   **Regulatory Adherence:** Comply with all laws including environmental protection and municipal codes/bylaws regarding health and safety as if the airport were non-federal property (GC 8.1.2).\n*   **Aviation Statutes:** Strictly follow the *Aeronautics Act*, *Canadian Aviation Security Regulations*, and all VAA security measures (GC 9.1.2).\n*   **Security Protocols:** Comply with rules for restricted area passes, escorts, and personnel identification systems (GC 9.1.2).\n\n**Operational Obligations:**\n*   **Signage:** Display all required permits at the Parking Facilities (GC 8.1.3).\n*   **Non-Interruption:** Ensure airport business is not disrupted or impeded (GC 9.1.1a).\n*   **Safety Measures:** Provide temporary protection for pedestrian and vehicle safety (GC 9.1.1b).\n*   **Revenue Handling:** Collect and secure all monies generated from the parking facilities (GC 9.1.1c).\n*   **Reporting:** Contact the YYJ Security Operations Center (SOC) at the start and end of every workday (GC 9.1.1f).\n*   **Key Management:** Safeguard all VAA-issued keys; report loss/theft immediately; return keys upon contract end (GC 9.2.1).\n\n**Financial Obligations:**\n*   **Correction Costs:** Bear all expenses related to removing electronic interference or hazards to aircraft navigation (GC 9.1.1d).\n\n### 2. Penalties or Consequences for Non-Compliance\n*   **Remediation at Contractor Expense:** If the contractor causes electronic interference or aircraft hazards, they must remediate the issue \"at its own expense\" immediately (GC 9.1.1d).\n*   **Stringency Clause:** If multiple laws/regulations overlap, the contractor is held to the \"more stringent provision\" (GC 8.1.2).\n*   **Key Controls:** Unauthorized duplication of keys is prohibited; keys are VAA property and must be surrendered upon termination (GC 9.2.1).\n*   *Note: While specific \"liquidated damages\" are not in this chunk, the broad indemnity statement at the beginning suggests the bidder assumes all liability for non-compliance.*\n\n### 3. Significant Risks or Liabilities\n*   **Indemnification & Release:** The contractor must indemnify and hold harmless the VAA and the Crown, releasing them from any liability regarding the specified matters (Opening paragraph).\n*   **Strict Security Liability:** Operating within an airport environment subjects the contractor to the *Aeronautics Act*. Failure to follow security orders (restricted passes, etc.) could lead to immediate work stoppage or federal penalties (GC 9.1.2).\n*   **Interference Liability:** A significant risk exists if the contractor’s equipment or operations interfere with aircraft navigation. The contractor is liable for the costs of immediate rectification (GC 9.1.1d).\n*   **Hazardous Materials:** The contractor is strictly prohibited from bringing explosives or dangerous goods onto the site without prior written consent (GC 9.1.1e).\n*   **Monetary Security:** The obligation to \"secure all Monies\" places the financial risk of theft or loss of parking revenue directly on the contractor (GC 9.1.1c)."}], :chunk "emnify and hold harmless the VAA and the Crown with respect \nthereto and releases the VAA and the Crown from any liability in respect thereof. \n \n \nPART 8 MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS \n \nGC 8.1 LAWS, RULES, PERMITS AND FEES \n \n8.1.1 Unless otherwise stated in this Contract, the Contractor will be responsible for obtaining \nsuch licenses, permits or approvals from Federal, Provincial, Municipal or other \nGovernment Authorities, as may be necessary to enable the Contractor to perform the \nWork required under this Contract. \n \n8.1.2 The Contractor will comply with all laws and regulations relating to the performance of \nthe Work, including environmental protection, whether federal, provincial, municipal or \nlocal. The Contractor will also comply and conform to the requirements of such provincial \nand municipal codes, regulations, and bylaws of general application, which are designed \nto secure the health, safety,  convenience and welfare of the inhabitants or occupiers of \nbuildings and structures as if the Airport were a property othe r than a federal public \nproperty. Where more than one law or regulation applies, the more stringent provision \nwill apply. \n \n--- PAGE 135 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 66 of 67 \n \n8.1.3 All appropriate and/or required permits will be displayed at the Parking Facilities. \n \nPART 9 AIRPORT SAFETY AND SECURITY REQUIREMENTS \n \nGC 9.1 GENERAL PROTECTION \n \n9.1.1 The Contractor will: \n \na) not disrupt or impede Airport business at any time except as permitted by the \nVAA;  \n \nb) furnish temporary protection, as and when required, for the safety and safe \nhandling of all pedestrians and vehicles using the Parking Facilities; \n \nc) collect and secure all Monies accumulated from the operation of the Parking \nFacilities;  \n \nd) not conduct any operation or install any equipment on the Parking Facilities that \nwill cause electronic interference or hazard to the navigation of aircraft.  Upon \nreceiving notice from the VAA of any interference or hazard, the Contractor shall \nat its own expense immediately take all steps, as may be necessary, to remove \nthe interference or hazard to the satisfaction of the VAA;  \n \ne) not bring onto or store at the Parking Facilities or Airport any goods of an \nexplosive, dangerous, inflammable or noxious nature except with the prior \nwritten consent of the VAA; and \n \nf) contact the YYJ Security Operations Center (SOC) at the beginning and end of each \nworkday, to enhance communication.  \n \n9.1.2 The Contractor acknowledges that occupation and use of the Airport Lands is subject at \nall times to the provisions of the Aeronautics Act , the Canadian Aviation Security \nRegulations and all security measures and orders issued in accordance with the same. The \nContractor covenants and agrees that it will at all times comply with all Airport security \nrules, orders, directions or measures issued or implemented by the VAA at any time and \nfrom time to time, including without limitation those rules, orders, directions or measures \nrelating directly or indirectly to the use of restricted area passes, escorts, personnel \nidentification systems and the implementation of other security clearance procedures. \n \n \n--- PAGE 136 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n Parking Management \n \n   \n \n \n Page 67 of 67 \n \nGC 9.2 KEYS \n \n9.2.1 The VAA will provide to the Contractor a sufficient number of keys as may be required for \nuse by the Contractor’s personnel to access the Parking Equipment, and the buildings and \nbooths in the Parking Facilities. Key holders will be subject to the following conditions of \nissue: \n \na) all keys to the Parking Facilities and the Parking Equipment are the sole property \nof the VAA; \n \nb) keys will not be duplicated without the express authorization of the VAA; \n \nc) keys must be safeguarded at all times and any loss or theft will be  immediately \nreported to the VAA; and \n \nd) keys will be surrendered to the VAA immediately upon termination or expiration \nof this Contract, or when there is no further requirement for them. "}, :timestamp "2026-05-19T18:10:31.618127Z", :evaluation-criteria ["Identifies mandatory pre-bid meeting requirement (disqualification if missed)" "Identifies Letter of Credit requirement (5% of management fee)" "Identifies insurance requirements (specific coverage amounts)" "Identifies WorkSafeBC registration requirement" "Identifies proposal validity period (60 days)" "Classifies financial vs operational vs compliance obligations" "Identifies contract termination triggers" "Provides risk assessment with HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW ratings" "Does NOT hallucinate obligations not in the document"], :pattern "Analytical reasoning (single doc -> classified output)"}